{"title_page": "Antonio Brown", "text_new": "{{For|the former Bills and Redskins player|Antonio Brown (wide receiver, born 1978)}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Antonio Brown\n| image = File:Antonio Brown vs Redskins 2016.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt =\n| caption = Brown with the Steelers in 2016\n| current_team = Free agent\n| position = [[Wide receiver]]\n| number = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1988|7|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Miami, Florida]]\n| death_place =\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lbs = 185\n| high_school = [[Miami Norland Senior High School|Miami Norland]]<br>([[Miami Gardens, Florida]])\n| college = [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]]\n| draftyear = 2010\n| draftround = 6\n| draftpick = 195\n| pastteams =\n* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[Oakland Raiders]] ({{NFL Year|2019}})*\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|2019}})\n| pastteamsnote = yes\n|status=\n| highlights =\n* 7\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2012 Pro Bowl|2011]], [[2014 Pro Bowl|2013]]\u2013[[2019 Pro Bowl|2018]])\n* 4\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2014 All-Pro Team|2014]]\u2013[[2017 All-Pro Team|2017]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2013 All-Pro Team|2013]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of National Football League season receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards leader]] ([[2014 NFL season|2014]], [[2017 NFL season|2017]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of NFL annual receptions leaders|NFL receptions leader]] ([[2014 NFL season|2014]], [[2015 NFL season|2015]])\n* [[List of National Football League annual receiving touchdowns leaders|NFL receiving touchdowns leader]] ([[2018 NFL season|2018]])\n* [[National Football League 2010s All-Decade Team|NFL 2010s All-Decade Team]]\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2008 College Football All-America Team|2008]], [[2009 College Football All-America Team|2009]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] (2008, 2009)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Mid-American Conference football individual awards|MAC Special Teams Player of the Year]] (2008, 2009)\n* Second-team All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] (2007)\n* [[Mid-American Conference football individual awards#Freshman Player of the Year|MAC Freshman of the Year]] (2007)\n| statleague = NFL\n| statweek   = \n| statseason = \n| statlabel1 = Receptions\n| statvalue1 = 841\n| statlabel2 = Receiving yards\n| statvalue2 = 11,263\n| statlabel3 = Rushing yards\n| statvalue3 = 124\n| statlabel4 = Return yards\n| statvalue4 = 2,932\n| statlabel5 = Total touchdowns\n| statvalue5 = 80\n| nfl = BRO000001\n| pfr = BrowAn04\n}}\n\n'''Antonio Tavaris Brown Sr.''' (born July 10, 1988) is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] who is a free agent. Raised in [[Liberty City (Miami)|Liberty City]], [[Miami]], Brown attended [[Miami Norland High School]], where he competed in both football and track. He played [[college football]] at [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan University]], where he earned All-American honors in 2008 and 2009 as a punt returner. A sixth-round pick by the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in 2010, Brown has amassed more receptions than any other player since he entered the league.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24005878 |title=Antonio at 30: How Brown stacks up against Rice, what's next |last=Fowler |first=Jeremy |date=July 10, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring Brown's first season with the Steelers, the team advanced to [[Super Bowl XLV]] but lost to the [[2010 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]]. He finished his rookie season with 16 receptions for 167 yards in ten games. During his second NFL season, he became the first player in NFL history to have more than 1,000 yards receiving and returning in the same year. For his efforts, Brown was selected as a punt returner for the [[2012 Pro Bowl]]. In 2013, he became the only receiver in NFL history to record five receptions and at least 50 yards in every single game of an NFL season. Although his on-the-field productivity continued over the next several seasons, including leading the league in receptions and receiving yards in 2014, receptions in 2015, receiving yards in 2017, and receiving touchdowns in 2018, Brown's relationship with the Steelers soured, especially with quarterback [[Ben Roethlisberger]], and he eventually requested a trade.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/antonio-brown-goes-public-with-his-desire-to-leave-pittsburgh-time-to-move-on/ |title=Antonio Brown goes public with his desire to leave Pittsburgh: 'Time to move on' |last=Dubin |first=Jared |date=February 12, 2019 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Brown was traded to the [[Oakland Raiders]], who then made him the highest-paid receiver in the league. However, his time in Oakland was short-lived, and following several off-the-field incidents, including a confrontation with general manager [[Mike Mayock]], the team released Brown without him ever playing a regular-season game. Brown signed with the [[New England Patriots]] shortly thereafter but was cut after appearing in just one game. At the time, the NFL was investigating [[sexual assault]] allegations made against him.\n\n==Early life==\nBrown is the son of retired [[Arena Football League]] star [[Eddie Brown (arena football)|Eddie Brown]], who was named the best player in the league's history in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2297305 |title='Touchdown' Eddie Brown tops Arena top 20 list |date=January 19, 2006 |agency=Associated Press|website=ESPN |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> He played wide receiver for the [[Albany Firebirds]] and collegiate football for [[Louisiana Tech]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/pittsburgh-steelers/post/_/id/17599/touchdown-eddie-brown-amazed-at-son-antonios-brilliance-not-bitter-at-burfict |title='Touchdown' Eddie Brown amazed at son Antonio's brilliance |last=Fowler |first=Jeremy |date=January 25, 2016 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\n\n===Miami Norland High School===\nBrown attended [[Miami Norland High School]] in [[Miami]], [[Florida]], where he was a two-sport athlete in both [[high school football|football]] and [[track & field]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/high-school/prep-miami-dade/article194365214.html |title=South Florida's deep connection to the NFL playoffs runs through high school football |last=McPherson |first=Jordan |date=January 12, 2018 |access-date=February 25, 2018 |language=en |website=Miami Herald}}</ref> In [[high school football|football]], Brown played [[running back]], [[quarterback]], [[wide receiver]], and [[punt returner]] for the Vikings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Bolt/Steelers-Antonio-Brown-posts-video-of-his-High-School-highlights-47676907 |title=Steelers Antonio Brown posts video of his High School highlights |last=Deardo |first=Bryan |date=September 22, 2016 |website=247Sports |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> He was a two-time Class 6A all-state selection and was also named North Athlete of the Year at 2005 Miami-Dade Gridiron Classic. In track, Brown was a two-time state qualifier in the [[100 meters|100-meter dash]], and also ran the fourth leg on the Norland [[4 \u00d7 100 metres relay|4 \u00d7 100 m relay]] squad, helping them capture the state title at 41.50 seconds.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/antonio-brown-7871/ |title=Antonio Brown |website=Tracking Football |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103165342/https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/antonio-brown-7871/ |archive-date=November 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===North Carolina Tech Prep===\nComing out of high school, Brown applied to [[Florida State University]]. His admission was denied over academic concerns.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=http://archive.freep.com/article/20110202/SPORTS01/102020425/Pittsburgh-s-Antonio-Brown-Central-Michigan-walk-dreamed-days-like-this |title=Pittsburgh Steeler's Antonio Brown, Central Michigan walk-on, Dreamed of days like this |last=Birkett |first=Dave |website=Detroit Free Press |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613002928/http://archive.freep.com/article/20110202/SPORTS01/102020425/Pittsburgh-s-Antonio-Brown-Central-Michigan-walk-dreamed-days-like-this |archive-date=June 13, 2015 |access-date=June 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter attempting to attend [[Alcorn State University|Alcorn State]], he decided to enroll at North Carolina Tech Prep.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.steelers.com/team/players-roster/antonio-brown/ |title=Pittsburgh Steelers: Antonio Brown |website=Steelers.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227015547/https://www.steelers.com/team/players-roster/antonio-brown/ |archive-date=December 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/chippewas/index.ssf/2008/10/antonio_brown_does_almost_ever.html |title=Antonio Brown Does Almost Everything for Central Michigan |last=Bernreuter |first=Hugh |date=April 4, 2019 |website=MLive.com |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> Playing in just five games at quarterback, Brown passed for 1,247 yards and 11 touchdowns, while rushing for 451 yards and 13 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/steelers-antonio-brown-posts-video-of-his-high-school-highlights/ |title=Steelers Antonio Brown posts video of his High School highlights |last=DeArdo |first=Bryan |date=September 22, 2016 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref> Once he finished his lone season at North Carolina Tech Prep, he received a scholarship to play at [[Florida International University]], but he was expelled before the season for an altercation with security.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14179705/antonio-brown-ty-hilton-unlikely-bond?ex_cid=sportscenterFB&sf16048515=1 |title=After a decade apart, Antonio Brown and TY Hilton's unlikely bond |last=Kimes |first=Mina |date=November 24, 2015 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=November 21, 2015}}</ref> Brown then began reaching out to wide receivers coach [[Butch Jones]] at [[West Virginia University|West Virginia]], since he had been highly recruited by him. After learning that Jones had left West Virginia to become the head coach at [[Central Michigan University|Central Michigan]], Brown enrolled at the school and started his college football career as a walk-on freshman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/chippewas/index.ssf/2008/10/antonio_brown_does_almost_ever.html |title=Antonio Brown Does Everything for Central Michigan |last=Bernreuter |first=Hugh |date=October 23, 2008 |website=MLive.com |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nBrown attended and played college football for Central Michigan from 2007\u20132009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/antonio-brown-1.html |title=Antonio Brown College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Freshman season===\n{{see also|2007 Central Michigan Chippewas football team}}\nBrown began attending [[Central Michigan University|Central Michigan]] in [[2007 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|2007]] after wide receivers coach [[Zach Azzanni]] told him he could fly to Michigan and try out for the team as a [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] wide receiver.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/steelers/2016/01/31/Antonio-Brown-Dapper-Dan-Sportsman-of-the-Year-again-continues-to-work/stories/201601310288 |title=Antonio Brown, Dapper Dan Sportsman of the Year again, continues to work |last=Meyer |first=Craig |date=January 31, 2016 |website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Transitioning from the quarterback position in high school to wide receiver in college was not that difficult for him, and after a few weeks, Central Michigan coaches offered him a scholarship. Brown had difficulty adjusting to the college lifestyle, and being on time for meetings and practice. Azzanni and his wife helped him get situated and into an established routine, and he soon became like a part of their family. During his first season at Central Michigan, Brown played in 14 games. He played well enough to win the Mid-American Conference Freshman of the Year and was All-Conference as a returner. For his freshman season, he had 102 receptions for 1,003 yards and six touchdowns.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rivals.com/cviewplayer.asp?Player=385796 |title=Rivals.com: Antonio Brown Stats |website=Rivals.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604141852/https://www.rivals.com/cviewplayer.asp?Player=385796 |archive-date=June 4, 2012}}</ref> His 102 receptions led the Mid-American Conference in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/conferences/mac/2007-leaders.html |title=2007 Mid-American Conference Leaders |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sophomore season===\n{{see also|2008 Central Michigan Chippewas football team}}\nBrown started every game during his sophomore season in [[2008 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|2008]]. Against [[2008 Temple Owls football team|Temple]], he had three receptions for 33 yards and a season-high two touchdown receptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-10-11-central-michigan.html |title=Temple at Central Michigan Box Score, October 11, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The next week, against [[2008 Western Michigan Broncos football team|Western Michigan]], he had 10 receptions for 113 yards and threw a two-yard touchdown pass in the third quarter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-10-18-central-michigan.html |title=Western Michigan at Central Michigan Box Score, October 18, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 13, 2017}}</ref> On November 28, while playing at [[2008 Eastern Michigan Eagles football team|Eastern Michigan]], he had seven receptions for a season-high 172 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-11-28-eastern-michigan.html |title=Central Michigan at Eastern Michigan Box Score, November 28, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> For the season, Brown hauled in 93 receptions for 998 yards and seven touchdowns.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> His 410 punt return yards and 791 kick return yards that season led the conference.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/conferences/mac/2008-leaders.html |title=2008 Mid-American Conference Leaders |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Junior season===\n{{see also|2009 Central Michigan Chippewas football team}}\nIn his junior season against [[2009 Akron Zips football team|Akron]] on September 26, 2009, Brown had nine receptions for 89 yards and a season-high two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2009-09-26-central-michigan.html |title=Akron at Central Michigan Box Score, September 26, 2009 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> For the 2009 season, he had five games with over 100 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/antonio-brown-1/gamelog/2009 |title=Antonio Brown 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> In his last regular season game on January 6, 2010, against [[2009 Troy Trojans football team|Troy]], Brown had a season-high 13 receptions for 178 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-01-06-central-michigan.html |title=GMAC Bowl \u2013 Troy vs Central Michigan Box Score, January 6, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> He finished [[2009 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|2009]] with single-season bests of 110 receptions (also a school record), 1,198 receiving yards, and nine touchdowns. For his career at Central Michigan, he had a school-record 305 receptions, (including the top three seasons with the most receptions in school history), 3,199 receiving yards (fourth all-time), and 22 touchdowns (third all-time).<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/cmu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2015-16/misc_non_event/2015-fb-media-guide-records.pdf |title=Central Michigan Media Guide |website=CSTV.com |access-date=January 9, 2017}}</ref> On January 7, 2010, he announced he would forgo his senior season and enter the [[2010 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scout.com/college/central-michigan/story/936196-antonio-brown-to-enter-nfl-draft |title=Antonio Brown to Enter NFL Draft |last=Mehl |first=Thomas |website=Scout.com |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Central Michigan Chippewas|color=white}}\" | Antonio Brown !! colspan=\"4\"|Receiving !! colspan=\"4\"|Rushing\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! G !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n! [[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007]] || [[2007 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]]\n| 14 || 102 || 1,003 || 9.8 || 6 || 10 || 74 || 7.4 || 1\n|-\n! [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]] || [[2008 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]]\n| 13 || 93 || 998 || 10.8 || 7 || 20 || 116 || 5.8 || 0\n|-\n! [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]] || [[2009 Central Michigan Chippewas football team|Central Michigan]]\n| 14 || 110 || 1,198 || 10.9 || 9 || 42 || 341 || 8.1 || 3\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|[https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/antonio-brown-1.html Career] || 41 || 305 || 3,199 || 10.5 || 22 || 72 || 531 || 7.4 ||4\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nAfter Brown entered the [[2010 NFL Draft]], the majority of analysts and scouts projected him to be a fifth or sixth round draft selection. He was ranked as the 37th best wide receiver by NFLDraftScout.com and was invited to the NFL combine, where he completed the entire workout and all the positional drills.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft10/news/story?id=4806168 |title=Central Michigan Chippewas WR Antonio Brown to enter NFL draft |last=Schad |first=Joe |date=January 7, 2010 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=74466&draftyear=2010&genpos=WR| title=*Antonio Brown, DS #37 WR, Central Michigan: 2010 NFL Draft| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=nfldraftscout.com}}</ref> Brown participated at Central Michigan's Pro Day and decided to try to improve on his 10, 20, and 40-yard dash times after being unsatisfied with the numbers he clocked at the combine. He was able to improve his time in all three categories.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlive.com/articles/4467104/central_michigan_universitys_d_1.amp |title=Central Michigan University's Dan LeFevour, Antonio Brown, and Bryan Anderson ready for the draft |last=Bernreuter |first=Hugh  |date=April 22, 2010 |website=mlive.com |access-date=January 10, 2017}}</ref>\n{{nfl predraft\n| height ft = 5\n| height in = 10\u215b\n| weight = 186\n| dash = 4.48\n| ten split = 1.56\n| twenty split = 2.61\n| shuttle = 4.18\n| cone drill = 6.98\n| vertical = 33\u00bd\n| broad ft = 8\n| broad in = 9\n| bench = 13\n| wonderlic = \n| arm span = 31\n| hand span = 9\n| note = All results from the 2010 [[NFL Combine]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=74466&draftyear=2010&genpos=WR|title=*Antonio Brown \u2013 Central Michigan, WR : 2010 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile|publisher=}}</ref>\n}}\nUsing a pick received in a trade with the [[Arizona Cardinals]], the [[2010 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] selected him in the sixth round (195th overall) in the 2010 NFL Draft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2010/draft.htm |title=2010 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 4, 2017}}</ref> He was the 22nd of 27 wide receivers selected in the draft, and the second by the Pittsburgh Steelers behind [[Emmanuel Sanders]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2010/draft.htm |title=2010 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> He picked the jersey number 84, which he explained: \"Eight times four is 32. Thirty-two teams looked past me, even the Steelers. So every time I go out there it\u2019s a little added motivation.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://steelerswire.usatoday.com/2015/07/12/steelers-antonio-brown-jersey-nfl-top-100-players-list/ |title=Here's why Antonio Brown wears No. 84 |last=Coolong |first=Neal |date=July 12, 2015 |website=Steelers Wire |language=en |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Pittsburgh Steelers===\n====2010 season: Rookie year====\nOn June 15, 2010, the Pittsburgh Steelers signed Brown to a three-year, $1.28 million contract with a signing bonus of $73,075.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/pittsburgh-steelers/antonio-brown-6702/| title=Sportrac.com: Antonio Brown contract| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=sportrac.com}}</ref>\n\nBrown entered training camp competing with [[Emmanuel Sanders]], [[Tyler Grisham]], [[Stefan Logan]], [[Isaiah Williams]], and Brandon Logan to be the Steelers' backup wide receivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/110/PIT| title=Ourlads.com: Pittsburgh Steeler's Depth Chart: 07/31/2010| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=ourlads.com}}</ref> Brown was named the Steelers' fifth wide receiver on their depth chart, behind veterans [[Hines Ward]], [[Mike Wallace (American football)|Mike Wallace]], [[Antwaan Randle El]], and [[Arnaz Battle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/111/PIT| title=Ourlads.com: Pittsburgh Steeler's Depth Chart: 09/05/2010| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 2010, Brown made his NFL debut against the [[2010 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] and returned two kickoffs and a punt for 128 yards, including an 89-yard touchdown from a reverse on the first play of the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009190oti.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Tennessee Titans \u2013 September 19th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On October 3, Brown made his first NFL catch for a six-yard gain during a 17\u201314 loss to the [[2010 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201010030pit.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 October 3rd, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> During the regular-season finale against the [[2010 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Brown made a season-high four catches for 52 yards in a 41\u20139 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101020cle.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Cleveland Browns \u2013 January 2nd, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> He finished his rookie season with 16 receptions for 167 yards in ten games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BrowAn04/gamelog/2010/ |title=Antonio Brown 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Steelers finished the 2010 season atop the [[AFC North]] with a 12\u20134 record]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/pit/2010.htm |title=2010 Pittsburgh Steelers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On January 15, 2011, Brown appeared in his first postseason game and caught a 58-yard pass from [[Ben Roethlisberger]] to set up the game-winning touchdown. He finished his first playoff game with a season-high 75 yards on three receptions as the Steelers defeated the Ravens in the [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs#AFC: Pittsburgh Steelers 31, Baltimore Ravens 24|AFC Divisional Round]] by a score of 31\u201324.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101150pit.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 January 15th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The following week in the [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: Pittsburgh Steelers 24, New York Jets 19|AFC Championship]] against the [[2010 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], at the two-minute warning, Brown caught a 14-yard pass on 3rd & 6, sealing the 24\u201319 victory for the Steelers and advancing them to [[Super Bowl XLV]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101230pit.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 New York Jets at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 January 23rd, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> In his first Super Bowl, Brown handled four kickoff returns, four punt returns, and finished with one catch for one yard in the 31\u201325 loss to the [[2010 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]].<ref name=\"NFL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/antoniobrown/2508061/profile| title=NFL Player Profile: Antonio Brown| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201102060pit.htm |title=Super Bowl XLV \u2013 Pittsburgh Steelers vs. Green Bay Packers \u2013 February 6th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2011 season====\n[[File:Antonio Brown (wide receiver, born 1988).JPG|thumb|225px|Brown in 2011]]\nBrown entered training camp competing with Emmanuel Sanders, Arnaz Battle, [[Limas Sweed]], and [[Jerricho Cotchery]] to be the Steelers' third wide receiver after the departure of Antwaan Randle El. He won the competition and was named the third wide receiver on the depth chart behind Hines Ward and Mike Wallace. Brown was also named the starting kick returner and punt returner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/122/PIT| title=Ourlads.com: Pittsburgh Steeler's Depth Chart: 09/04/2011| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nBrown made his first appearance of the season in the season-opener against the [[2011 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] and finished with two receptions for 14 yards and had three kickoff returns for 34 yards in a 35\u20137 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2011091100/2011/REG1/steelers@ravens| title=NFL Game Center: Week 1\u20132011: Pittsburgh Steelers @ Baltimore Ravens| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=nfl.com}}</ref> On October 30, Brown had a season-high nine receptions for 67 yards and caught his first career touchdown reception on a seven-yard pass from [[Ben Roethlisberger]] in a 25\u201317 victory over the [[2011 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2011103008/2011/REG8/patriots@steelers| title=NFL Game Center: Week 8-2011: New England Patriots @ Pittsburgh Steelers| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=NFL.com}}</ref> The next game, he caught five passes for 109 yards, marking his first career game with over 100 receiving yards, in a 23\u201320 loss to the Ravens.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111060pit.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 November 6th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On November 13, he earned his first career start and made five receptions for 86 yards in a 24\u201317 defeat of the [[2011 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111130cin.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Cincinnati Bengals \u2013 November 13th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On December 4, he returned a punt for a 60-yard touchdown and made two catches for 67 yards, as the Steelers routed the Bengals 35\u20137.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112040pit.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 December 4th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The punt return for a touchdown was the first in his career and Brown was named AFC Special Teams Player of the Week for his performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/week_13.htm |title=2011 NFL Week 13 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> In a Week 14 win over the [[2011 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], he made his second start of the season and ended the game with five catches for a season-high 151-yards and scored a season-long 79-yard touchdown in a 14\u20133 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112080pit.htm |title=Cleveland Browns at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 December 8th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Brown finished the season with 69 receptions for 1,108 yards and two touchdown receptions in 16 games and three starts.<ref name=\"NFL\"/>\n\nThe Steelers finished 12\u20134 and received a playoff berth. On January 8, 2012, Brown caught five passes for 70 yards and had one carry for 18 yards in a 29\u201323 overtime loss to the [[2011 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] in the AFC [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 29, Pittsburgh Steelers 23 (OT)|Wild Card Round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201080den.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Pittsburgh Steelers at Denver Broncos \u2013 January 8th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrown became the first player in NFL history to have more than 1,000 yards receiving and returning in the same year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.profootballhof.com/news/antonio-brown-s-record-season/ |title=Antonio Brown\u2019s record season |website=Pro Football Hall of Fame Official Site |access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> For his efforts, Brown was selected as a punt returner for the [[2012 Pro Bowl]]. In his first Pro Bowl, Brown caught two passes for 15 yards, helping the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] defeat the [[National Football Conference|NFC]] 59\u201341.<ref name=\"NFL\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/nfl/boxscore?id=6348 |title=NFC Nationals vs. AFC Americans \u2013 Box Score \u2013 January 29, 2012 |website=www.foxsports.com |language=en-US |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2012 season====\nOn July 28, 2012, the Steelers signed Brown to a five-year, $42.5 million extension that included an $8.5 million [[signing bonus]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Florio |first=Mike |title=Steelers ink Antonio Brown to long-term deal |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/07/27/steelers-ink-antonio-brown-to-long-term-deal/ |accessdate=March 28, 2014 |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |work=[[Profootballtalk.com|Pro Football Talk]] |date=July 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319061607/http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/07/27/steelers-ink-antonio-brown-to-long-term-deal/ |archivedate=March 19, 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nWith the retirement of Hines Ward during the offseason, Brown entered training camp competing with Mike Wallace and Emmanuel Sanders to be the starting wide receivers. Brown and Wallace were subsequently named the starters at the position to begin the regular season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/135/PIT| title=Ourlads.com: Pittsburgh Steeler's Depth Chart: 09/01/2012| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=ourlads.com}}</ref> In December 2018, former Steelers safety [[Ryan Clark (American football)|Ryan Clark]] claimed that during a practice in 2012, Brown started shouting at defensive coordinator [[Dick LeBeau]] and began yelling at players on the defense, saying, \"Don't touch me. I'm the franchise.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/01/01/ryan-clark-antonio-brown-screamed-dick-lebeau-steelers-defense/2458293002/ |title=Ryan Clark: Antonio Brown screamed at Dick LeBeau, told Steelers' defense not to touch him |last=Clarke |first=Dave |date=January 1, 2019 |website=The Cincinnati Enquirer |access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the Steelers' season opener against the [[2012 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], Brown finished the 31\u201319 loss with four receptions for 74 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209090den.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Denver Broncos \u2013 September 9th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On September 23, he had seven receptions for 87 yards and a touchdown in the 34\u201331 loss to the [[2012 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://archive.triblive.com/sports/steelers/raiders-rally-to-down-steelers-34-31/ |title=Raiders rally to down Steelers, 34-31 |website=TribLIVE.com |access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, Brown was fined $10,000 by the NFL for [[unsportsmanlike conduct]] when he ran backwards for the final 20 yards of a punt return touchdown the previous week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000089472/article/league-fines-pittsburgh-steelers-antonio-brown-10k |title=League fines Pittsburgh Steelers' Antonio Brown $10K |publisher=[[National Football League]] |work=[[NFL.com]] |date=November 4, 2012 |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219232912/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000089472/article/league-fines-pittsburgh-steelers-antonio-brown-10k |archivedate=February 19, 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The following game, Brown suffered a high ankle sprain and left the game. The ankle injury prevented him from appearing in the next three games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.inquisitr.com/389737/antonio-brown-injury-status-2012-steelers-vs-chiefs/ |title=Antonio Brown injury: Steeler's WR sprains ankle, likely to miss Chief's game |last=S\u00f6ze |first=Michael  |date=November 6, 2012 |website=inquisitr.com |access-date=January 10, 2017}}</ref> During Week 15 against the [[2012 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], Brown made a season-high eight catches for 76 yards and a touchdown in a 27\u201324 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212160dal.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Dallas Cowboys \u2013 December 16th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The following week, Brown caught five passes for a season-high 97 yards and scored a 60-yard touchdown in a 13\u201310 loss to the [[2012 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212300pit.htm |title=Cleveland Browns at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 December 30th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> He finished the 2012 season with 66 receptions for 787 yards and five touchdowns in 13 games and ten starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BrowAn04/gamelog/2012/ |title=Antonio Brown 2012 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2013 season====\n[[File:Antonio brown vs coty sensabaugh.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Brown being pursued by cornerback [[Coty Sensabaugh]] in a 2013 game against the Titans]]\nBrown entered the 2013 regular season as one of the Steelers' starting wide receivers with [[Emmanuel Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/148/PIT| title=Ourlads.com: Pittsburgh Steeler's depth chart| accessdate=January 10, 2017| website=ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nBrown started in the season opener against the [[2013 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] and had five receptions for 71 yards in a 16\u20139 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080pit.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 September 8th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On September 22, he caught nine passes for a season-high and then career-high 196 yards and two touchdowns in a 40\u201323 loss to the [[2013 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309220pit.htm |title=Chicago Bears at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 September 22nd, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> The following game, Brown caught a season-high 12 passes for 88 yards in a 34\u201327 loss to the [[2013 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]].<ref name=\"NFL\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309290min.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Minnesota Vikings \u2013 September 29th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 22, Brown broke [[Yancey Thigpen|Yancey Thigpen]]'s single-season team record of 1,398 receiving yards set in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/pit/single-season-receiving.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers Single-Season Receiving Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> Brown also became the second Steeler to amass at least 100 receptions in a season, joining former teammate [[Hines Ward]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/pit/single-season-receiving.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers Single-Season Receiving Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On December 29, he, along with [[Pierre Gar\u00e7on]] of the [[Washington Redskins]], tied Jimmy Smith as the only players to record at least five receptions in every game of an NFL season. In addition, Brown became the only receiver in NFL history to record five receptions and at least 50 yards in every game of an NFL season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.steelersdepot.com/2013/12/antonio-brown-becomes-first-player-ever-with-5-receptions-50-yards-in-every-game/ |title=Antonio Brown Becomes First Player Ever With 5 Receptions, 50 Yards In Every Game \u2013 Steelers Depot |last=Marczi |first=Matthew |date=December 29, 2013 |website=Steelers Depot |language=en-US |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrown finished the 2013 season with 110 receptions for 1,499 yards and eight touchdowns.<ref name=\"NFL\"/> On December 27, 2013, Brown was selected for the [[2014 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] as a receiver and a punt returner.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/probowl.htm |title=2013 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> On January 3, 2014, Brown was named to the AP All-Pro team for the first time in his career.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/allpro.htm |title=2014 NFL All-Pros |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 23rd by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2014]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/2014-nfl-top-100.htm |title=2014 NFL Top 100 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/pittsburgh-steelers/0ap2000000361710 |title='Top 100 Players of 2014': Antonio Brown |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\nIn the season-opener against the [[2014 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], while returning a punt, Brown attempted to hurdle Cleveland Browns punter [[Spencer Lanning]] and kicked him in the facemask, garnering significant media attention.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/11483081/antonio-brown-pittsburgh-steelers-jump-kicks-cleveland-browns-punter-failed-hurdle-attempt |title=Antonio Brown jump-kicks punter |last=Brown |first=Scott |date=September 7, 2014 |website=[[ESPN.com]] |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> He finished the narrow 30\u201327 victory with five receptions for 116 yards and later apologized for the kick, calling it an accident.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070pit.htm |title=Cleveland Browns at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 September 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> Brown was fined $8,200 for the kick.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2014/09/07/antonio-brown-face-kick-steelers-browns |title=Steelers WR Antonio Brown penalized for kicking Browns' punter in face |date=September 7, 2014 |website=[[SI.com]] |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> On October 20, Brown threw his first NFL touchdown pass, a three-yard pass to wide receiver [[Lance Moore]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410200pit.htm |title=Houston Texans at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 October 20th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The following game, Brown caught ten passes for 133 yards and two touchdowns in a 51\u201334 victory over the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410260pit.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 October 26th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> During Week 9 against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Brown made a season-high 11 catches for a season-high 144 yards, including a 54-yard touchdown reception.<ref name=\"NFL\"/> In the regular-season finale against the [[2014 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], he had seven receptions for 128 yards and a touchdown to go along with a 71-yard punt return touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412280pit.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 December 28th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> His successful performance earned him AFC Special Teams Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/week_17.htm |title=2014 NFL Week 17 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Brown led the NFL in receptions (129), receiving yards (1,698), and was tied for second in touchdowns (13); all three were new team records.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/receiving.htm |title=2014 NFL Receiving |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref> The Steelers made the playoffs and faced off against the Ravens in the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC: Baltimore Ravens 30, Pittsburgh Steelers 17|Wild Card Round]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014.htm |title=2014 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> In the 30\u201317 loss, he had nine receptions for 117 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501030pit.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Baltimore Ravens at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 January 3rd, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> His successful season garnered him a third [[2015 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] selection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/probowl.htm |title=2014 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked eighth by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2015]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/2015-nfl-top-100.htm |title=2015 NFL Top 100 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2015/0ap3000000500628/Top-100-Players-of-2015-No-8-Antonio-Brown |title='Top 100 Players of 2015': No. 8 Antonio Brown |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2015 season====\n[[File:Antonio Brown 2015.jpg|thumb|Brown against the Ravens in 2015]]\nBrown started in the season-opening 28\u201321 loss to the [[2015 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] and caught nine passes for 133 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509100nwe.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at New England Patriots \u2013 September 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The following week, he had nine receptions for 195 yards and a touchdown along with a 16-yard punt return in a 43\u201318 victory over the [[2015 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200pit.htm |title=San Francisco 49ers at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 September 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> This brought his career total to 5,587 yards, good for 200th on the NFL's all-time receiving yards list. He also moved past Steelers' legend [[Lynn Swann]] on the all-time list. On November 8, Brown caught a career-high 17 passes for a career-high 284 yards in a narrow 38\u201335 victory over the [[2015 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201511080pit.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 November 8th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> His 284 receiving yards broke [[Keenan McCardell]]'s mark of 232 in 1996 for most receiving yards in a game without a receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/H3qJU |title=Most receiving yards in a game without a receiving touchdown, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> On December 6, he caught eight passes for 118 yards and two touchdowns in a 45\u201310 victory over the [[2015 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512060pit.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 December 6th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> This game is particularly notable for a play in which Brown returned a punt for a touchdown and then proceeded to leap onto the goalpost. He was flagged on the play for excessive celebration. On December 9, Brown was fined $11,576 by the NFL for the incident.<ref>{{cite news|title=Antonio Brown fined for touchdown celebration with goalpost|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2015/12/09/antonio-brown-fined-touchdown-celebration-goal-post-pittsburgh-steelers|accessdate=October 9, 2016|work=Sports Illustrated|date=December 9, 2015}}</ref> For his efforts against the Colts, he earned his third career AFC Special Teams Player of the Week Award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/week_13.htm |title=2015 NFL Week 13 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> In a Week 15 34\u201327 victory over the [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], he caught 16 passes for 189 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512200pit.htm |title=Denver Broncos at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 December 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> For his performance against the Broncos, he was named as the AFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/week_15.htm |title=2015 NFL Week 15 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 3, Brown totaled 13 receptions for 187 yards and a touchdown in a win over the [[2015 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]]. He finished the regular season with a league-high 136 receptions for 1,834 yards and 10 touchdowns<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/receiving.htm|title=2015 NFL Receiving|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> \u2013 the first two marks surpassing his own team records of 129 catches and 1,698 yards. He also set the record for most receptions in a two-year span with 265 from 2014\u201315; and most receptions in a three-year span with 375 from 2013\u201315. With his 16 receptions against the Browns, Brown became the first receiver to have two 16+ catch games in a single season, and his four games of 175+ yards in a season also set a new NFL record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/8EmEW |title=Two 16+ reception games, single season, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/wkvh5 |title=175+ receiving yards, single season, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Steelers opened postseason play with a [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: Pittsburgh Steelers 18, Cincinnati Bengals 16|Wild Card]] game against the [[2015 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], and late in the fourth quarter, Brown left the contest with a concussion after taking a hit from Bengals linebacker [[Vontaze Burfict]]. The Steelers went on to win the game by a score of 18\u201316.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601090cin.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Pittsburgh Steelers at Cincinnati Bengals \u2013 January 9th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The injury kept Brown out of the Steelers' next game in the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 23, Pittsburgh Steelers 16|Divisional Round]], where they lost 23\u201316 to the eventual [[Super Bowl 50]] champion [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601170den.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Pittsburgh Steelers at Denver Broncos \u2013 January 17th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrown was named to his third consecutive and fourth career [[2016 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]], his second first-team All-Pro, and was ranked as the top wide receiver and the fourth best player on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/probowl.htm |title=2015 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/allpro.htm |title=2015 NFL All-Pros |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000673258/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-4-Antonio-Brown |title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 4 Antonio Brown |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\nBrown started in the season opener against the [[2016 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] and finished the 38\u201316 victory with eight receptions for 126 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609120was.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Washington Redskins \u2013 September 12th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> After the game, the NFL fined him a combined $15,191 for wearing baby blue cleats, which violated the league's uniform policy, and for [[twerking]] after scoring his second touchdown.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fowler|first1=Jeremy|title=Antonio Brown on fines for TD twerk, cleats: 'Nothing to a boss'|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/antonio-brown-fines-td-twerk-cleats-boss/story?id=42122332|accessdate=October 9, 2016|work=ABC News|date=September 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Antonio Brown fined $9,115 for twerking in end zone|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/09/16/antonio-brown-fined-twerking-end-zone-shoes|accessdate=October 9, 2016|work=Sports Illustrated|date=September 16, 2016}}</ref> After performing a similar dance in the end zone in Week 4 against the [[2016 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], Brown was fined $24,309.<ref name=Roth>{{cite news|last1=Roth|first1=Dan|title=Antonio Brown's twerk celebration draws $24,000 fine|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/antonio-brown-fines-td-twerk-cleats-boss/story?id=42122332|accessdate=October 9, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=October 6, 2016}}</ref> The second fine was largely criticized by sportswriters, who considered it much too steep a penalty for a celebration.<ref name=Roth/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilder|first1=Charlotte|title=Don't stop twerking, Antonio Brown|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/10/antonio-brown-twerking-fine-chiefs|accessdate=October 9, 2016|work=USA Today|date=October 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Brinson|first1=Will|title=Antonio Brown draws a ridiculously large fine for his latest end-zone twerk|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/antonio-brown-draws-a-ridiculously-large-fine-for-his-latest-end-zone-twerk/|accessdate=October 9, 2016|work=CBS Sports|date=October 7, 2016}}</ref> The league reasoned that the dances were \"sexually suggestive\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Pittsburgh Steelers' Antonio Brown fined again for TD celebration|url=http://www.upi.com/Sports_News/NFL/2016/10/06/Pittsburgh-Steelers-Antonio-Brown-fined-again-for-TD-celebration-Video/4191475797609/|accessdate=October 9, 2016|agency=United Press International|publisher=The Sports Xchange|date=October 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week 3, Brown moved into the NFL top 100 all-time for career receptions,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_career.htm |title=NFL Receptions Career Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> and in Week 9, he joined the top 100 for career receiving yards. During Week 10, Brown caught a season-high 14 passes for a season-high 154 yards and a touchdown in a 35\u201330 loss to the [[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201611130pit.htm |title=Dallas Cowboys at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 November 13th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Two weeks later, he finished with five receptions for 91 yards and a career-high three touchdown receptions, as the Steelers defeated the [[2016 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] on the road by a score of 28-7 on [[NFL on Thanksgiving Day|Thanksgiving]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201611240clt.htm |title=Pittsburgh Steelers at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 November 24th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrown finished the regular season with 106 receptions (second in the NFL to [[Larry Fitzgerald]]) for 1,284 yards and 12 touchdowns in 15 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/receiving.htm |title=2016 NFL Receiving |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The Steelers decided to sit him for the season finale against the [[2016 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]] as they had already clinched a playoff berth.<ref name=\"NFL\"/> At the end of the 2016 regular season, Brown ranked second in career receptions and third in career receiving yards for the Steelers franchise, and 57th and 78th all-time among NFL players in those categories.\n\nIn the 2016 season, Brown posted his fourth consecutive and fifth career 1,000+ yard season in receiving yards, earning him his fourth consecutive and fifth career [[2017 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] selection on December 20, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL announces 2017 Pro Bowl rosters|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000760503/article/nfl-announces-2017-pro-bowl-rosters|website=NFL.com|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> He was named First Team [[2016 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]] for the third consecutive time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000770458/article/three-rookies-matt-ryan-among-players-named-to-allpro-team?campaign=Twitter_atn |title=Three rookies, Matt Ryan among players named to All-Pro team |date=January 6, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 21, 2019}}</ref> He was also ranked fourth by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000817551/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-4-Antonio-Brown |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 4 Pittsburgh Steelers wide receiver Antonio Brown |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, Brown caught five passes for 124 yards and two touchdowns in a 30\u201312 victory over the [[2016 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] in the AFC [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#AFC: Pittsburgh Steelers 30, Miami Dolphins 12|Wild Card Round]] game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sltrib.com/sports/nfl/2017/01/10/nfl-big-three-power-steelers-by-dolphins-30-12/ |title=NFL: \"Big Three\" power Steelers by Dolphins 30-12 |last=Graves |first=Will |date=January 9, 2017 |website=The Salt Lake Tribune |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-22 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> His two touchdowns of 50 and 62 yards were the first time since 2001 that a player had caught two 50+ yard touchdowns in a single post-season game,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fowler|first1=Jeremy|title=Steelers WR Antonio Brown scores two touchdowns on first two drives of game|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18431504/pittsburgh-steelers-wide-receiver-antonio-brown-racks-first-ever-scores-nfl-postseason|work=ESPN.com|date=January 8, 2017}}. Note that [[Jacoby Jones]] caught a 56 yard touchdown pass and returned a kickoff 108 yards in 2013.</ref> the first time ever in the first quarter,<ref>[[Ricky Sanders]] is the only player to do so in the second quarter (in 1988), [[Wayne Millner]] is the only player in the third quarter (in 1938).</ref> and the first time a Steeler had two receiving touchdowns in a Wild Card game.<ref> Brown is one of four Steelers with two receiving touchdowns in a playoff game. The 124 yards were also a Steeler record for a Wild Card game, and tied for fourth-best in any Pittsburgh playoff game.</ref> In the [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#AFC: Pittsburgh Steelers 18, Kansas City Chiefs 16|Divisional Round]], Brown caught six passes for 108 yards in an 18\u201316 road victory over the [[2016 Kansas City Chiefs season|Chiefs]], becoming the third Steeler with four or more 100-yard receiving playoff games.<ref>The others are [[Hines Ward]] with four and [[John Stallworth]] with five. Brown also joined three other Steelers for the most 100-yard playoff games in a single postseason with two.</ref> After the game, Brown broadcast the team's locker room celebration on [[Facebook Live]] in violation of NFL rules and despite the requests of teammates [[Ben Roethlisberger]] and [[Ramon Foster]] to \"keep a low profile on social media\". The broadcast included head coach [[Mike Tomlin]] speaking crudely about championship round opponent [[2016 New England Patriots season|New England]], for which Tomlin later apologized and disciplined Brown.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Michael David|title=Antonio Brown: \"I absolutely regret the Facebook Live situation\"|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2017/01/18/antonio-brown-i-absolutely-regret-the-facebook-live-situation/|accessdate=January 19, 2017|work=NBC Sports|date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Brown had been paid $244,000 by Facebook before the season to \"create content\" for live channels.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-to-pay-internet-stars-for-live-video-1468920602 |title=Facebook to Pay Internet Stars for Live Video |last=Seetharaman |first=Deepa |date=July 19, 2016 |work=Wall Street Journal |access-date=September 21, 2019 |last2=Perlberg |first2=Steven}}</ref> In the [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 36, Pittsburgh Steelers 17|AFC Championship]] against the Patriots, Brown had seven receptions for 77 yards in the 36\u201317 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201701220nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Pittsburgh Steelers at New England Patriots \u2013 January 22nd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> For his accomplishments in the 2017 season, he was ranked fourth on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/2017-nfl-top-100.htm |title=2017 NFL Top 100 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000817551/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-4-Antonio-Brown |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 4 Pittsburgh Steelers wide receiver Antonio Brown |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\nOn February 27, 2017, Brown signed a new five-year contract with the Steelers through the 2021 season. The contract was a four-year extension worth $68 million ($19 million guaranteed at signing) with a $17 million annual salary, making Brown the highest paid wide receiver in the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Brown-signed-to-a-new-five-year-contract/bcbe221d-69a7-4efe-a1f1-b11b8e1377d1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907140650/http://www.steelers.com/news/article-1/Brown-signed-to-a-new-five-year-contract/bcbe221d-69a7-4efe-a1f1-b11b8e1377d1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 7, 2017 |title=Brown signed to a new five-year contract |last=Varley |first=Teresa |date=February 27, 2017 |website=Steelers.com |access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000788040/article/antonio-brown-steelers-moving-toward-extension |title=Steelers sign Antonio Brown to new five-year deal |last=Sessler |first=Marc |date=February 27, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the season-opener against the [[2017 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Brown recorded 182 receiving yards on 11 receptions as the Steelers won on the road by a score of 21\u201318.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/boston/new-england-patriots/antonio-browns-big-day-helps-pittsburgh-steelers-beat-cleveland-browns-21-18 |title=Antonio Brown's big day helps Pittsburgh Steelers beat Cleveland Browns, 21-18 |date=September 10, 2017 |website=NBC Sports Boston |agency=Associated Press|access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> His 182 receiving yards led all NFL receivers for the season opening week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/QCDuz |title=Week 1 Receiving Results |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 26, 2018}}</ref> In addition, he caught all 11 of his targets, which marked a career-high in terms of receptions with a 100% completion rate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BrowAn04/gamelog/|title=Antonio Brown Career Game Log|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref> During a Week 4 26-9 road victory over the [[2017 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Brown became angry over not being thrown the ball by Roethlisberger on an incomplete play, and was filmed throwing a [[Gatorade]] cooler and yelling at coaches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2017/10/1/16392994/antonio-brown-flipped-cooler-screamed-at-coaches |title=Antonio Brown flipped a cooler and screamed at coaches after not getting thrown to |last=D'Andrea |first=Christian |date=October 1, 2017 |website=SB Nation |access-date=September 5, 2019}}</ref> During Week 11 against the [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], Brown made a one-handed catch adjacent to his helmet in the end zone for a touchdown. Overall, he had 10 receptions for 144 yards and three touchdowns as the Steelers won 40\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000878403/article/antonio-brown-steelers-romp-to-victory-over-titans |title=Antonio Brown, Steelers romp to victory over Titans |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |date=November 17, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=November 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000878371/article/social-media-reacts-to-antonio-browns-amazing-catch |title=Social media reacts to Antonio Brown's amazing catch |date=November 16, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=November 17, 2017}}</ref> Brown joined [[John Stallworth]] as the only Steelers player with two career games with 3+ receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/dU1aQ |title=Players with at least three receiving touchdowns in a single game, by total of games, Pittsburgh Steelers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=September 21, 2019}}</ref> For his performance in Week 11, Brown was named AFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000881394/article/antonio-brown-mark-ingram-among-players-of-week |title=Antonio Brown, Mark Ingram among Players of Week |last=Lam |first=Quang M. |date=November 22, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2017 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], he had 169 receiving yards and two touchdowns, including two sideline receptions for 37 yards in the final 17 seconds to set up the game-winning field goal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201711260pit.htm |title=Green Bay Packers at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 November 26th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref> Brown became the fifth player since the 1970 merger with four 150+ yard receiving games in the first 12 weeks of a season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/MJ0Yi |title=Players with at least 150 receiving yards in a single game, by total of games, Weeks 1-12, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=September 21, 2019}}</ref> Plagued with a minor toe injury,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000888261/article/antonio-brown-active-for-steelers-against-bengals |title=Antonio Brown plays for Steelers against Bengals |date=December 4, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> In Week 14 against the Ravens, Brown finished with a season-high 213 receiving yards, helping the Steelers narrowly win 39\u201338 and clinch the AFC North title.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712100pit.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 December 10th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 15, 2017}}</ref> His 213-yard performance marked the second time in his career with at least 200 receiving yards in a single game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/ravens-vs-steelers-score-highlights-big-ben-leads-comeback-with-career-night/ |title=Ravens vs. Steelers score, highlights: Big Ben leads comeback with career night |last=Wilson |first=Ryan |date=December 11, 2017 |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=December 20, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> During Week 15 against the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Brown left the game with a left calf injury, and was taken to the hospital. Shortly after the Steelers' 27\u201324 loss to the [[AFC East]]-clinching Patriots, it was revealed that Brown's left calf was partially torn, meaning that he would not play for the rest of the regular season, but would return during the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000894417/article/brown-out-with-partially-torn-calf-at-least-until-playoffs |title=Antonio Brown out with partially torn calf at least until playoffs |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |date=December 17, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 17, 2017}}</ref> He returned in the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: Jacksonville Jaguars 45, Pittsburgh Steelers 42|Divisional Round]] of the playoffs, recording seven catches for 132 yards and two touchdowns as the Steelers lost to the [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] by a score of 45\u201342.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801140pit.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Jacksonville Jaguars at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 January 14th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBrown finished the 2017 season with a league-leading 1,533 receiving yards. This was the second time in his career he led the league in receiving yards.  He also finished fifth in the league with 101 receptions and tied for fourth in the league with nine touchdown receptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017/receiving.htm |title=2017 NFL Receiving |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref> He was named to his sixth Pro Bowl, and was named first-team All-Pro as a unanimous selection.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895772/article/nfl-announces-2018-pro-bowl-rosters |title=NFL announces 2018 Pro Bowl rosters |date=December 19, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000903015/article/allpro-team-antonio-brown-is-unanimous-selection |title=All-Pro Team: Antonio Brown is unanimous selection |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=January 5, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked the second best player, as well as the best wide receiver, by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2018/0ap3000000938446/Top-100-Players-of-2018-Antonio-Brown-No-2 |title='Top 100 Players of 2018': Pittsburgh Steelers wide receiver Antonio Brown |work=NFL.com |access-date=October 31, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\n[[File:Antonio Brown 2018.png|thumb|Brown in 2018]]\nIn the season opener against the [[2018 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Brown reached 10,000 career receiving yards. He achieved the milestone in 116 career games; only two NFL players have reached the mark in fewer games ([[Calvin Johnson]] in 115 games and [[Julio Jones]] in 104 games).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/atlanta-falcons/post/_/id/33343 |title=Antonio Brown Becomes 2nd-Fastest Player To 10,000 Receiving Yards |last=McClure |first=Vaughn |date=November 11, 2018 |website=ESPN |access-date=October 5, 2019}}</ref> Brown finished the 21\u201321 tie with nine catches for 93 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/browns-steelers-james-conner-tyrod-taylor-antonio-brown-rain-nfl-week-1-results-fantasy-stats/145iqvfoodem61nt1j4qe0qdsv |title=Steelers, Browns tie in wet 'n' wild OT thriller |last=Chiappelli |first=Kirstie  |date=September 9, 2018 |work=Sporting News |access-date=October 31, 2018}}</ref> During Week 5 against the [[2018 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], he had six catches for 101 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2018/10/07/brown-scores-twice-steelers-roll-past-reeling-falcons-41-17/38082481/ |title=Antonio Brown scores twice as Steelers roll past reeling Falcons |date=October 7, 2018 |work=USA TODAY |access-date=October 31, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |language=en}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], Brown had five catches for 105 yards and caught the game-winning touchdown with 10 seconds left in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.profootballweekly.com/2018/10/14/steelers-foil-bengals-again-this-time-with-late-td-from-antonio-brown/as2k24/ |title=Steelers foil Bengals again, this time with late TD from Antonio Brown |last=Edholm |first=Eric |date=October 14, 2018 |work=Pro Football Weekly |access-date=October 31, 2018}}</ref> He was also a victim of a dirty hit from [[Vontaze Burfict]] in the game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ftw/2018/10/14/vontaze-burfict-is-back-to-taking-cheap-shots-at-antonio-browns-head/38156965/ |title=Vontaze Burfict takes cheap shot at Antonio Brown's head |last=Joseph |first=Andrew |date=October 14, 2018 |work=USA TODAY |access-date=October 31, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> During Week 11 against the [[2018 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], Brown had five receptions for 117 yards and a touchdown in a narrow 20-16 road victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://triblive.com/sports/steelers/14312535-74/steelers-wide-receivers-win-war-of-words-with-jaguars-corners |title=Steelers wide receivers win war of words with Jaguars corners |last=Gorman |first=Kevin |date=November 19, 2018 |website=triblive.com |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> Two weeks later, he had 10 receptions for 154 yards and a touchdown in a 33\u201330 loss against the [[2018 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/steelers-antonio-brown-season-high-receiving-yards-in-loss/ |title=Steelers' Antonio Brown: Season-high receiving yards in loss |date=December 3, 2018 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> During Week 16 against the [[2018 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], Brown finished with 185 receiving yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/steelers-antonio-brown-monstrous-outing-against-saints/ |title=Steelers' Antonio Brown: Monstrous outing against Saints |date=December 23, 2018 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> He would then tie with [[Brandon Marshall]] for most seasons with 1,000 yards and 100 receptions in NFL history with 6.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/tBoJ7 |title=Most seasons with 100 receptions and 1,000 receiving yards, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |url-status=live |access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Overall, Brown finished the 2018 season with 104 receptions for 1,297 and a career-high 15 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/pittsburgh-steelers/post/_/id/29832 |title=Antonio Brown and JuJu Smith-Schuster hit historic milestone |last=Fowler |first=Jeremy |date=December 27, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter allegedly getting into an argument with quarterback [[Ben Roethlisberger]], then skipping practices leading up to the Week 17 game against the Bengals, Brown was benched for that game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/12/31/report-antonio-brown-missed-game-for-disciplinary-reasons-not-injury/ |title=Report: Antonio Brown missed game for disciplinary reasons, not injury |last=Williams |first=Charean |date=December 31, 2018 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=February 2, 2019}}</ref> Following the season, reports surfaced indicating Brown's dissatisfaction with his role on the Steelers, and he eventually requested a trade.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/antonio-brown-goes-public-with-his-desire-to-leave-pittsburgh-time-to-move-on/ |title=Antonio Brown goes public with his desire to leave Pittsburgh: 'Time to move on' |last=Dubin |first=Jared |date=February 12, 2019 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Oakland Raiders===\nOn March 9, 2019, the Steelers agreed to trade Brown to the [[Oakland Raiders]] in exchange for a third and a fifth-round selection in the [[2019 NFL Draft]]. The deal became official on March 13, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.raiders.com/news/raiders-acquire-all-pro-wide-receiver-antonio-brown |title=Raiders acquire All-Pro wide receiver Antonio Brown |date=March 13, 2019 |website=Raiders.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331034319/https://www.raiders.com/news/raiders-acquire-all-pro-wide-receiver-antonio-brown |archive-date=March 31, 2019 |access-date=September 21, 2019}}</ref> Prior to the trade to Oakland, reports surfaced that the Steelers were \"close to a deal\" with the [[Buffalo Bills]], but that the deal was cancelled after Brown protested on social media.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/03/08/pittsburgh-steelers-antonio-brown-buffalo-bills-trade-rumors |title='Very Few Options' Left For Steelers, Antonio Brown After Failed Bills Trade |last=Axson |first=Scooby |date=March 8, 2019 |website=SI.com |language=en |access-date=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Brown's introductory press conference with the Raiders, he said \"I'm here to elevate everything around me. I'm here to just be a surge of energy, of positivity, and good force. A great teammate and to bring out the best of everyone around me cause we all know it's not just about me.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nesn.com/2019/09/this-antonio-brown-quote-from-introductory-raiders-press-conference-aged-dreadfully/ |title=This Antonio Brown Quote From Introductory Raiders Press Conference Aged Dreadfully |last=Mullen |first=Logan |date=September 7, 2019 |website=www.nesn.com |access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> On August 3, Brown posted a picture of his heavily blistered feet on Instagram, which was later revealed to be [[frostbite]]s to his feet due to not wearing proper footwear during a [[cryotherapy]] session. Brown's injury forced him to miss 10 out of 11 training camp practices with the Raiders.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2019/8/8/20758582/antonio-brown-feet-frostbite-raiders-nfl |title=Antonio Brown's feet look like a horror show. Here's why. |last=Dator |first=James |date=August 12, 2019 |website=www.sbnation.com |access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 9, he filed a grievance to continue wearing his old helmet even though it was banned, threatening to retire from football if he was forced to wear a new helmet. Despite Brown's pleas to continue wearing his old helmet, an arbitrator denied his request.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/antonio-browns-grievance-to-wear-old-helmet-denied-by-arbitrator-says-hell-rejoin-raiders/ |title=Antonio Brown's grievance to wear old helmet denied by arbitrator, says he'll rejoin Raiders |last=Sullivan |first=Tyler |date=August 12, 2019 |website=www.cbssports.com |access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Brown eventually found a replacement for his old helmet, but it also did not meet the NFL's standards. Afterwards, he continued to not practice with the Raiders.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/antonio-brown-raiders-helmet-practice-mayock-221755897.html |title=Antonio Brown skips practice over helmet issue; Raiders GM wants him 'all in or out' |last=Baer |first=Jack |date=August 18, 2019 |website=www.sports.yahoo.com |access-date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> Brown filed a second grievance regarding his helmet on August 19, which he also lost.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/08/19/antonio-brown-helmet-grievance-oakland-raiders |title=Report: Antonio Brown Files New Grievance Against NFL Over Helmet |last=Carroll |first=Charlotte |date=August 19, 2019 |website=www.si.com |access-date=August 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001051098/article/antonio-brown-faces-potential-discipline-from-raiders |title=Antonio Brown faces potential discipline from Raiders |last=Maya |first=Adam |date=September 5, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sfgate.com/raiders/article/Antonio-Brown-helmet-deal-drew-rosenhaus-14379894.php |title=Antonio Brown lost the helmet battle, but he may have won the helmet war |last=Costley |first=Drew |date=August 25, 2019 |website=www.sfgate.com |access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref> On September 4, Brown chose to wear the Xenith Shadow helmet for the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/09/04/antonio-brown-helmet-xenith-shadow-selection-raiders-wide-receiver |title=Report: Antonio Brown Ends Helmet Saga, Chooses 'Xenith Shadow' Helmet for 2019 |last=Shapiro |first=Michael |date=September 4, 2019 |website=www.si.com |access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 4, Brown was fined a combined $54,000 by general manager [[Mike Mayock]] due to unexcused absences and missing two team practice sessions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001047257/article/antonio-brown-upset-by-raiders-fines-over-absences |title=Antonio Brown upset by Raiders fines over absences |last=Gordon |first=Grant |date=September 4, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> Brown posted the letter of his fines on [[Instagram]], a move that was scrutinized around the league. The following day, Brown confronted Mayock and had a verbal altercation, with reports stating that Brown called Mayock a \"[[cracker (term)|cracker]]\", which Brown later denied. It was also reported that Brown threatened to hit Mayock, and had to be held back by several teammates, including linebacker [[Vontaze Burfict]].  Afterwards, he punted a football and said to Mayock \"fine me for that\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/raiders-reportedly-planning-to-suspend-antonio-brown-after-incident-between-wr-and-gm-mike-mayock/ |title=Raiders reportedly planning to suspend Antonio Brown after incident between WR and GM Mike Mayock |last=Brinson |first=Will |date=September 5, 2019 |website=www.cbssports.com |access-date=September 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/09/05/vontaze-burfict-peacemaker-of-course/ |title=Vontaze Burfict, peacemaker, of course |last=Gantt |first=Darin |date=September 5, 2019 |website=www.profootballtalk.nbcsports.com |access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 6, Brown showed up at a Raiders' team meeting and made an emotional apology for his actions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/09/06/antonio-brown-attends-raiders-team-meeting-gives-emotional-apology/ |title=Antonio Brown attends Raiders team meeting, gives \"emotional apology\" |last=Smith |first=Michael David |date=September 6, 2019 |website=www.profootballtalk.nbcsports.com |access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref> When head coach [[Jon Gruden]] was asked if Brown would play in Week 1 against the [[Denver Broncos]], he replied \"That's the plan. Yes.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001051543/article/gruden-the-plan-is-for-antonio-brown-to-play-monday |title=Gruden: 'The plan' is for Antonio Brown to play Monday |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=September 6, 2019 |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref> Later that day, Brown read a 20-second statement that read \"I'm excited to be out here today. I apologized to my teammates and the organization. Enough talk, man. I'm excited to be out here with my teammates. I'm grateful for all the fans. I'm excited to be a part of the Raiders and see you guys soon.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001051592/article/antonio-brown-i-apologized-to-my-teammates |title=Antonio Brown: 'I apologized to my teammates' |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=September 6, 2019 |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, less than a day later on September 7, Brown demanded his release from the Raiders after they voided the guaranteed money in his contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001051670/article/antonio-brown-posts-release-me-on-instagram |title=Antonio Brown posts \"Release me\" on Instagram |last=Gordon |first=Grant |date=September 7, 2019 |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> Brown was released by the Raiders later that day, just hours before his 2019 salary would have become guaranteed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nj.com/sports/2019/09/where-will-antonio-brown-land-next-after-raiders-disaster-patriots-cowboys-giants-looking-at-viability-for-all-31-other-teams.html |title=Raiders release Antonio Brown: Where will he land next? Patriots? Cowboys? Giants? Looking at all 31 other teams |last=Rosenblatt |first=Zack |date=September 7, 2019 |website=NJ.com |access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> Prior to his release, the Raiders fined Brown $215,000 due to his altercation with Mayock.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001051679/article/stunner-raiders-announce-release-of-antonio-brown |title=Raiders release Antonio Brown |last=Gordon |first=Grant |date=September 7, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== New England Patriots ===\n[[File:Antonio Brown 2019.png|thumb|Brown in his lone game with the Patriots in 2019.]]\nOn September 7, 2019, the same day he was released by the Raiders, Brown agreed to a one-year contract with the [[New England Patriots]] worth up to $15 million, with a $9 million signing bonus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/09/07/antonio-brown-agrees-to-terms-with-patriots/|title=Antonio Brown agrees to terms with Patriots|last=Alper|first=Josh|date=September 7, 2019|website=ProFootballTalk|language=en|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, on September 9, the Patriots added a second-year option in Brown's contract in which he would receive $20 million if picked up.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.patriots.com/news/report-2020-option-added-to-brown-pact |title=Report: 2020 option added to Brown pact |last=Scalavino |first=Erik |date=September 9, 2019 |website=Patriots.com |access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite allegations of sexual and personal misconduct levied against him, Brown practiced with the Patriots in preparation for his season debut in Week 2 against the [[2019 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/09/13/antonio-brown-new-england-patriots-debut-dolphins-rape-lawsuit/ |title=ANTONIO BROWN EXPECTED TO PLAY SUNDAY FOR PATS...Despite Rape Allegations |date=September 13, 2019 |website=www.tmz.com |access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref> He officially made his Patriots debut in Week 2, catching four passes for 56 yards and a touchdown along with a 5-yard rush in a 43\u20130 road victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2019/09/15/patriots-dolphins-recap-antonio-brown-tom-brady-gilmore-collins-defense-nfl-week-2/ |title=Antonio Brown Debuts, Patriots Defense Dominates Dolphins in 43-0 Victory |date=September 15, 2019 |work=CBS News - Boston |access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> On September 20, following further allegations, in addition to allegedly intimidating text messages sent to one of his accusers after going to New England, Brown was cut by the Patriots.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27662788/patriots-cut-ties-antonio-brown |title=Patriots cut ties with Antonio Brown |last=Reiss |first=Mike |date=September 20, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|<center>Legend</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|\n| Led the league\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n