 cover athlete for ''[[Madden NFL 19]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24129734/steelers-wr-antonio-brown-madden-19-cover |title=Steelers receiver Antonio Brown featured on Madden cover |last=Fowler |first=Jeremy |date=July 18, 2018 |website=[[ESPN.com]] |access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref> In September 2019, Brown re-enrolled for online classes at his [[alma mater]], Central Michigan University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27685104/back-school-ab-reenrolls-central-michigan|title=Back to school: AB reenrolls at Central Michigan|date=September 23, 2019|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBrown is also the cousin of [[Baltimore Ravens]] wide receiver [[Marquise Brown]], who was drafted in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/draft/2019/03/01/marquise-brown-antonio-nfl-draft-2019-combine/3030403002/ |title=Marquise Brown, cousin of Steelers' Antonio Brown, could be first wide receiver drafted in 2019 |last=Davis |first=Nate |date=March 1, 2019 |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n===Off-the-field controversies===\n\nDuring and before the 2018 season, Brown was embroiled in numerous incidents in addition to [[2018 Pittsburgh Steelers season#Off-the-field drama|causing drama within the Steelers organization]]. This included tossing furniture out of his 14th-floor apartment window in April, nearly hitting a 22-month old child on the patio below,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24942401/antonio-brown-sued-allegedly-throwing-items-balcony/ |title=Antonio Brown accused of tossing items off balcony |last=Fowler |first=Kevin |date=October 11, 2018 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 11, 2019}}</ref> and getting cited for speeding in excess of 100&nbsp;mph along a suburban highway.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.post-gazette.com/sports/steelers/2018/11/08/Pittsburgh-steelers-antonio-brown-police-speeding-ticket-ross-mcknight-road-allegheny-county/stories/201811080137/ |title= Steelers' Antonio Brown cited for driving over 100 mph on McKnight Road in Ross |last=Murray |first=Ashley |date=November 8, 2018 |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |language=en |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Brown was later sued for the April incident.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2018/10/09/antonio-brown-lawsuit-throwing-furniture-florida-balcony/ |title=Steelers' WR Antonio Brown Sued, Accused Of Nearly Hitting Toddler With Furniture Thrown From Balcony |date=October 9, 2018 |website=CBS - Pittsburgh |access-date=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2019, Brown's former trainer Britney Taylor filed a lawsuit alleging he sexually assaulted her thrice. She claimed that he exposed himself to her, ejaculated on her back, and finally raped her. Brown and his legal team denied the allegations.<ref name=\"NYT-Shpigel\">{{cite news |last1=Shpigel |first1=Ben |title=Antonio Brown Accused of Rape in a Lawsuit |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/10/sports/football/antonio-brown-sexual-asssault-patriots.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=September 11, 2019|date=September 11, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27589799/antonio-brown-accused-rape-civil-lawsuit |title=Antonio Brown accused of rape in civil lawsuit |date=September 10, 2019 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> On September 16, a second woman accused him of sexual misconduct.  Pittsburgh-based Dr. Victor Prisk, who Brown worked with while with the Steelers, also sued Brown for $11,500 in unpaid fees.<ref name=\"Brown History\">{{cite web|author=Klemko, Robert |date=September 16, 2019 |title=There's More History to Antonio Brown's History |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/09/16/antonio-brown-new-england-patriots-lawsuits-accusations-sexual-midconduct-assault |accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2020, following several domestic incidents in which police were called to Brown's home in [[Hollywood, Florida]], the [[Hollywood Police Department (Florida)|Hollywood Police Department]] stated they no longer want Brown to be associated with their youth league (PAL). The Hollywood police department returned a check from Brown and issued a trespass order preventing him from being involved with their youth league while saying in a statement, \"We do not want him to continue to affect our youth, or influence them in a negative way.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cetoute |first=Devoun |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/broward/article239246323.html |title=Former NFL star Antonio Brown waved a \u2018bag of d--ks\u2019 at cops. Police banned him from PAL |date=January 13, 2020 |work=Miami Herald |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Days later on January 21, it was reported that Brown and an accomplice had attacked a moving truck driver at the home. Brown's trainer was arrested, while a warrant for Brown's arrest was issued a day later with a felony charge of [[Battery (crime)|battery]] and [[burglary]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2020/01/22/antonio-brown-arrest-warrant-issued-battery/4548818002/ |title=Arrest warrant issued for Antonio Brown on burglary with battery charge |last=Middlehurst-Schwartz |first=Michael |date=2020-01-22 |website=USA TODAY |language=en-US |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> He turned himself in a night later on January 23.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28550533/antonio-brown-turns-police-arrest-warrant |title=AB turns himself in to police after arrest warrant |last=Wolfe |first=Cameron |date=2020-01-24 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n===''Dancing with the Stars''===\nOn March 8, 2016, Brown was announced as one of the celebrities who competed on [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 22)|season 22]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. He was paired with professional dancer [[Sharna Burgess]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/dancing-stars-2016-season-22-celebrity-cast-revealed/story?id=37472389|title='Dancing With the Stars' 2016: Season 22 Celebrity Cast Revealed Live on 'GMA'|work=ABC News|date=March 8, 2016|accessdate=March 8, 2016}}</ref> Brown and Burgess were eliminated during the semifinals of the show and finished the competition in fourth place overall.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://abc.go.com/shows/dancing-with-the-stars/news/dwts-results-and-eliminations/dancing-with-the-stars-2016-semifinals-results-wanya-morris-antonio-brown-eliminated-051616 |title=DWTS 2016 Results: Wanya Morris and Antonio Brown Eliminated! |last=Donnelly |first=Jim |date=May 16, 2016 |access-date=February 26, 2018 |website=ABC}}</ref>\n\n===''The Masked Singer''===\nOn January 2, 2019, Brown took part on the first season of the American version of ''[[The Masked Singer (U.S. TV series)|The Masked Singer]]''. He competed in the show wearing \"The Hippo\" costume and sang \"[[My Prerogative]]\" by [[Bobby Brown]] before being eliminated in the first episode.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2019/01/03/antonio-brown-eliminated-masked-singer/ |title=Antonio Brown Eliminated From Masked Singing Competition Show |date=January 3, 2019 |website=CBS Pittsburgh |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of National Football League annual receiving touchdowns leaders]]\n* [[List of National Football League annual receiving yards leaders]]\n* [[List of National Football League annual receptions leaders]]\n* [[List of National Football League career receiving yards leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Antonio Brown}}\n* [https://www.patriots.com/team/players-roster/antonio-brown/ New England Patriots profile]\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Steelers2010DraftPicks}}\n{{NFL receiving yardage leaders}}\n{{NFL receiving touchdown leaders}}\n{{NFL2010s}}\n{{Madden NFL games}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:American male sprinters]]\n[[Category:Central Michigan Chippewas football players]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Steelers players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Miami]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:The Masked Singer (American TV series) contestants]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Brown"}
{"title_page": "Isle of Portland", "text_new": "{{other uses|Portland (disambiguation)}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|official_name= Portland (Isle of Portland)\n|static_image_name = Flag of Isle of Portland.gif\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.550|-2.440|display=inline,title}}\n|population = 12,400\n|population_ref =<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\">{{cite web| year = 2011 | url = http://www.dorsetforyou.com/index.jsp?articleid=343603 | title=Portland\u2014Dorset For You | publisher = Dorset County Council | accessdate = 14 December 2012}}</ref>{{ref label|estimate|A|A}}\n|civil_parish= Portland\n|unitary_england= [[Dorset (unitary authority)|Dorset]]\n|shire_county = [[Dorset]]\n|region= South West England\n|constituency_westminster= [[South Dorset (UK Parliament constituency)|South Dorset]]\n|post_town= PORTLAND\n|postcode_district = DT5\n|postcode_area= DT\n|dial_code= 01305\n|os_grid_reference= SY690721\n|london_distance_mi = 120\n|london_distance = &nbsp;east north-east\n}}\n\nThe '''Isle of Portland''' is a [[tied island]], {{convert|4|mi|km|0}} long by {{convert|1.7|mi|km|1}} wide, in the [[English Channel]].<ref name=\"Isle of Portland\">{{cite web | year = 2015 | url = http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/471189/Isle-of-Portland | title = Isle of Portland | publisher = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica | accessdate = 27 April 2015}}</ref> Portland is {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} south of the resort of [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]], forming the southernmost point of the county of [[Dorset]], England. A [[barrier beach]] called [[Chesil Beach]] joins it to the mainland. The [[A354 road]] passes down the Portland end of the beach and then over the [[Fleet Lagoon]] by bridge to the mainland. Portland and Weymouth together form the borough of [[Weymouth and Portland]]. The population of Portland is 12,400.\n\nPortland is a central part of the [[Jurassic Coast]], a [[World Heritage Site]] on the Dorset and east [[Devon]] coast, important for its geology and landforms. [[Portland stone]], a [[limestone]] famous for its use in British and world architecture, including [[St Paul's Cathedral]] and the [[United Nations Headquarters]], continues to be quarried here.\n\n[[Portland Harbour]], in between Portland and Weymouth, is one of the largest man-made harbours in the world. The harbour was made by the building of stone [[breakwater (structure)|breakwater]]s between 1848 and 1905. From its inception it was a [[Royal Navy]] base, and played prominent roles during [[World War I|the First]] and [[World War II|Second World Wars]]; ships of the Royal Navy and [[North Atlantic Treaty Organisation|NATO]] countries worked up and exercised in its waters until 1995. The harbour is now a civilian port and popular recreation area, and was used for the [[2012 Olympic Games]].\n\nThe name Portland is used for one of the [[British Sea Areas]], and has been [[Portland (disambiguation)|exported]] as the name of North American and Australian towns.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Uk dor portcastle.JPG|thumb|left|325px|[[Portland Castle]] was built to defend Portland in the 16th century.]]\n\nPortland has been inhabited since at least the [[Mesolithic]] period (the Middle [[Stone Age]])\u2014there is archaeological evidence of Mesolithic inhabitants at the [[Culverwell Mesolithic Site]], near [[Portland Bill]],<ref name=\"Mesolithic\">{{cite web | year = 2002 | url = http://www.gallica.co.uk/celts/portland.htm | title = Mesolithic Site, Portland | publisher = Association for Portland Archaeology | accessdate = 30 July 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070609212653/http://www.gallica.co.uk/celts/portland.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 9 June 2007}}</ref> and of habitation since then. The Romans occupied Portland, reputedly calling it ''Vindelis''.<ref name=\"vindelis\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.uni-mannheim.de/mateo/camenaref/hofmann/hof4/s0773b.html | title = Lexicon Universale | publisher = Universit\u00e4t Mannheim | accessdate = 3 April 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Portland stone\" />\n\nAlthough the beginning of the [[Viking Age]] in England is dated to their raid in 793,<ref name=\"English Heritage\">{{cite web |url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/lindisfarne-priory/history/ |title=History of Lindisfarne Priory|publisher=English Heritage |accessdate=2016-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"Swanton\">Swanton, Michael (1998). ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''. Psychology Press. {{ISBN|0-415-92129-5}}. p. 57, n. 15.</ref> when they destroyed the [[abbey]] on [[Lindisfarne]], their first documented landing occurred in Portland four years earlier, in 789, as recorded in the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saxons.etrusia.co.uk/vikings_invasions.php|title=What spurred the Viking invasions?|work=Saxons and Vikings in Britain}}</ref> Three lost Viking ships from [[Hordaland]] (the district around [[Hardanger]] fjord in west [[Norway]]) landed at Portland Bill. The king's [[Reeve (England)|reeve]] tried to collect taxes from them, but they killed him and sailed on.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.cn.edu/kwheeler/viking_attacklist.html?showall=1|title=Viking Attacks}}</ref>\n\n[[Rufus Castle]], standing over [[Church Ope Cove]] was built for [[William II of England]] (also known as William Rufus) soon after the conquest of England by his father [[William the Conqueror]].  None of that castle remains; the existing castle dates from the 15th century.\n\nIn 1539 [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII]] ordered the construction of [[Portland Castle]] for defence against attacks by the French; the castle cost \u00a34,964.<ref name=\"portlandcastle\">{{cite web | year = 2000 | url = http://www.thedorsetpage.com/locations/Place/P120.htm | title = Portland, Dorset, England | publisher = The Dorset Page | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> It is one of the best preserved castles from this period, and is opened to the public by the custodians [[English Heritage]].<ref name=\"englishheritage\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/nav.15746 | title = Portland Castle | publisher = English Heritage | accessdate = 30 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the 17th century, chief architect and Surveyor-General to James I, [[Inigo Jones]], surveyed the area and introduced the local [[Portland stone]] to London, using it in his [[Banqueting House, Whitehall]], and for repairs on [[St Paul's Cathedral]].<ref name=\"RhodesStone2013\">{{cite book|first1=Frank H. T.|last1=Rhodes|first2=Richard O.|last2=Stone|title=Language of the Earth|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Rq_fBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA261 |year=2013|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-1-4831-6166-2|page=261}}</ref> His successor, Sir [[Christopher Wren]], the architect and Member of Parliament for nearby Weymouth, used six million tons of white Portland limestone to rebuild destroyed parts of the capital after the [[Great Fire of London]] of 1666. Well-known buildings in the capital, including St Paul's Cathedral<ref name=\"st paul's\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.stpauls.co.uk/page.aspx?theLang=001lngdef&pointerid=32207NnDnfjeCGJ1g2bvy1Jt3FI0gUAP | title = 1710&nbsp;\u2013 Construction is Completed | publisher = Dean and Chapter St Paul's | accessdate = 3 April 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928083501/http://www.stpauls.co.uk/page.aspx?theLang=001lngdef&pointerid=32207NnDnfjeCGJ1g2bvy1Jt3FI0gUAP |archivedate = 28 September 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the eastern front of [[Buckingham Palace]] feature the stone.<ref name=\"buckinghampalace\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page568.asp | title = Buckingham Palace History | publisher = HM Queen Elizabeth II | accessdate = 3 April 2007}}</ref> After the First World War, a [[quarry]] was opened by [[The Crown Estate]] to provide stone for the [[Cenotaph]] in [[Whitehall]] and half a million gravestones for war cemeteries,<ref name=\"Portland stone\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.dorsets.co.uk/Portland/ | title = Portland\u2014Dorset | publisher = Dorset Guide | accessdate = 3 April 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070505011524/http://www.dorsets.co.uk/Portland/ | archive-date = 5 May 2007 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and after the Second World War hundreds of thousands of gravestones were hewn for soldiers who had fallen on the [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]].<ref name=\"Portland stone\" /> [[Portland cement]] has nothing to do with Portland; it was so named due to its similar colour to Portland stone when mixed with lime and sand.<ref name=\"cement\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.cement.org/basics/concretebasics_history.asp | title = History & Manufacture of Portland Cement | publisher = Portland Cement Association | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Porland island map1937.jpg|thumb|right|A map of the Isle of Portland from 1937, showing the railway to [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]]]]\nThere have been railways in Portland since the early 19th century. The [[Merchant's Railway]] was the earliest\u2014it opened in 1826 (one year after the [[Stockton and Darlington railway]]) and ran from the quarries at the north of [[Tophill]] to a pier at [[Castletown, Dorset|Castletown]], from where the Portland stone was shipped around the country.<ref name=\"railways\">{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.johnrnew.demon.co.uk/weyrails.htm | title = Railways of the Weymouth area | publisher = Island Publishing | accessdate = 26 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070403155729/http://www.johnrnew.demon.co.uk/weyrails.htm | archivedate = 3 April 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Portland, an illustrated History\">{{cite web | year =2016 | url = http://www.dovecotepress.com/?product=portland-an-illustrated-historystuart-morris | title = Portland, an Illustrtaed History | publisher = The Dovecote Press | accessdate = 10 October 2016}}</ref>  The [[Portland Branch Railway|Weymouth and Portland Railway]] was laid in 1865, and ran from a station in [[Melcombe Regis]], across the Fleet and along the low isthmus behind Chesil Beach to a station at [[Victoria Square, Portland|Victoria Square]] in [[Chiswell]].<ref name=\"railways2\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=351 | title = Weymouth to Portland Railway, Construction and growth | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 26 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008013056/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=351 |archivedate = 8 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the end of the 19th century the line was extended to the top of the island as the Easton and Church Ope Railway, running through Castletown and ascending the cliffs at East Weares, to loop back north to a station in [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]].<ref name=\"railways\" /> The line closed to passengers in 1952, and the final goods train (and two passenger 'specials') ran in April 1965.<ref name=\"railways2\" />\n\nThe [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution|Royal National Institution for the Preservation of Life from Shipwreck]] stationed a [[Lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]] at Portland in 1826, which was withdrawn in 1851.<ref>{{cite book |last= Denton |first= Tony |title= Handbook 2009 |year= 2009 |publisher= Lifeboat Enthusiasts Society |location= Shrewsbury |page= 59 }}</ref> Coastal flooding has affected Portland's residents and transport for centuries\u2014the only way off the island by land is along the causeway in the lee of Chesil Beach. At times of extreme floods (about every 10 years) this road link is cut by floods. The low-lying village of [[Chiswell]] used to flood on average every 5 years. Chesil Beach occasionally faces severe storms and massive waves, which have a [[fetch (geography)|fetch]] across the Atlantic Ocean.<ref name=\"flooding\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://content.swgfl.org.uk/jurassic/chis10.htm | title = Chiswell case study: The Scheme | publisher = Jurassic Coast | accessdate = 27 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140320175647/http://content.swgfl.org.uk/jurassic/chis10.htm | archivedate = 20 March 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Following two severe flood events in the 1970s, [[Weymouth and Portland]] Borough Council and [[Wessex Water]] decided to investigate the structure of the beach, and [[coastal management]] schemes that could be built to protect Chiswell and the beach road. In the 1980s it was agreed that a scheme to protect against a [[return period|one-in-five-year]] storm would be practicable; it would reduce flood depth and duration in more severe storms.<ref name=\"flooding\"/> [[Coastal management#Hard construction techniques|Hard engineering]] techniques were employed in the scheme, including a [[gabion]] running {{convert|550|m|yd|-1}}<ref name=\"gabion\">{{cite web | year = 2013 | url = http://test.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Chiswell_Gabions_LL_Factsheet_aug12.pdf | title = Chiswell Gabions Flood Alleviation Scheme | publisher = Environment Agency | accessdate = 20 March 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140320172310/http://test.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Chiswell_Gabions_LL_Factsheet_aug12.pdf | archivedate = 20 March 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> to the north of Chiswell, an extended [[sea wall]] in [[Chesil Cove]], and a [[culvert]] running from inside the beach, underneath the beach road and into [[Portland Harbour]], to divert flood water away from low-lying areas.<ref name=\"flooding\"/>\n\n[[Image:uk dor portharbour.JPG|thumb|right|Portland Harbour was home to the [[Royal Navy]]. Their former [[barracks]] are in the foreground.]]\n\nAt the start of the First World War, [[HMS Hood (1891)|HMS ''Hood'']] was sunk in the passage between the southern breakwaters to protect the harbour from torpedo and submarine attack.<ref name=\"HMShood\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/hms_hood.htm | title = Turret Battleship, HMS Hood | publisher = Cranston Fine Arts | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> [[Portland Harbour]] was formed (1848\u20131905) by the construction of breakwaters, but before that the natural anchorage had hosted ships of the [[Royal Navy]] for more than 500 years. It was a centre for Admiralty research into [[asdic]] submarine detection and underwater weapons from 1917 to 1998; the shore base [[HMS Serepta]] was renamed [[RNAS Portland (HMS Osprey)|HMS Osprey]] in 1927.<ref name=\"serepta\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.helis.com/database/?menu=2&tpais=UK&tbase=33&menudiv=1 | title = Portland Base/Heliport History | publisher = helis.com | accessdate = 28 July 2007}}</ref> During the Second World War Portland was the target of heavy bombing, although most warships had moved north as Portland was within enemy striking range across the Channel. [[Mulberry Harbour]] Phoenix Units can be seen at Black Barge beach, near [[Portland Castle]].  Portland was a major embarkation point for Allied forces on [[Normandy landings|D-Day]] in 1944. Early [[helicopter]]s were stationed at Portland in 1946\u20131948, and in 1959 a shallow tidal flat, The Mere, was infilled, and sports fields taken to form a heliport. The station was formally commissioned as HMS Osprey, which then became the largest and busiest military helicopter station in Europe. The base was gradually improved with additional landing areas and one of England's shortest runways, at {{convert|229|m|ft|0}}.<ref name=\"serepta\" />\n\nThe naval base closed after the end of the [[Cold War]] in 1995, and the Royal Naval Air Station closed in 1999, although the runway remained in use for [[Her Majesty's Coastguard]] Search and Rescue flights as MRCC Portland<ref name=\"serepta\" /> until 2014.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2014 | url = http://www.mby.com/news/portland-coastguard-centre-to-close-next-month-mca-confirms-40749 | title = Portland Coastguard centre to close next month, MCA confirms | publisher = mby.com | accessdate = 16 May 2018}}</ref> MRCC Portland's area of responsibility extended midway across the [[English Channel]], and from [[Start Point, Devon|Start Point]] in Devon to the Dorset/[[Hampshire]] border, covering an area of around {{convert|10400|km2|sqmi|-2}}.<ref name=\"coastguard\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.beercoastguard.org/coastguard_rescue_helicoper.htm | title = Coastguard Rescue Helicopter | publisher = Beer Coastguard | accessdate = 28 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930140301/http://www.beercoastguard.org/coastguard_rescue_helicoper.htm |archivedate = 30 September 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The 12 Search and Rescue teams in the Portland area dealt with almost 1000 incidents in 2005.<ref name=\"mrccportland\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.mcga.gov.uk/c4mca/mcga-dops-regional/eastern-region/mcga-dops_rr_east_regional-eastern-region-solent.htm | title = Eastern Region&nbsp;\u2013 Area South | publisher = [[Maritime and Coastguard Agency]] | accessdate = 28 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070806080135/http://www.mcga.gov.uk/c4mca/mcga-dops-regional/eastern-region/mcga-dops_rr_east_regional-eastern-region-solent.htm | archivedate = 6 August 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are still two prisons on Portland: [[The Verne (HM Prison)|HMP The Verne]], which until 1949 was a huge Victorian military fortress, and a Young Offenders' Institution ([[HMYOI]]) on the Grove clifftop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.uk/contacts/prison-finder/portland |title=HMP/YOI Portland information |publisher=Justice.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> This was the original prison ([[HM Prison Portland]]) built for convicts who quarried stone for the Portland Breakwaters from 1848. For a few years until 2005 Britain's only [[prison ship]], [[Weare (HM Prison)|HMP ''The Weare'']], was berthed in the harbour.<ref>{{cite web|first=Steven |last=Morris |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/aug/12/ukcrime.prisonsandprobation |title=Britain's only prison ship ends up on the beach &#124; UK news |newspaper=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:DorsetWeymouthPortland.png|thumb|left|[[Weymouth and Portland]] shown in Dorset]]\n\n== Governance ==\nPortland is an ancient [[royal manor]], and until the 19th century remained a separate [[Liberty (division)|liberty]] within Dorset for administration purposes. It was an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] from 1894 to 1974, until the borough of [[Weymouth and Portland]] formed on 1 April 1974 under the [[Local Government Act 1972]]. This merged the borough of Weymouth and Melcombe Regis with Portland urban district. For [[UK local elections|local elections]] the borough is divided into 15 wards, and three of them cover Portland.<ref name=\"wards\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=620 | title = Ward Map | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 16 December 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224210742/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=620 |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Elections take place in a four-year cycle; one third of the councillors in all but three wards retire or seek re-election in years one, two and three, and county council elections are held in year four.<ref name=\"election cycle\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=618 | title = Electoral Cycles Thirds | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 4 January 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080408031609/http://weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=618 |archivedate = 8 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe mayor of Weymouth and Portland is Ray Banham ([[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]), Kate Wheller ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]) is deputy mayor.<ref name=\"weymouthcouncillors\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://webapps-wpbc.dorsetforyou.com/apps/democracy/councillors.asp | title = WPBC Serving Councillors | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 14 December 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121231143454/http://webapps-wpbc.dorsetforyou.com/apps/democracy/councillors.asp | archivedate = 31 December 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Weymouth, Portland and the [[Purbeck (district)|Purbeck]] district are in the [[South Dorset]] [[United Kingdom constituencies|parliamentary constituency]], created in 1885. The constituency elects one Member of Parliament; the current MP is [[Richard Drax]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]).<ref name=\"drax\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/constituency/1296/dorset-south | title = Dorset South | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | accessdate = 19 June 2010 | year=2010}}</ref> South Dorset, the rest of the [[South West England]], and [[Gibraltar]] are in the [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England constituency]] of the [[European Parliament]].<ref name=\"euparliament\">{{cite web | year = 2004 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=621 | title = European elections | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 16 December 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224210748/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=621 |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWeymouth and Portland have been twinned with the town of [[Holzwickede]] in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany since 1986,<ref name=\"holzwickede\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | language = German | url = http://testholzwickede.kdvz.de/erleben/kultur_sport_freizeit/sp_auto_424.php | title = St\u00e4dtepartnerschaften in Holzwickede | publisher = Gemeinde Holzwickede | accessdate = 15 December 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224200246/http://testholzwickede.kdvz.de/erleben/kultur_sport_freizeit/sp_auto_424.php |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the French town of [[Louviers]], in the [[departments of France|department]] of [[Eure]] in Normandy, since 1959.<ref name=\"louviers\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | language = French | url = http://www.ville-louviers.fr/ville/associations/jumelages/anglais/jum-anglais.htm | title = Associations de jumelage | publisher = Ville de Louviers | accessdate = 15 December 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224201120/http://www.ville-louviers.fr/ville/associations/jumelages/anglais/jum-anglais.htm | archivedate = 24 December 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The borough and nearby [[Chickerell]] have been a [[Fairtrade Zone]] since 2007.<ref name=\"fairtrade\">{{cite web | year = 2008 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/living/community/pages/fairtrade/home.asp?svid=982 | title = Weymouth & Portland: a Fairtrade Zone | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 7 March 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071029080021/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/living/community/pages/fairtrade/home.asp?svid=982 |archivedate = 29 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[Image:Terraced houses at fortuneswell 2.jpg|right|thumb|Terraced Portland Stone houses in [[Villages of Portland#Fortuneswell|Fortuneswell, Underhill]]]]\n[[Image:PortlandBill&ChesilBeach.jpg|thumb|Isle of Portland from the air]]\nThe Isle of Portland lies in the [[English Channel]], {{convert|3|km|mi|0}} south of [[Wyke Regis]], and {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}} west-southwest of London, at {{coord|50|33|0|N|2|26|24|W| region:GB_type:city}} (50.55,&nbsp;\u22122.44). Portland is situated approximately halfway along the [[UNESCO]] [[Jurassic Coast]] [[World Heritage Site]]; the site includes {{convert|153|km|mi|0}} of the Dorset and east Devon coast that is important for its geology and landforms.<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.jurassiccoast.com/279/visiting-the-coast-31/gateway-towns-146/portland-447.html | title = Portland | publisher = [[Jurassic Coast]] | accessdate = 29 December 2007}}</ref> The [[South West Coast Path]] runs around the coast; it is the United Kingdom's longest [[Long-distance footpaths in the UK|national trail]] at {{convert|1014|km|mi|0}}. Portland is unusual as it is connected to the mainland at [[Abbotsbury]] by [[Chesil Beach]], a [[tombolo]] which runs {{convert|29|km|mi|0}} north-west to [[West Bay, Dorset|West Bay]].<ref name=\"chesil\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.soton.ac.uk/~imw/chesil.htm | title = The Chesil Beach&nbsp;\u2013 General Introduction | publisher = Southampton University | accessdate = 13 August 2007}}</ref> Portland is sometimes defined incorrectly as a tombolo\u2014in fact Portland is a tied island, and Chesil Beach is the tombolo (a spit joined to land at both ends).<ref name=\"tombolo\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.vnc.qld.edu.au/enviro/flinders/land-defns.htm | title = Coastal Landform Definitions | publisher = Villanova College | accessdate = 29 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070714013950/http://www.vnc.qld.edu.au/enviro/flinders/land-defns.htm | archivedate = 14 July 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are eight settlements on Portland, the largest being [[Fortuneswell]] in Underhill and [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]] on Tophill. [[Castletown, Dorset|Castletown]] and [[Chiswell]] are the other villages in Underhill, and [[Weston, Dorset|Weston]], [[Southwell, Dorset|Southwell]], [[Wakeham]] and [[The Grove, Portland|the Grove]] are on the Tophill plateau.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dorsetlife.co.uk/2015/02/a-portrait-of-portland/ |title=A portrait of Portland &#124; Dorset Life - The Dorset Magazine |publisher=Dorset Life |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> Many old buildings are built out of Portland Stone; several parts have been designated Conservation Areas to preserve the unique character the older settlements which date back hundreds of years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.gov.uk/conservation-area/weymouth-and-portland |title=Conservation areas - Weymouth and Portland |publisher=Weymouth & Portland Borough Council |date=2017-09-29 |accessdate=2018-04-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416200757/https://www.dorsetforyou.gov.uk/conservation-area/weymouth-and-portland |archive-date=16 April 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Isle of Portland has been designated by [[Natural England]] as National Character Area 137. It is adjoined by the [[Weymouth Lowlands]] to the north.<ref>[http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/Images/jca137+138_tcm6-5506.pdf ''Isle of Portland/Weymouth Lowlands''] at naturalengland.org.uk. Accessed on 4 April 2013.</ref>\n\n[[Image:Dorset geology.png|thumb|left|upright=1.25|The Isle of Portland lies on Upper [[Oolite]] [[limestone]].]]\n\n=== Geology ===\nGeologically, Portland is separated into two areas; the steeply sloping land at its north end called [[Underhill, Dorset|Underhill]], and the larger, gently sloping land to the south, called [[Tophill]]. [[Portland stone]] lies under Tophill; the strata decline at a shallow angle of around 1.5 degrees, from a height of {{convert|151|m|ft|0}} near [[Verne (HM Prison)|the Verne]] in the north, to just above sea level at [[Portland Bill]].<ref name=\"geology\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.soton.ac.uk/~imw/portnew.htm#cross | title = General Geology | publisher = Southampton University | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> The geology of Underhill is different to Tophill; Underhill lies on a steep [[escarpment]] composed of Portland Sand, lying above a thicker layer of [[Kimmeridge Clay]], which extends to Chesil Beach and Portland Harbour. This Kimmeridge Clay has resulted in a series of landslides, forming West Weares and East Weares.<ref name=\"geology\" />\n\n{{convert|2.4|km|1}} underneath south Dorset lies a layer of [[Triassic]] [[rock salt]], and Portland is one of four locations in the United Kingdom where the salt is thick enough to create stable cavities.<ref name=\"echogas\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/local/display.var.1881457.0.island_may_be_key_gas_supplier.php | title = Island may be key gas supplier | publisher = Dorset Echo | accessdate = 5 December 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"portlandgas1\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.portland-gas.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=48&Itemid=105 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070729214525/http://www.portland-gas.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=48&Itemid=105 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 29 July 2007 | title = Portland gas storage project | publisher = Portland Gas | accessdate = 5 December 2007 }}</ref> Portland Gas applied to [[salt mine|excavate]] 14 caverns to store {{convert|1000000000|m3|cuft}} of natural gas, which is one percent of the UK's total annual demand.<ref name=\"echogas\" /><ref name=\"portlandgas1\" /> It was proposed that the caverns should be connected to the National gas grid at [[Mappowder]] via a {{convert|37|km|mi|adj=on}} pipeline.<ref name=\"echogas\" /><ref name=\"portlandgas1\" /> Plans had it that the surface facilities should be complete to store the first gas in 2011, and the entire cavern space available for storage in winter 2013.<ref name=\"portlandgas1\" /> As part of the \u00a3350&nbsp;million scheme,<ref name=\"echogas\" /> the [[Grade II listed]] former [[The Old Engine Shed, Portland|Old Engine Shed]] would be converted into a \u00a31.5&nbsp;million educational centre with a caf\u00e9 and an exhibition space about the geology of Portland.<ref name=\"educationcentre\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/local/display.var.1881211.0.island_may_get_a_1_5m_visitor_centre.php | title = Island may get a \u00a31.5m visitor centre | publisher = Dorset Echo | accessdate = 5 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Portland Bill ===\n[[Image:Portland Bill Lighthouse 2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Portland Bill Lighthouse]] and visitors' centre]]\n[[Portland Bill]] is the southern tip of the island of Portland. The Bill has three lighthouse towers: [[Old Higher Lighthouse|The Higher Lighthouse]] is now a dwelling and holiday apartments; [[Old Lower Lighthouse|the Lower Lighthouse]] is now a bird observatory and field centre providing records of bird migration and accommodation for visitors, which opened in 1961.<ref>Stuart Morris, 2016 ''Portland, an Illustrated History'' The Dovecote Press, [[Wimborne]], Dorset: {{ISBN|978-0-9955462-0-2}}</ref> The [[Portland Bill Lighthouse|white and red lighthouse]] on Bill Point replaced the Higher and Lower Lighthouses in 1906. It is a prominent and much photographed feature; an important landmark for ships passing the headland and its [[tidal race]]. The current lighthouse was refurbished in 1996 and became remotely controlled. It now contains a visitors' centre giving information and guided tours of the lighthouse.<ref name=\"lighthouse\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.trinityhouse.co.uk/interactive/gallery/portland_bill.html | title = Portland Bill Lighthouse | publisher = Trinity House | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}. * Stuart Morris, 2016 ''Portland, an Illustrated History'' The Dovecote Press, [[Wimborne]], Dorset: {{ISBN|978-0-9955462-0-2}}</ref> As of June 2009, the lighthouse uses a 1&nbsp;kW metal-halide US-made lamp with an operational life of about 4000 hours, or 14 months.\n\nPortland Ledge is an underwater extension of Portland Stone into the English Channel at a place where the depth of Channel is 20 to 40 metres (about 10 to 20 fathoms). Tidal flow is disrupted by the feature; at 10 metres (about 5 fathoms) deep and {{convert|2.4|km|nmi|1}} long, it causes a tidal race to the south of Portland Bill, the so-called ''Portland Race''.<ref name=\"shambles\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.soton.ac.uk/~imw/portnew.htm#offshore | title = Offshore Geology | publisher = Southampton University | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> The current only stops for brief periods during the {{frac|12|1|2}}-hour tidal cycle and can reach {{convert|4|m/s|kn|0}} at the spring tide of {{convert|2|m|0}}.<ref name=\"shambles\" />\n\n=== Ecology ===\n[[Image:PortlandCoast.JPG|thumb|right|Portland's cliffs and quarries have extensive specialised flora and fauna.]]\nDue to its isolated coastal location, the Isle of Portland has an extensive range of [[flora]] and [[fauna]]; the coastline and disused quarries are designated as [[Sites of Special Scientific Interest]].<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\" /><ref name=\"wildlife\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=546|title=Portland wildlife|year=2007|publisher=Weymouth & Portland Borough Council |accessdate=27 July 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513165029/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=546|archivedate=13 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sea and migratory birds occupy the cliffs in different seasons, sometimes these include rare species which draw ornithologists from around the country.<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\" /><ref name=\"fauna\" /> Rare visitors to the surrounding seas include dolphins, seals and basking sharks.<ref name=\"wildlife\" /> Chesil Beach is one of only two sites in Britain where the scaly cricket can be found; unlike any other cricket it is wingless and does not sing or hop.<ref name=\"fauna\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=542 | title = Chesil Beach | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 27 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070513190720/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=542 |archivedate = 13 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Ten British Primitive goats were introduced to the East Weares part of the island to control scrub in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portlandcp.org.uk/island/WildlifeNewsletter.pdf|title=Wildlife on Portland|date=Spring 2008|publisher=Heights Hotel and Swarovski Optik |accessdate=18 March 2012|format=PDF}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe comparatively warm and sunny climate allows species of plants to thrive which do not on the mainland. The limestone soil has low nutrient levels; hence smaller species of wild flowers and grasses are able to grow in the absence of larger species.<ref name=\"wildlife\" /> Portland sea lavender can be found on the higher sea cliffs; unique to Portland, it is one of the United Kingdom's rarest plants.<ref name=\"flora\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=543 | title = Coastal Flora & Fauna | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 27 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070513164925/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=543 |archivedate = 13 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The wild flowers and plants make an excellent habitat for butterflies; over half of the British Isles' 57 butterfly species can be seen on Portland, including varieties that migrate from mainland Europe.<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\" /> Species live on Portland that are rare in the United Kingdom, including the limestone race of the [[silver-studded blue]].<ref name=\"butterflies\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=541 | title = Portland Butterflies | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 27 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070513190734/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=541 |archivedate = 13 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate ===\n[[Image:Weymouth Climatic Graph.png|right|thumb|upright=1.75|Climatic [[ergograph]] for the nearby [[Wyke Regis]] weather station]]\nThe mild seas which almost surround the tied island produce a [[temperate]] climate ([[Humid temperate climate|K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Cfb'') with a small variation in daily and annual temperatures. The average annual mean temperature from 1981 to 2010 was {{Convert|11.2|C|F|1}}.<ref name=\"annualmean\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/portland#?tab=climateTables | title = Climate \u2013 Chosen location: Portland | publisher = [[Met Office]] | accessdate = 5 December 2012}}</ref> The warmest month is August, which has an average [[temperature|temperature range]] of {{convert|14.5|to|19.3|C|F}}, and the coolest is February, which has a range of {{convert|4.0|to|8.0|C|F}}.<ref name=\"annualmean\" /> Maximum and minimum temperatures throughout the year are above England's average,<ref name=\"englandclimate\">{{cite web|year=2001 |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/england.html |title=England 1971\u20132000 averages |publisher=Met Office |accessdate=10 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605024000/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/england.html |archivedate= 5 June 2011 }}</ref> and Portland is in [[Hardiness zone#American Horticultural Society heat zones|AHS Heat zone 1]].{{ref label|ahs1|B|B}} Mean [[sea surface temperatures]] range from {{convert|7.0|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|1}} in February to {{convert|17.2|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|1}} in August; the annual mean is {{convert|11.8|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|1}}.<ref name=\"seatemperatures\"/>\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Isle of Portland [[climate|climatic]] averages\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 8.4\n|Feb high C = 8.0\n|Mar high C = 9.4\n|Apr high C = 11.5\n|May high C = 14.3\n|Jun high C = 16.8\n|Jul high C = 18.8\n|Aug high C = 19.3\n|Sep high C = 17.8\n|Oct high C = 14.8\n|Nov high C = 11.6\n|Dec high C = 9.2\n|year high C = 13.4\n\n|Jan mean C = 6.6\n|Feb mean C = 6.0\n|Mar mean C = 7.3\n|Apr mean C = 9.0\n|May mean C = 11.7\n|Jun mean C = 14.3\n|Jul mean C = 16.4\n|Aug mean C = 16.9\n|Sep mean C = 15.4\n|Oct mean C = 12.8\n|Nov mean C = 9.7\n|Dec mean C = 7.3\n|year mean C = 11.2\n\n|Jan low C = 4.7\n|Feb low C = 4.0\n|Mar low C = 5.2\n|Apr low C = 6.4\n|May low C = 9.1\n|Jun low C = 11.8\n|Jul low C = 14.0\n|Aug low C = 14.5\n|Sep low C = 13.0\n|Oct low C = 10.8\n|Nov low C = 7.7\n|Dec low C = 5.4\n|year low C = 8.9\n\n|Jan sun =64.6\n|Feb sun =86.7\n|Mar sun =126.3\n|Apr sun =191.0\n|May sun =225.0\n|Jun sun =226.5\n|Jul sun =236.9\n|Aug sun =218.0\n|Sep sun =167.2\n|Oct sun =115.1\n|Nov sun =82.0\n|Dec sun =59.7\n|year sun = 1798.9\n<!-- NOT RECOGNIZED BY THE TEMPLATE\n|Jan mean sea surf C = 7.8\n|Feb mean sea surf C = 7.0\n|Mar mean sea surf C = 7.5\n|Apr mean sea surf C = 8.8\n|May mean sea surf C = 11.0\n|Jun mean sea surf C = 13.3\n|Jul mean sea surf C = 15.8\n|Aug mean sea surf C = 17.2\n|Sep mean sea surf C = 16.7\n|Oct mean sea surf C = 14.7\n|Nov mean sea surf C = 12.3\n|Dec mean sea surf C = 9.8\n|year mean sea surf C = 11.8\n -->\n|Jan rain mm =67.3\n|Feb rain mm =53.1\n|Mar rain mm =52.3\n|Apr rain mm = 46.9\n|May rain mm =44.1\n|Jun rain mm =39.3\n|Jul rain mm =35.1\n|Aug rain mm =41.4\n|Sep rain mm =46.9\n|Oct rain mm =81.6\n|Nov rain mm =81.6\n|Dec rain mm =78.2\n|year rain mm = 667.9\n\n|unit rain days = 1&nbsp;mm\n|Jan rain days =12.4\n|Feb rain days =9.8\n|Mar rain days = 9.6\n|Apr rain days =8.5\n|May rain days = 8.2\n|Jun rain days =6.6\n|Jul rain days = 6.6\n|Aug rain days =7.1\n|Sep rain days =7.8\n|Oct rain days = 11.5\n|Nov rain days =12.4\n|Dec rain days =12.0\n|year rain days = 112.5\n\n| source 1 = 1981&ndash;2010 averages for the Isle of Portland climate station and Weymouth Cefas station. Sources: [[Met Office]]<ref name=\"MetOffice\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/portland#?tab=climateTables | title = Climate - Chosen location: Portland | publisher = Met Office | accessdate = 2012-12-05}}</ref> and [[Cefas]]<ref name=\"seatemperatures\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.cefas.co.uk/data/sea-temperature-and-salinity-trends/presentation-of-results/station-24-weymouth.aspx | title = Cefas Station 24: Weymouth | publisher = [[Cefas|The Centre for Environment Fisheries & Aquaculture Science]] | accessdate = 2012-12-05 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070613213637/http://www.cefas.co.uk/data/sea-temperature-and-salinity-trends/presentation-of-results/station-24-weymouth.aspx | archivedate = 13 June 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe mild seas that surround Portland act to keep night-time temperatures above freezing, making winter frost rare: on average 9.6 days per year&nbsp;\u2014 this is far below the United Kingdom's average annual total of 55.6 days of frost.<ref name=\"annualmean\" /><ref name=\"UKaverages\" /> Days with snow lying are equally rare: on average zero to six days per year;<ref name=\"metofficesnow\">{{cite web|year=2001 |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/dl/17.gif |title=Met Office UK snow lying days |publisher=Met Office |accessdate=18 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809125155/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/dl/17.gif |archivedate= 9 August 2007 }}</ref> almost all winters have no more than one day with snow lying. It may snow or [[rain and snow mixed|sleet]] in winter, yet it almost never settles on the ground\u2014coastal areas in [[South West England]] such as Portland generally experience the mildest winters in the UK.<ref name=\"metofficewinter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/tmean/16.gif |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531061625/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/tmean/16.gif |archive-date=2010-05-31 |accessdate=10 December 2016 |publisher=Met Office |year=2001 |title=Mean Temperature (\u00b0C) Winter Average 1971-2000}}</ref> Portland is less affected by the Atlantic storms that [[Devon]] and [[Cornwall]] experience. The [[growing season]] lasts for more than 310 days per year,<ref name=\"growingseason\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/#?tab=climateMaps | title = Growing season length \u2013 Annual average: 1971\u20132000 | publisher = Met Office | accessdate = 5 December 2012}}</ref>{{ref label|growingseason|D|D}} and the borough is in [[Hardiness zone]] 9.<ref name=\"hardinesszones\">{{cite web | year = 1999 | url = http://www.gardenweb.com/zones/europe/ | title = Hardiness Zone Map for Europe | publisher = GardenWeb | accessdate = 20 June 2007}}</ref>{{ref label|hardinesszone|E|E}}\n\nWeymouth and Portland, and the rest of the south coast,<ref name=\"metofficeengland\">{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/location/england/index.html | title = Met Office: English climate | publisher = Met Office | accessdate = 6 November 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061117202818/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/location/england/index.html |archivedate = 17 November 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> has the sunniest climate in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\" /><ref name=\"sunshine\">{{cite news | url = http://property.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/property/buying_and_selling/article2875491.ece | title = Bring me sunshine | publisher = [[Times Online]] | accessdate = 8 March 2008 | location=London | first1=Robert | last1=Penn | first2=Antony | last2=Woodward | date=18 November 2007}}</ref> Portland averaged 1798.9 hours of sunshine annually between 1981 and 2010,<ref name=\"annualmean\" /> which is 41% of the maximum possible,{{ref label|sunshine|C|C}} and 34% above the [[Climate of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom average]] of 1339.7 hours.<ref name=\"UKaverages\">{{cite web|year=2001 |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/uk.html |title=UK 1971\u20132000 averages |publisher=Met Office |accessdate=4 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705140124/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/uk.html |archivedate= 5 July 2009 }}</ref> December is the cloudiest month (59.7 hours of sunshine), October and November the joint wettest ({{Convert|81.6|mm|in|1}} of rain) and July is the sunniest and driest month (236.9 hours of sunshine, {{Convert|35.1|mm|in|1}} of rain).<ref name=\"annualmean\" /> Sunshine totals in all months are well above the United Kingdom average,<ref name=\"UKaverages\" /> and monthly rainfall totals throughout the year are less than the UK average, particularly in summer;<ref name=\"UKaverages\" /> this summer minimum of rainfall is not experienced away from the south coast of England.<ref name=\"metofficeengland\" /> The average annual rainfall of {{convert|667.9|mm|in|1}} is well below the UK average of {{convert|1125|mm|in|1}}.<ref name=\"UKaverages\" />\n\n== Demography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"float:right; line-height:1.1em; border:1px #000; margin-left:0; text-align:right;\"\n|-\n! Religion\n! %<ref name=\"WPreligion\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-286262 | title = 2011 Census, Key Statistics for Local Authorities in England and Wales | publisher = [[Office for National Statistics]] | accessdate = 16 December 2007}}</ref>{{ref label|weymouthandportland|F|F}}\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Buddhism|Buddhist]]\n|0.4\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |Christian\n|61.0\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Hinduism|Hindu]]\n|0.1\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Jewish]]\n|0.1\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Muslim]]\n|0.5\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Irreligion|No religion]]\n|29.3\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[List of religions|Other]]\n|0.7\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Sikhism|Sikh]]\n|0.1\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |Not stated\n|7.9\n|}\n\n{| class=\"toc\" border=\"1\" style=\"float:right; border-collapse:collapse; margin-right:10pt; margin-top:1em;\"\n|-\n!Age!!Percentage<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" />\n|-\n||0\u201315||align=right|18.1\n|-\n||16\u201317||align=right|2.4\n|-\n||18\u201344||align=right|33.5\n|-\n||45\u201359||align=right|21.9\n|-\n||60\u201384||align=right|21.7\n|-\n||85+||align=right|2.3\n|}\n\n{| class=\"toc\" border=\"1\" style=\"float:right; border-collapse:collapse; margin-right:10pt; margin-top:1em; margin-left:1em; margin-bottom:2em;\"\n|-\n!Year!!Population<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" />\n|-\n||1971||align=right|12,330\n|-\n||1981||align=right|12,410\n|-\n||1991||align=right|13,190\n|-\n||2001||align=right|12,800\n|-\n||2010||align=right|12,400{{ref label|estimate|A|A}}\n|}\n\nThe mid-year population of Portland in 2010 was 12,400;{{ref label|estimate|A|A}} this figure has remained around twelve to thirteen thousand since the 1970s. In 2010 there were 5,786 dwellings in an area of {{convert|11.5|km2|acre|-1}}, giving an approximate population density of 1100 people per km<sup>2</sup> (4.5 per acre).<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" /> The population is almost entirely native to England\u201494.9 percent of residents are of white British ethnicity, well above the England and Wales average of 80.5 percent.<ref name=\"WPreligion\" /> The average price of a detached house on Portland in 2010 was [[GBP|\u00a3]]194,200; [[terraced house]]s are cheaper, at \u00a3149,727, and an apartment or [[Maisonette (apartment)|maisonette]] costs \u00a3110,500.<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" />{{ref label|julysep|G|G}}\n\nCrime rates are below average\u2014there were 5.4 burglaries per 1000 households in 2009 and 2010; which is lower than [[South West England]] (7.6 per 1000) and significantly lower than [[England and Wales]] (11.6 per 1000).<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" /> Unemployment levels are very low, at 1.9 percent in July 2011,<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" /> compared to the United Kingdom average of 7.7 percent.<ref name=\"unemployment\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.statistics.gov.uk/cci/nugget.asp?id=12 | title = All releases of Labour Market Statistics | publisher = [[Office for National Statistics]] | accessdate = 14 December 2012}}</ref> The most common religious identity in Weymouth and Portland is Christianity, at 61.0 percent, which is slightly above the [[Religion in the United Kingdom#Statistics|England and Wales average]] of 59.3 percent.<ref name=\"WPreligion\" /> The next-largest sector is those with no religion, at 29.3 percent, also slightly above the average of 25.1 percent.<ref name=\"WPreligion\" />\n\n== Transport ==\n[[Image:Dorset transport.png|thumb|right|upright=1.75|The [[A354 road|A354]] links Portland to the main road network and other transport services in Weymouth.]]\nThe [[A354 road]] is the only land access to Portland, via Ferry Bridge, connecting to [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]] and to the wider road network at the [[A35 road|A35]] [[trunk road]] in [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]]. It runs from [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]], splitting into a northbound section through [[Chiswell]] and a southbound section through [[Fortuneswell]], then along [[Chesil Beach]] and across a bridge to the mainland in [[Wyke Regis]]. Formerly the [[Portland Branch Railway]] also crossed to the island. The corridor is now a traffic-free walking and cycle path.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sustrans.org.uk/ncn/map/route/route-26|title=Route 26|publisher=Sustrans |access-date=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nLocal buses are run by [[FirstGroup]], with services to Weymouth.<ref name=\"firstbus\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.firstgroup.com/ukbus/southwest/dorset/timetables/index.php | title = Dorset Timetables | publisher = First Group | accessdate = 6 January 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.today/20070811131154/http://www.firstgroup.com/ukbus/southwest/dorset/timetables/index.php | archivedate = 11 August 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Weymouth is the hub for south Dorset bus routes, with services to Dorchester and local villages.<ref name=\"firstbus\" /> Weymouth is connected to towns and villages along the [[Jurassic Coast]] by the Jurassic Coast Bus service, which runs for {{convert|142|km|mi|0}} from [[Exeter]] to [[Poole]], through [[Sidford]], [[Beer, Devon|Beer]], [[Seaton, Devon|Seaton]], [[Lyme Regis]], [[Charmouth]], [[Bridport]], [[Abbotsbury]], Weymouth, [[Wool, Dorset|Wool]], and [[Wareham, Dorset|Wareham]].<ref name=\"coastbus\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.jurassiccoast.com/283/visiting-the-coast-31/getting-to-and-around-the-jurassic-coast-148/jurassic-coast-bus-service-464.html | title = Jurassic Coast Bus Service | publisher = Jurassic Coast | accessdate = 6 January 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070826183226/http://www.jurassiccoast.com/283/visiting-the-coast-31/getting-to-and-around-the-jurassic-coast-148/jurassic-coast-bus-service-464.html | archive-date = 26 August 2007 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Trains run from Weymouth to London, [[Southampton]] and [[Bristol]], but ferries no longer transport passengers to the French port of [[St Malo]] and the [[Channel Islands]] of [[Guernsey]] and [[Jersey]].<ref name=\"used\">{{cite web | year = 2015 | url = hhttps://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-dorset-32013883 | title = used to go | publisher = BBC News | accessdate = 23 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nSt George's Community Primary School is located in [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.schoolguide.co.uk/schools/st-georges-community-primary-school-portland |title=St George's Community Primary School review |publisher=School Guide |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> The only other school on Portland is the [[Atlantic Academy Portland|Atlantic Academy]], an all-through school for pupils aged 3 to 19 based at two different sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantic-aspirations.org/268/welcome |title=Welcome - Atlantic Academy Isle of Portland |publisher=Atlantic-aspirations.org |date=2018-04-10 |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> Formerly known as the Isle of Portland Aldridge Community Academy, it formed in 2012 by merging four primary schools and one secondary school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/10184563.VIPs_to_attend_handover_of_buildings_to_Portland_Academy/ |title=VIPs to attend handover of buildings to Portland Academy &#124; Bournemouth Echo |publisher=Bournemouthecho.co.uk |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\nSome students commute to [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]] or [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]] to study [[A-Level]]s, or to attend other secondary schools nearby. [[Weymouth College]] in [[Melcombe Regis]] is the nearest [[further education]] college, which has around 7,500 students from [[south west England]] and overseas,<ref name=\"weymouthcollege\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.ac.uk/the-college/welcome.html | title = About Us | publisher = Weymouth College | accessdate = 4 January 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080530161535/http://www.weymouth.ac.uk/the-college/welcome.html | archivedate = 30 May 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> about 1500 studying A-Level courses.<ref name=\"sixthform\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://localinfo.dorsetecho.co.uk/li/secondary_schools_a_level.in.Weymouth | title = Secondary Schools (A-Level) in Weymouth | publisher = Dorset Echo | accessdate = 4 January 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071030134924/http://localinfo.dorsetecho.co.uk/li/secondary_schools_a_level.in.Weymouth | archivedate = 30 October 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n=== Sport and recreation ===\n[[Image:Uk dor sailingacademy.JPG|thumb|right|[[Weymouth and Portland National Sailing Academy]]]]\nIn 2000, the [[Weymouth and Portland National Sailing Academy]] was built in Osprey Quay in Underhill as a centre for sailing in the United Kingdom. [[Weymouth Bay|Weymouth and Portland's waters]] were credited by the [[Royal Yachting Association]] as the best in Northern Europe.<ref name=\"wpnsa\">{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/London2012/home.asp?svid=14 | title = 2012 Olympic Games sailing venue | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 12 November 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061231110947/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/London2012/home.asp?svid=14 |archivedate = 31 December 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> Weymouth and Portland regularly host local, national and international sailing events in their waters; these include the J/24 World Championships in 2005, trials for the 2004 Athens Olympics, the ISAF World Championship 2006, the BUSA Fleet Racing Championships, and the RYA Youth National Championships.<ref name=\"wpnsaevents\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url= http://www.wpnsa.org.uk/pressreleases.htm | title = Press Releases 2006 | publisher = Weymouth & Portland National Sailing Academy | accessdate = 12 November 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061202013033/http://www.wpnsa.org.uk/pressreleases.htm |archivedate = 2 December 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the WPNSA was selected to host sailing events at the [[2012 Summer Olympic Games|2012 Olympic Games]]\u2014mainly because the Academy had recently been built, so no new venue would have to be provided.<ref name=\"2012chosen\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/4653721.stm | title = Sailing town's joy at Olympic win | publisher = BBC | accessdate = 7 January 2008 | date=6 July 2005}}</ref> However, as part of the [[South West of England Regional Development Agency]]'s plans to redevelop Osprey Quay, a new 600-berth marina and an extension with more on-site facilities were built.<ref name=\"portlandmarina\">{{cite web |year = 2007 | url = http://www.portlandmarina.co.uk | title = Dean and Reddyhoff Marina | publisher = Dean and Reddyhoff Limited | accessdate = 26 March 2007}}</ref> Construction was scheduled between October 2007 and the end of 2008, and with its completion and formal opening on 11 June 2009, the venue became the first of the 2012 Olympic Games to be completed.<ref name=\"wpnsaextension\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/6246176.stm | title = New Olympic marina plan approved |publisher= [[BBC]] |accessdate= 27 June 2007 |date=27 June 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= 2012 work completed at WPNSA |url= http://www.rya.org.uk/newsevents/news/Pages/2012sailingvenueofficially.aspx | publisher = [[Royal Yachting Association]] | year = 2009 | accessdate = 10 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Sailing rivals use Olympic venue | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/8193246.stm | publisher = BBC News | accessdate = 10 August 2009 | date=10 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = First 2012 Olympic venue unveiled | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/7753734.stm | publisher = BBC News | accessdate = 30 September 2009 | date=28 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|NyBEyROnlCg|Video of HM The Queen visiting the Sailing Academy at YouTube}}</ref>\n\nWeymouth Bay and Portland Harbour are used for other water sports&nbsp;\u2013 the reliable wind is favourable for [[windsurfing|wind]] and [[kitesurfing|kite-surfing]]. Chesil Beach and Portland Harbour are used regularly for angling, scuba diving to shipwrecks, snorkelling, canoeing, and swimming.<ref name=\"watersports\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/Leisure/Watersports/home.asp?svid=69 | title = Watersports in Weymouth and Portland | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 12 November 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061010232523/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/Leisure/Watersports/home.asp?svid=69 |archivedate = 10 October 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> The limestone cliffs and quarries are used for [[rock climbing]]; Portland has areas for [[bouldering]] and deep water soloing, however [[sport climbing]] with bolt protection is the most common style.<ref name=\"rock climbing\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.rockfax.com/databases/results_area.html?id=5 | title = World Rock Climbing Information: Portland | publisher = Rockfax | accessdate = 19 May 2007}}</ref> Since June 2003 the [[South West Coast Path]] [[National Trail]] has included {{convert|21.3|km|mi|1}} of coastal walking around the Isle of Portland, including following the A354 Portland Beach Road twice.<ref>{{cite book|last=South West Coast Path Association|authorlink=South West Coast Path Association|title=South West Coast Path 2009 Guide|publisher=SWCPA|year=2009|page=94|isbn=978-0-907055-15-0}}</ref>\n\nIsle of Portland has a [[Non-League football]] club [[Portland United F.C.]] who play at Grove Corner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portlandutdfc.co.uk/club-info/new-grove-corner/ |title=Portland United FC |publisher=Portlandutdfc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> They also have a youth set up called Portland United youth football Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familyinformationdirectory.dorsetforyou.gov.uk/kb5/dorset/fsd/service.page?id=1pzil8E_wfI |title=Portland United Youth Football Club &#124; Dorset FID |publisher=Familyinformationdirectory.dorsetforyou.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Rabbits ===\n[[Image:PortlandQuarry.jpg|thumb|right|Accidents in Portland's quarries led to a fear of the word ''rabbit''.]]\nRabbits have long been associated with bad luck on Portland. Use of the name is still taboo\u2014the creatures are often referred to as \"underground mutton\", \"long-eared furry things\" or just \"bunnies\".<ref name=\"wallaceandgromit\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/4318710.stm | title = Wallace and Gromit spook island | publisher = BBC | accessdate = 26 July 2007 | date=7 October 2005}}</ref> The origin of this superstition is obscure (there is no record of it before the 1920s) but it is believed to derive from quarry workers. They would see rabbits emerging from their burrows immediately before a rock fall and blame them for increasing the risk of dangerous, sometimes deadly, [[landslide]]s.<ref name=\"rabbits\" /> If a rabbit was seen in a quarry, the workers would go home for the day, until the safety of the area had been assured.<ref name=\"wallaceandgromit\" />\n\nToday older Portland residents are 'offended' (sometimes for the benefit of tourists) by the mention of rabbits;<ref name=\"rabbits\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=784 | title = Rabbits, the Portland taboo word | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 26 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071024070726/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=784 |archivedate = 24 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> this superstition came to national attention in October 2005 when a special batch of advertisement posters were made for the [[Wallace and Gromit]] film, ''[[Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit|The Curse of the Were-Rabbit]]''. Out of respect for local beliefs the adverts omitted the word 'rabbit' and replaced the film's title with the phrase ''\"Something bunny is going on\"''.<ref name=\"wallaceandgromit\" />\n\n=== Literature ===\n[[Thomas Hardy]] described Portland as \"the peninsula carved by Time out of a single stone\", and named it the ''Isle of Slingers'' and ''Isle of the Race'' in his Wessex novels; it was the main setting of ''[[The Well-Beloved]]'' (1897), and was featured in ''[[The Trumpet-Major]]'' (1880).<ref name=\"Orel1990\">{{cite book|first=H.|last=Orel|title=Thomas Hardy's Personal Writings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XMleCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA263|year= 1990|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-0-230-37371-6|page=263}}</ref><ref name=\"slingers\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.lymeregis.com/hardy_country/ | title = Thomas Hardy County and the Hardy Trail | publisher = Lyme Regis Tourist Information | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> The cottage that now houses [[Portland Museum, Dorset|Portland Museum]] was the inspiration for the heroine's house in ''The Well-Beloved''. Portlanders were expert stone-throwers in the defence of their land, and Hardy's ''Isle of Slingers'' is heavily based on Portland; the ''Street of Wells'' representing Fortuneswell and ''The Beal'' Portland Bill.  Hardy also called Portland the ''Gibraltar of the North'', with reference to its similarities with [[Gibraltar]]; its physical geography, isolation, comparatively mild climate, and [[Underhill, Dorset|Underhill]]'s winding streets.<ref name=\"wellbeloved\">{{cite web | authorlink = [[Thomas Hardy]] | year = 2007 | url = http://www.fullbooks.com/The-Well-Beloved1.html | title = The Well-Beloved by Thomas Hardy | publisher = Full Books | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Hilaire Belloc]]'s book ''The Cruise of the \"''Nona''\"'' is about sailing near Portland, and the reflections it occasions. He describes Portland Race as \"the master terror of our world\", and says \"...&nbsp;if you were to make a list of all the things which Portland Race has swallowed up, it would rival [[Orcus]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/719165/UK-The-Gibraltar-of-Wessex.html |title=UK: The Gibraltar of Wessex |publisher=Telegraph |date=2001-07-14 |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Charlie|last=Connelly|title=Attention All Shipping: A Journey Round the Shipping Forecast|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27urnq0h7OAC&pg=PT88|year=2011|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-0-7481-3187-7|page=88}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Museums Without Walls'', [[Jonathan Meades]] declares that \"Portland is a bulky chunk of geological, social, topographical and demographic weirdness. It is the obverse of a beauty spot. 'Beauty' in this construction implies the picturesque. Portland is gloriously bereft of this quality. It is awesome. There is nothing pretty about it.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KWsuCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT40|title=Museum Without Walls|authorlink=Jonathan Meades}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Warlord Chronicles]]'' (1995\u201397), [[Bernard Cornwell]] makes Portland the [[Isle of the Dead (mythology)|Isle of the Dead]], a place of internal exile, where the causeway was guarded to keep the 'dead' (people suffering insanity) from crossing [[Fleet Lagoon|the Fleet]] and returning to the mainland. No historical evidence exists to support this idea.<ref name=\"isleofthedead\">{{cite web | year = 1999 | url = http://www.britishdowsers.org/EEG_site/archive/articles/aua2001_issue24/isleofdead_JHarvey_m.htm | title = The Isle of the Dead | publisher = British Society of Dowsers | accessdate = 30 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930021015/http://www.britishdowsers.org/EEG_site/archive/articles/aua2001_issue24/isleofdead_JHarvey_m.htm | archivedate = 30 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Portland Chronicles series of four children's books, set on and around Portland and Weymouth and written by local author Carol Hunt, draw on local history to explore a seventeenth century world of smuggling, witchcraft, piracy and local intrigue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rovingpress.co.uk/PortlandSeaDragon.html |title=Portland Sea Dragon |publisher=Roving Press |date=2 July 2013 |accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Louis L'Amour]] novel ''[[To the Far Blue Mountains]]'' the novel's main character, [[Barnabas Sackett]], hides in [[Cave Hole, Portland|Cave Hole]] at the Bill of Portland before meeting a sailing ship in an attempt to escape from England.\n\n''[[Pink Pippos of Portland]]'', a children's storybook about nearby [[Chesil Beach]] was written by Portland author [[Sandra Fretwell]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Joanna |title=Page-turner is a family affair |url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/1768414.Page-turner_is_a_family_affair/ |website=Dorset Echo |accessdate=12 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Vernacular ===\n''Bunnies'': ([[Isle of Portland#Rabbits|see above]]).\n\n''Kimberlin'': slang for any 'strangers' who live on the island but are not from the island.<ref>Fido Lunettes (nom de plume), 1825, An Historical and Descriptive Account of the Peninsula of Portland from the Earliest to the Present Time, p 48 summary in The Portland Year Book and Island Record 1905, reprinted Portland Museum, 2004. * Stuart Morris, 2016 ''Portland, an Illustrated History'' The Dovecote Press, [[Wimborne]], Dorset: {{ISBN|978-0-9955462-0-2}}</ref>\n\n''Portland screw'': [[fossil]] [[mollusc]] (''[[Aptyxiella portlandica]]'') with a long screw-like shell or its cast.<ref name=\"Portland Stone\">{{cite web | year = 2000 | url = http://iq.learningstone.net/p2/nf/bob_ford/briefing_pack/portland_stone.php | title = The Independent Quarry Research Project | publisher = Portland Quarry and Sculpture Trust | accessdate = 21 July 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100202202257/http://iq.learningstone.net/p2/nf/bob_ford/briefing_pack/portland_stone.php | archive-date = 2 February 2010 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Notable people==\n* Lead singer of rock band [[Art Brut]], [[Eddie Argos]]\n* [[Edgar F. Codd]] (23 August 1923&nbsp;\u2013 18 April 2003), British [[computer science|computer scientist]] and inventor of the [[relational model]] for database management\n* Former Premier League referee [[Paul Durkin]]\n* Former Queensland, Australia, politician [[Pat Comben]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portalbar|England|Islands}}\n\n== References ==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{refbegin}}\n:{{note label|estimate|A|A}}This figure is an estimate for mid-2010.\n:{{note label|ahs1|B|B}}Areas in [[American Horticultural Society]] Heat Zone 1 experience less than one day per year with maximum temperatures above {{convert|30|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.ahs.org/pdfs/05_heat_map.pdf | title = Plant Heat-Zone Map | format = PDF | publisher = [[American Horticultural Society]] | accessdate = 3 January 2008}}</ref>\n:{{note label|sunshine|C|C}}The maximum hours of sunshine possible in one year is approximately 4383 hours (12 hours/day \u00d7 365.25 days).\n:{{note label|growingseason|D|D}}The [[growing season]] in the United Kingdom is defined as starting on the day after five consecutive days with mean temperatures above {{convert|5|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}. The season finishes the day after mean temperatures are below {{convert|5|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}} for five consecutive days.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.defra.gov.uk/environment/statistics/globatmos/kf/gakf19.htm | title = Length of the thermal growing season: 1772\u20132006 | publisher = [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] | accessdate = 22 December 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071103041655/http://www.defra.gov.uk/environment/statistics/globatmos/kf/gakf19.htm <!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate = 3 November 2007}}</ref>\n:{{note label|hardinesszone|E|E}}Areas in [[Hardiness zone]] 9 experience an average lowest recorded temperature each year between {{convert|-6.6|and|-1.1|C|F}}.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2003 | url = http://www.usna.usda.gov/Hardzone/hrdzon3.html | title = Hardiness Zones&nbsp;\u2013 Details | publisher = [[United States National Arboretum]] | accessdate = 22 December 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20010422044919/http://www.usna.usda.gov/Hardzone/hrdzon3.html | archivedate = 22 April 2001 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n:{{note label|weymouthandportland|F|F}}Figures are for Weymouth and Portland as a whole.\n:{{note label|julysep|G|G}}These figures are for July to September in 2010.\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n* Anon 1905, ''The Portland Year Book and Island Record 1905'', reprinted 2004, Portland Museum, Portland, Dorset\n* Theresa Murphy, ''Murder in Dorset 1988.'' Robert Hale Limited, London \u2013 Portland chapters\n* Stuart Morris, 2016 ''Portland, an Illustrated History'' The Dovecote Press, [[Wimborne]], Dorset: {{ISBN|978-0-9955462-0-2}} \n* Geoffrey Carter, 1999 ''Royal Navy at Portland Since 1845''. Maritime Books, {{ISBN|978-0907771296}}.\n* Stuart Morris, 1998 ''Portland'' (''Discover Dorset'' Series) The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|1-874336-49-0}}.\n* Rodney Legg, 1999 ''Portland Encyclopedia''. Dorset Publishing Company, {{ISBN|978-0948699566}}.\n* Jackson, Brian L. 1999. ''Isle of Portland railways''. {{ISBN|0-85361-540-3}}\n* Palmer, Susann. 1999. ''Ancient Portland: Archaeology of the Isle''. Portland: S. Palmer. {{ISBN|0-9532811-0-8}}\n* Stuart Morris, 2002 ''Portland: A Portrait in Colour'' The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|1-874336-91-1}}.\n* Stuart Morris, 2006 ''Portland, Then and Now'' The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|1-904349-48-X}}.\n* ''Dorset: The Royal Navy'' Stuart Morris, 2011, The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|978-1-904349-88-4}}. Features Portland.\n* ''Weymouth & Portland'', Stuart Morris 2012. The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|978-1-904349-98-3}}.\n* {{cite book |last=Hackman |first=Gill |year=2014 |title=Stone to Build London: Portland's Legacy |location=Monkton Farleigh, Wilts |publisher=Folly Books |isbn=978-0-9564405-9-4 |oclc=910854593}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Portland, Isle of}}\n{{commons category|Isle of Portland}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Isle of Portland}}\n* Map sources for grid reference {{mmukscaled|SY690721|100|SY 690 721}}.\n* [http://www.portlandtowncouncil.gov.uk/ Portland Town Council]\n* {{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Portland, Isle of|short=x}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-dorset-32013883 Last Ferry Crossing]\n\n{{Dorset}}\n{{SSSIs Dorset biological}}\n{{Isle of Portland}}\n{{Jurassic Coast}}\n{{Viking Invasion of England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Portland, Isle Of}}\n[[Category:Isle of Portland| ]]\n[[Category:Headlands of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Islands of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Liberties of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Peninsulas of England]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Jurassic Coast]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Tied islands]]\n[[Category:Tombolos]]\n[[Category:Natural regions of England]]\n[[Category:Natural regions of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Weymouth and Portland]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Portland (disambiguation)}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|official_name= Portland (Isle of Portland)\n|static_image_name = Flag of Isle of Portland.gif\n|coordinates = {{coord|50.550|-2.440|display=inline,title}}\n|population = 12,400\n|population_ref =<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\">{{cite web| year = 2011 | url = http://www.dorsetforyou.com/index.jsp?articleid=343603 | title=Portland\u2014Dorset For You | publisher = Dorset County Council | accessdate = 14 December 2012}}</ref>{{ref label|estimate|A|A}}\n|civil_parish= Portland\n|unitary_england= [[Dorset (unitary authority)|Dorset]]\n|shire_county = [[Dorset]]\n|region= South West England\n|constituency_westminster= [[South Dorset (UK Parliament constituency)|South Dorset]]\n|post_town= PORTLAND\n|postcode_district = DT5\n|postcode_area= DT\n|dial_code= 01305\n|os_grid_reference= SY690721\n|london_distance_mi = 120\n|london_distance = &nbsp;east north-east\n}}\n\nThe '''Isle of Portland''' is a [[tied island]], {{convert|4|mi|km|0}} long by {{convert|1.7|mi|km|1}} wide, in the [[English Channel]].<ref name=\"Isle of Portland\">{{cite web | year = 2015 | url = http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/471189/Isle-of-Portland | title = Isle of Portland | publisher = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica | accessdate = 27 April 2015}}</ref> Portland is {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} south of the resort of [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]], forming the southernmost point of the county of [[Dorset]], England. A [[barrier beach]] called [[Chesil Beach]] joins it to the mainland. The [[A354 road]] passes down the Portland end of the beach and then over the [[Fleet Lagoon]] by bridge to the mainland. Portland and Weymouth together form the borough of [[Weymouth and Portland]]. The population of Portland is 12,400.\n\nPortland is a central part of the [[Jurassic Coast]], a [[World Heritage Site]] on the Dorset and east [[Devon]] coast, important for its geology and landforms. [[Portland stone]], a [[limestone]] famous for its use in British and world architecture, including [[St Paul's Cathedral]] and the [[United Nations Headquarters]], continues to be quarried here.\n\n[[Portland Harbour]], in between Portland and Weymouth, is one of the largest man-made harbours in the world. The harbour was made by the building of stone [[breakwater (structure)|breakwater]]s between 1848 and 1905. From its inception it was a [[Royal Navy]] base, and played prominent roles during [[World War I|the First]] and [[World War II|Second World Wars]]; ships of the Royal Navy and [[North Atlantic Treaty Organisation|NATO]] countries worked up and exercised in its waters until 1995. The harbour is now a civilian port and popular recreation area, and was used for the [[2012 Olympic Games]].\n\nThe name Portland is used for one of the [[British Sea Areas]], and has been [[Portland (disambiguation)|exported]] as the name of North American and Australian towns.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Uk dor portcastle.JPG|thumb|left|325px|[[Portland Castle]] was built to defend Portland in the 16th century.]]\n\nPortland has been inhabited since at least the [[Mesolithic]] period (the Middle [[Stone Age]])\u2014there is archaeological evidence of Mesolithic inhabitants at the [[Culverwell Mesolithic Site]], near [[Portland Bill]],<ref name=\"Mesolithic\">{{cite web | year = 2002 | url = http://www.gallica.co.uk/celts/portland.htm | title = Mesolithic Site, Portland | publisher = Association for Portland Archaeology | accessdate = 30 July 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070609212653/http://www.gallica.co.uk/celts/portland.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 9 June 2007}}</ref> and of habitation since then. The Romans occupied Portland, reputedly calling it ''Vindelis''.<ref name=\"vindelis\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.uni-mannheim.de/mateo/camenaref/hofmann/hof4/s0773b.html | title = Lexicon Universale | publisher = Universit\u00e4t Mannheim | accessdate = 3 April 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Portland stone\" />\n\nAlthough the beginning of the [[Viking Age]] in England is dated to their raid in 793,<ref name=\"English Heritage\">{{cite web |url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/lindisfarne-priory/history/ |title=History of Lindisfarne Priory|publisher=English Heritage |accessdate=2016-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"Swanton\">Swanton, Michael (1998). ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle''. Psychology Press. {{ISBN|0-415-92129-5}}. p. 57, n. 15.</ref> when they destroyed the [[abbey]] on [[Lindisfarne]], their first documented landing occurred in Portland four years earlier, in 789, as recorded in the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saxons.etrusia.co.uk/vikings_invasions.php|title=What spurred the Viking invasions?|work=Saxons and Vikings in Britain}}</ref> Three lost Viking ships from [[Hordaland]] (the district around [[Hardanger]] fjord in west [[Norway]]) landed at Portland Bill. The king's [[Reeve (England)|reeve]] tried to collect taxes from them, but they killed him and sailed on.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.cn.edu/kwheeler/viking_attacklist.html?showall=1|title=Viking Attacks}}</ref>\n\n[[Rufus Castle]], standing over [[Church Ope Cove]] was built for [[William II of England]] (also known as William Rufus) soon after the conquest of England by his father [[William the Conqueror]].  None of that castle remains; the existing castle dates from the 15th century.\n\nIn 1539 [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII]] ordered the construction of [[Portland Castle]] for defence against attacks by the French; the castle cost \u00a34,964.<ref name=\"portlandcastle\">{{cite web | year = 2000 | url = http://www.thedorsetpage.com/locations/Place/P120.htm | title = Portland, Dorset, England | publisher = The Dorset Page | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> It is one of the best preserved castles from this period, and is opened to the public by the custodians [[English Heritage]].<ref name=\"englishheritage\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/nav.15746 | title = Portland Castle | publisher = English Heritage | accessdate = 30 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the 17th century, chief architect and Surveyor-General to James I, [[Inigo Jones]], surveyed the area and introduced the local [[Portland stone]] to London, using it in his [[Banqueting House, Whitehall]], and for repairs on [[St Paul's Cathedral]].<ref name=\"RhodesStone2013\">{{cite book|first1=Frank H. T.|last1=Rhodes|first2=Richard O.|last2=Stone|title=Language of the Earth|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Rq_fBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA261 |year=2013|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-1-4831-6166-2|page=261}}</ref> His successor, Sir [[Christopher Wren]], the architect and Member of Parliament for nearby Weymouth, used six million tons of white Portland limestone to rebuild destroyed parts of the capital after the [[Great Fire of London]] of 1666. Well-known buildings in the capital, including St Paul's Cathedral<ref name=\"st paul's\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.stpauls.co.uk/page.aspx?theLang=001lngdef&pointerid=32207NnDnfjeCGJ1g2bvy1Jt3FI0gUAP | title = 1710&nbsp;\u2013 Construction is Completed | publisher = Dean and Chapter St Paul's | accessdate = 3 April 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928083501/http://www.stpauls.co.uk/page.aspx?theLang=001lngdef&pointerid=32207NnDnfjeCGJ1g2bvy1Jt3FI0gUAP |archivedate = 28 September 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the eastern front of [[Buckingham Palace]] feature the stone.<ref name=\"buckinghampalace\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page568.asp | title = Buckingham Palace History | publisher = HM Queen Elizabeth II | accessdate = 3 April 2007}}</ref> After the First World War, a [[quarry]] was opened by [[The Crown Estate]] to provide stone for the [[Cenotaph]] in [[Whitehall]] and half a million gravestones for war cemeteries,<ref name=\"Portland stone\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.dorsets.co.uk/Portland/ | title = Portland\u2014Dorset | publisher = Dorset Guide | accessdate = 3 April 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070505011524/http://www.dorsets.co.uk/Portland/ | archive-date = 5 May 2007 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and after the Second World War hundreds of thousands of gravestones were hewn for soldiers who had fallen on the [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]].<ref name=\"Portland stone\" /> [[Portland cement]] has nothing to do with Portland; it was so named due to its similar colour to Portland stone when mixed with lime and sand.<ref name=\"cement\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.cement.org/basics/concretebasics_history.asp | title = History & Manufacture of Portland Cement | publisher = Portland Cement Association | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Porland island map1937.jpg|thumb|right|A map of the Isle of Portland from 1937, showing the railway to [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]]]]\nThere have been railways in Portland since the early 19th century. The [[Merchant's Railway]] was the earliest\u2014it opened in 1826 (one year after the [[Stockton and Darlington railway]]) and ran from the quarries at the north of [[Tophill]] to a pier at [[Castletown, Dorset|Castletown]], from where the Portland stone was shipped around the country.<ref name=\"railways\">{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.johnrnew.demon.co.uk/weyrails.htm | title = Railways of the Weymouth area | publisher = Island Publishing | accessdate = 26 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070403155729/http://www.johnrnew.demon.co.uk/weyrails.htm | archivedate = 3 April 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Portland, an illustrated History\">{{cite web | year =2016 | url = http://www.dovecotepress.com/?product=portland-an-illustrated-historystuart-morris | title = Portland, an Illustrtaed History | publisher = The Dovecote Press | accessdate = 10 October 2016}}</ref>  The [[Portland Branch Railway|Weymouth and Portland Railway]] was laid in 1865, and ran from a station in [[Melcombe Regis]], across the Fleet and along the low isthmus behind Chesil Beach to a station at [[Victoria Square, Portland|Victoria Square]] in [[Chiswell]].<ref name=\"railways2\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=351 | title = Weymouth to Portland Railway, Construction and growth | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 26 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008013056/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=351 |archivedate = 8 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the end of the 19th century the line was extended to the top of the island as the Easton and Church Ope Railway, running through Castletown and ascending the cliffs at East Weares, to loop back north to a station in [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]].<ref name=\"railways\" /> The line closed to passengers in 1952, and the final goods train (and two passenger 'specials') ran in April 1965.<ref name=\"railways2\" />\n\nThe [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution|Royal National Institution for the Preservation of Life from Shipwreck]] stationed a [[Lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]] at Portland in 1826, which was withdrawn in 1851.<ref>{{cite book |last= Denton |first= Tony |title= Handbook 2009 |year= 2009 |publisher= Lifeboat Enthusiasts Society |location= Shrewsbury |page= 59 }}</ref> Coastal flooding has affected Portland's residents and transport for centuries\u2014the only way off the island by land is along the causeway in the lee of Chesil Beach. At times of extreme floods (about every 10 years) this road link is cut by floods. The low-lying village of [[Chiswell]] used to flood on average every 5 years. Chesil Beach occasionally faces severe storms and massive waves, which have a [[fetch (geography)|fetch]] across the Atlantic Ocean.<ref name=\"flooding\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://content.swgfl.org.uk/jurassic/chis10.htm | title = Chiswell case study: The Scheme | publisher = Jurassic Coast | accessdate = 27 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140320175647/http://content.swgfl.org.uk/jurassic/chis10.htm | archivedate = 20 March 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Following two severe flood events in the 1970s, [[Weymouth and Portland]] Borough Council and [[Wessex Water]] decided to investigate the structure of the beach, and [[coastal management]] schemes that could be built to protect Chiswell and the beach road. In the 1980s it was agreed that a scheme to protect against a [[return period|one-in-five-year]] storm would be practicable; it would reduce flood depth and duration in more severe storms.<ref name=\"flooding\"/> [[Coastal management#Hard construction techniques|Hard engineering]] techniques were employed in the scheme, including a [[gabion]] running {{convert|550|m|yd|-1}}<ref name=\"gabion\">{{cite web | year = 2013 | url = http://test.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Chiswell_Gabions_LL_Factsheet_aug12.pdf | title = Chiswell Gabions Flood Alleviation Scheme | publisher = Environment Agency | accessdate = 20 March 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140320172310/http://test.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Chiswell_Gabions_LL_Factsheet_aug12.pdf | archivedate = 20 March 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> to the north of Chiswell, an extended [[sea wall]] in [[Chesil Cove]], and a [[culvert]] running from inside the beach, underneath the beach road and into [[Portland Harbour]], to divert flood water away from low-lying areas.<ref name=\"flooding\"/>\n\n[[Image:uk dor portharbour.JPG|thumb|right|Portland Harbour was home to the [[Royal Navy]]. Their former [[barracks]] are in the foreground.]]\n\nAt the start of the First World War, [[HMS Hood (1891)|HMS ''Hood'']] was sunk in the passage between the southern breakwaters to protect the harbour from torpedo and submarine attack.<ref name=\"HMShood\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/hms_hood.htm | title = Turret Battleship, HMS Hood | publisher = Cranston Fine Arts | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> [[Portland Harbour]] was formed (1848\u20131905) by the construction of breakwaters, but before that the natural anchorage had hosted ships of the [[Royal Navy]] for more than 500 years. It was a centre for Admiralty research into [[asdic]] submarine detection and underwater weapons from 1917 to 1998; the shore base [[HMS Serepta]] was renamed [[RNAS Portland (HMS Osprey)|HMS Osprey]] in 1927.<ref name=\"serepta\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.helis.com/database/?menu=2&tpais=UK&tbase=33&menudiv=1 | title = Portland Base/Heliport History | publisher = helis.com | accessdate = 28 July 2007}}</ref> During the Second World War Portland was the target of heavy bombing, although most warships had moved north as Portland was within enemy striking range across the Channel. [[Mulberry Harbour]] Phoenix Units can be seen at Black Barge beach, near [[Portland Castle]].  Portland was a major embarkation point for Allied forces on [[Normandy landings|D-Day]] in 1944. Early [[helicopter]]s were stationed at Portland in 1946\u20131948, and in 1959 a shallow tidal flat, The Mere, was infilled, and sports fields taken to form a heliport. The station was formally commissioned as HMS Osprey, which then became the largest and busiest military helicopter station in Europe. The base was gradually improved with additional landing areas and one of England's shortest runways, at {{convert|229|m|ft|0}}.<ref name=\"serepta\" />\n\nThe naval base closed after the end of the [[Cold War]] in 1995, and the Royal Naval Air Station closed in 1999, although the runway remained in use for [[Her Majesty's Coastguard]] Search and Rescue flights as MRCC Portland<ref name=\"serepta\" /> until 2014.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2014 | url = http://www.mby.com/news/portland-coastguard-centre-to-close-next-month-mca-confirms-40749 | title = Portland Coastguard centre to close next month, MCA confirms | publisher = mby.com | accessdate = 16 May 2018}}</ref> MRCC Portland's area of responsibility extended midway across the [[English Channel]], and from [[Start Point, Devon|Start Point]] in Devon to the Dorset/[[Hampshire]] border, covering an area of around {{convert|10400|km2|sqmi|-2}}.<ref name=\"coastguard\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.beercoastguard.org/coastguard_rescue_helicoper.htm | title = Coastguard Rescue Helicopter | publisher = Beer Coastguard | accessdate = 28 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930140301/http://www.beercoastguard.org/coastguard_rescue_helicoper.htm |archivedate = 30 September 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The 12 Search and Rescue teams in the Portland area dealt with almost 1000 incidents in 2005.<ref name=\"mrccportland\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.mcga.gov.uk/c4mca/mcga-dops-regional/eastern-region/mcga-dops_rr_east_regional-eastern-region-solent.htm | title = Eastern Region&nbsp;\u2013 Area South | publisher = [[Maritime and Coastguard Agency]] | accessdate = 28 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070806080135/http://www.mcga.gov.uk/c4mca/mcga-dops-regional/eastern-region/mcga-dops_rr_east_regional-eastern-region-solent.htm | archivedate = 6 August 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are still two prisons on Portland: [[The Verne (HM Prison)|HMP The Verne]], which until 1949 was a huge Victorian military fortress, and a Young Offenders' Institution ([[HMYOI]]) on the Grove clifftop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.uk/contacts/prison-finder/portland |title=HMP/YOI Portland information |publisher=Justice.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> This was the original prison ([[HM Prison Portland]]) built for convicts who quarried stone for the Portland Breakwaters from 1848. For a few years until 2005 Britain's only [[prison ship]], [[Weare (HM Prison)|HMP ''The Weare'']], was berthed in the harbour.<ref>{{cite web|first=Steven |last=Morris |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/aug/12/ukcrime.prisonsandprobation |title=Britain's only prison ship ends up on the beach &#124; UK news |newspaper=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:DorsetWeymouthPortland.png|thumb|left|[[Weymouth and Portland]] shown in Dorset]]\n\n== Governance ==\nPortland is an ancient [[royal manor]], and until the 19th century remained a separate [[Liberty (division)|liberty]] within Dorset for administration purposes. It was an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] from 1894 to 1974, until the borough of [[Weymouth and Portland]] formed on 1 April 1974 under the [[Local Government Act 1972]]. This merged the borough of Weymouth and Melcombe Regis with Portland urban district. For [[UK local elections|local elections]] the borough is divided into 15 wards, and three of them cover Portland.<ref name=\"wards\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=620 | title = Ward Map | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 16 December 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224210742/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=620 |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Elections take place in a four-year cycle; one third of the councillors in all but three wards retire or seek re-election in years one, two and three, and county council elections are held in year four.<ref name=\"election cycle\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=618 | title = Electoral Cycles Thirds | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 4 January 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080408031609/http://weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=618 |archivedate = 8 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe mayor of Weymouth and Portland is Ray Banham ([[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]), Kate Wheller ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]) is deputy mayor.<ref name=\"weymouthcouncillors\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://webapps-wpbc.dorsetforyou.com/apps/democracy/councillors.asp | title = WPBC Serving Councillors | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 14 December 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121231143454/http://webapps-wpbc.dorsetforyou.com/apps/democracy/councillors.asp | archivedate = 31 December 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Weymouth, Portland and the [[Purbeck (district)|Purbeck]] district are in the [[South Dorset]] [[United Kingdom constituencies|parliamentary constituency]], created in 1885. The constituency elects one Member of Parliament; the current MP is [[Richard Drax]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]).<ref name=\"drax\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/constituency/1296/dorset-south | title = Dorset South | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | accessdate = 19 June 2010 | year=2010}}</ref> South Dorset, the rest of the [[South West England]], and [[Gibraltar]] are in the [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England constituency]] of the [[European Parliament]].<ref name=\"euparliament\">{{cite web | year = 2004 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=621 | title = European elections | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 16 December 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224210748/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=621 |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWeymouth and Portland have been twinned with the town of [[Holzwickede]] in North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany since 1986,<ref name=\"holzwickede\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | language = German | url = http://testholzwickede.kdvz.de/erleben/kultur_sport_freizeit/sp_auto_424.php | title = St\u00e4dtepartnerschaften in Holzwickede | publisher = Gemeinde Holzwickede | accessdate = 15 December 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224200246/http://testholzwickede.kdvz.de/erleben/kultur_sport_freizeit/sp_auto_424.php |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the French town of [[Louviers]], in the [[departments of France|department]] of [[Eure]] in Normandy, since 1959.<ref name=\"louviers\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | language = French | url = http://www.ville-louviers.fr/ville/associations/jumelages/anglais/jum-anglais.htm | title = Associations de jumelage | publisher = Ville de Louviers | accessdate = 15 December 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224201120/http://www.ville-louviers.fr/ville/associations/jumelages/anglais/jum-anglais.htm | archivedate = 24 December 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The borough and nearby [[Chickerell]] have been a [[Fairtrade Zone]] since 2007.<ref name=\"fairtrade\">{{cite web | year = 2008 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/living/community/pages/fairtrade/home.asp?svid=982 | title = Weymouth & Portland: a Fairtrade Zone | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 7 March 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071029080021/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/living/community/pages/fairtrade/home.asp?svid=982 |archivedate = 29 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[Image:Terraced houses at fortuneswell 2.jpg|right|thumb|Terraced Portland Stone houses in [[Villages of Portland#Fortuneswell|Fortuneswell, Underhill]]]]\n[[Image:PortlandBill&ChesilBeach.jpg|thumb|Isle of Portland from the air]]\nThe Isle of Portland lies in the [[English Channel]], {{convert|3|km|mi|0}} south of [[Wyke Regis]], and {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}} west-southwest of London, at {{coord|50|33|0|N|2|26|24|W| region:GB_type:city}} (50.55,&nbsp;\u22122.44). Portland is situated approximately halfway along the [[UNESCO]] [[Jurassic Coast]] [[World Heritage Site]]; the site includes {{convert|153|km|mi|0}} of the Dorset and east Devon coast that is important for its geology and landforms.<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.jurassiccoast.com/279/visiting-the-coast-31/gateway-towns-146/portland-447.html | title = Portland | publisher = [[Jurassic Coast]] | accessdate = 29 December 2007}}</ref> The [[South West Coast Path]] runs around the coast; it is the United Kingdom's longest [[Long-distance footpaths in the UK|national trail]] at {{convert|1014|km|mi|0}}. Portland is unusual as it is connected to the mainland at [[Abbotsbury]] by [[Chesil Beach]], a [[tombolo]] which runs {{convert|29|km|mi|0}} north-west to [[West Bay, Dorset|West Bay]].<ref name=\"chesil\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.soton.ac.uk/~imw/chesil.htm | title = The Chesil Beach&nbsp;\u2013 General Introduction | publisher = Southampton University | accessdate = 13 August 2007}}</ref> Portland is sometimes defined incorrectly as a tombolo\u2014in fact Portland is a tied island, and Chesil Beach is the tombolo (a spit joined to land at both ends).<ref name=\"tombolo\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.vnc.qld.edu.au/enviro/flinders/land-defns.htm | title = Coastal Landform Definitions | publisher = Villanova College | accessdate = 29 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070714013950/http://www.vnc.qld.edu.au/enviro/flinders/land-defns.htm | archivedate = 14 July 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are eight settlements on Portland, the largest being [[Fortuneswell]] in Underhill and [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]] on Tophill. [[Castletown, Dorset|Castletown]] and [[Chiswell]] are the other villages in Underhill, and [[Weston, Dorset|Weston]], [[Southwell, Dorset|Southwell]], [[Wakeham]] and [[The Grove, Portland|the Grove]] are on the Tophill plateau.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dorsetlife.co.uk/2015/02/a-portrait-of-portland/ |title=A portrait of Portland &#124; Dorset Life - The Dorset Magazine |publisher=Dorset Life |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> Many old buildings are built out of Portland Stone; several parts have been designated Conservation Areas to preserve the unique character the older settlements which date back hundreds of years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.gov.uk/conservation-area/weymouth-and-portland |title=Conservation areas - Weymouth and Portland |publisher=Weymouth & Portland Borough Council |date=2017-09-29 |accessdate=2018-04-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416200757/https://www.dorsetforyou.gov.uk/conservation-area/weymouth-and-portland |archive-date=16 April 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Isle of Portland has been designated by [[Natural England]] as National Character Area 137. It is adjoined by the [[Weymouth Lowlands]] to the north.<ref>[http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/Images/jca137+138_tcm6-5506.pdf ''Isle of Portland/Weymouth Lowlands''] at naturalengland.org.uk. Accessed on 4 April 2013.</ref>\n\n[[Image:Dorset geology.png|thumb|left|upright=1.25|The Isle of Portland lies on Upper [[Oolite]] [[limestone]].]]\n\n=== Geology ===\nGeologically, Portland is separated into two areas; the steeply sloping land at its north end called [[Underhill, Dorset|Underhill]], and the larger, gently sloping land to the south, called [[Tophill]]. [[Portland stone]] lies under Tophill; the strata decline at a shallow angle of around 1.5 degrees, from a height of {{convert|151|m|ft|0}} near [[Verne (HM Prison)|the Verne]] in the north, to just above sea level at [[Portland Bill]].<ref name=\"geology\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.soton.ac.uk/~imw/portnew.htm#cross | title = General Geology | publisher = Southampton University | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> The geology of Underhill is different to Tophill; Underhill lies on a steep [[escarpment]] composed of Portland Sand, lying above a thicker layer of [[Kimmeridge Clay]], which extends to Chesil Beach and Portland Harbour. This Kimmeridge Clay has resulted in a series of landslides, forming West Weares and East Weares.<ref name=\"geology\" />\n\n{{convert|2.4|km|1}} underneath south Dorset lies a layer of [[Triassic]] [[rock salt]], and Portland is one of four locations in the United Kingdom where the salt is thick enough to create stable cavities.<ref name=\"echogas\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/local/display.var.1881457.0.island_may_be_key_gas_supplier.php | title = Island may be key gas supplier | publisher = Dorset Echo | accessdate = 5 December 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"portlandgas1\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.portland-gas.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=48&Itemid=105 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070729214525/http://www.portland-gas.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=48&Itemid=105 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 29 July 2007 | title = Portland gas storage project | publisher = Portland Gas | accessdate = 5 December 2007 }}</ref> Portland Gas applied to [[salt mine|excavate]] 14 caverns to store {{convert|1000000000|m3|cuft}} of natural gas, which is one percent of the UK's total annual demand.<ref name=\"echogas\" /><ref name=\"portlandgas1\" /> It was proposed that the caverns should be connected to the National gas grid at [[Mappowder]] via a {{convert|37|km|mi|adj=on}} pipeline.<ref name=\"echogas\" /><ref name=\"portlandgas1\" /> Plans had it that the surface facilities should be complete to store the first gas in 2011, and the entire cavern space available for storage in winter 2013.<ref name=\"portlandgas1\" /> As part of the \u00a3350&nbsp;million scheme,<ref name=\"echogas\" /> the [[Grade II listed]] former [[The Old Engine Shed, Portland|Old Engine Shed]] would be converted into a \u00a31.5&nbsp;million educational centre with a caf\u00e9 and an exhibition space about the geology of Portland.<ref name=\"educationcentre\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/local/display.var.1881211.0.island_may_get_a_1_5m_visitor_centre.php | title = Island may get a \u00a31.5m visitor centre | publisher = Dorset Echo | accessdate = 5 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Portland Bill ===\n[[Image:Portland Bill Lighthouse 2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Portland Bill Lighthouse]] and visitors' centre]]\n[[Portland Bill]] is the southern tip of the island of Portland. The Bill has three lighthouse towers: [[Old Higher Lighthouse|The Higher Lighthouse]] is now a dwelling and holiday apartments; [[Old Lower Lighthouse|the Lower Lighthouse]] is now a bird observatory and field centre providing records of bird migration and accommodation for visitors, which opened in 1961.<ref>Stuart Morris, 2016 ''Portland, an Illustrated History'' The Dovecote Press, [[Wimborne]], Dorset: {{ISBN|978-0-9955462-0-2}}</ref> The [[Portland Bill Lighthouse|white and red lighthouse]] on Bill Point replaced the Higher and Lower Lighthouses in 1906. It is a prominent and much photographed feature; an important landmark for ships passing the headland and its [[tidal race]]. The current lighthouse was refurbished in 1996 and became remotely controlled. It now contains a visitors' centre giving information and guided tours of the lighthouse.<ref name=\"lighthouse\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.trinityhouse.co.uk/interactive/gallery/portland_bill.html | title = Portland Bill Lighthouse | publisher = Trinity House | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}. * Stuart Morris, 2016 ''Portland, an Illustrated History'' The Dovecote Press, [[Wimborne]], Dorset: {{ISBN|978-0-9955462-0-2}}</ref> As of June 2009, the lighthouse uses a 1&nbsp;kW metal-halide US-made lamp with an operational life of about 4000 hours, or 14 months.\n\nPortland Ledge is an underwater extension of Portland Stone into the English Channel at a place where the depth of Channel is 20 to 40 metres (about 10 to 20 fathoms). Tidal flow is disrupted by the feature; at 10 metres (about 5 fathoms) deep and {{convert|2.4|km|nmi|1}} long, it causes a tidal race to the south of Portland Bill, the so-called ''Portland Race''.<ref name=\"shambles\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.soton.ac.uk/~imw/portnew.htm#offshore | title = Offshore Geology | publisher = Southampton University | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> The current only stops for brief periods during the {{frac|12|1|2}}-hour tidal cycle and can reach {{convert|4|m/s|kn|0}} at the spring tide of {{convert|2|m|0}}.<ref name=\"shambles\" />\n\n=== Ecology ===\n[[Image:PortlandCoast.JPG|thumb|right|Portland's cliffs and quarries have extensive specialised flora and fauna.]]\nDue to its isolated coastal location, the Isle of Portland has an extensive range of [[flora]] and [[fauna]]; the coastline and disused quarries are designated as [[Sites of Special Scientific Interest]].<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\" /><ref name=\"wildlife\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=546|title=Portland wildlife|year=2007|publisher=Weymouth & Portland Borough Council |accessdate=27 July 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513165029/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=546|archivedate=13 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sea and migratory birds occupy the cliffs in different seasons, sometimes these include rare species which draw ornithologists from around the country.<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\" /><ref name=\"fauna\" /> Rare visitors to the surrounding seas include dolphins, seals and basking sharks.<ref name=\"wildlife\" /> Chesil Beach is one of only two sites in Britain where the scaly cricket can be found; unlike any other cricket it is wingless and does not sing or hop.<ref name=\"fauna\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=542 | title = Chesil Beach | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 27 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070513190720/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=542 |archivedate = 13 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Ten British Primitive goats were introduced to the East Weares part of the island to control scrub in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portlandcp.org.uk/island/WildlifeNewsletter.pdf|title=Wildlife on Portland|date=Spring 2008|publisher=Heights Hotel and Swarovski Optik |accessdate=18 March 2012|format=PDF}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe comparatively warm and sunny climate allows species of plants to thrive which do not on the mainland. The limestone soil has low nutrient levels; hence smaller species of wild flowers and grasses are able to grow in the absence of larger species.<ref name=\"wildlife\" /> Portland sea lavender can be found on the higher sea cliffs; unique to Portland, it is one of the United Kingdom's rarest plants.<ref name=\"flora\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=543 | title = Coastal Flora & Fauna | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 27 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070513164925/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=543 |archivedate = 13 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The wild flowers and plants make an excellent habitat for butterflies; over half of the British Isles' 57 butterfly species can be seen on Portland, including varieties that migrate from mainland Europe.<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\" /> Species live on Portland that are rare in the United Kingdom, including the limestone race of the [[silver-studded blue]].<ref name=\"butterflies\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=541 | title = Portland Butterflies | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 27 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070513190734/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=541 |archivedate = 13 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate ===\n[[Image:Weymouth Climatic Graph.png|right|thumb|upright=1.75|Climatic [[ergograph]] for the nearby [[Wyke Regis]] weather station]]\nThe mild seas which almost surround the tied island produce a [[temperate]] climate ([[Humid temperate climate|K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Cfb'') with a small variation in daily and annual temperatures. The average annual mean temperature from 1981 to 2010 was {{Convert|11.2|C|F|1}}.<ref name=\"annualmean\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/portland#?tab=climateTables | title = Climate \u2013 Chosen location: Portland | publisher = [[Met Office]] | accessdate = 5 December 2012}}</ref> The warmest month is August, which has an average [[temperature|temperature range]] of {{convert|14.5|to|19.3|C|F}}, and the coolest is February, which has a range of {{convert|4.0|to|8.0|C|F}}.<ref name=\"annualmean\" /> Maximum and minimum temperatures throughout the year are above England's average,<ref name=\"englandclimate\">{{cite web|year=2001 |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/england.html |title=England 1971\u20132000 averages |publisher=Met Office |accessdate=10 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605024000/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/england.html |archivedate= 5 June 2011 }}</ref> and Portland is in [[Hardiness zone#American Horticultural Society heat zones|AHS Heat zone 1]].{{ref label|ahs1|B|B}} Mean [[sea surface temperatures]] range from {{convert|7.0|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|1}} in February to {{convert|17.2|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|1}} in August; the annual mean is {{convert|11.8|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|1}}.<ref name=\"seatemperatures\"/>\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Isle of Portland [[climate|climatic]] averages\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 8.4\n|Feb high C = 8.0\n|Mar high C = 9.4\n|Apr high C = 11.5\n|May high C = 14.3\n|Jun high C = 16.8\n|Jul high C = 18.8\n|Aug high C = 19.3\n|Sep high C = 17.8\n|Oct high C = 14.8\n|Nov high C = 11.6\n|Dec high C = 9.2\n|year high C = 13.4\n\n|Jan mean C = 6.6\n|Feb mean C = 6.0\n|Mar mean C = 7.3\n|Apr mean C = 9.0\n|May mean C = 11.7\n|Jun mean C = 14.3\n|Jul mean C = 16.4\n|Aug mean C = 16.9\n|Sep mean C = 15.4\n|Oct mean C = 12.8\n|Nov mean C = 9.7\n|Dec mean C = 7.3\n|year mean C = 11.2\n\n|Jan low C = 4.7\n|Feb low C = 4.0\n|Mar low C = 5.2\n|Apr low C = 6.4\n|May low C = 9.1\n|Jun low C = 11.8\n|Jul low C = 14.0\n|Aug low C = 14.5\n|Sep low C = 13.0\n|Oct low C = 10.8\n|Nov low C = 7.7\n|Dec low C = 5.4\n|year low C = 8.9\n\n|Jan sun =64.6\n|Feb sun =86.7\n|Mar sun =126.3\n|Apr sun =191.0\n|May sun =225.0\n|Jun sun =226.5\n|Jul sun =236.9\n|Aug sun =218.0\n|Sep sun =167.2\n|Oct sun =115.1\n|Nov sun =82.0\n|Dec sun =59.7\n|year sun = 1798.9\n<!-- NOT RECOGNIZED BY THE TEMPLATE\n|Jan mean sea surf C = 7.8\n|Feb mean sea surf C = 7.0\n|Mar mean sea surf C = 7.5\n|Apr mean sea surf C = 8.8\n|May mean sea surf C = 11.0\n|Jun mean sea surf C = 13.3\n|Jul mean sea surf C = 15.8\n|Aug mean sea surf C = 17.2\n|Sep mean sea surf C = 16.7\n|Oct mean sea surf C = 14.7\n|Nov mean sea surf C = 12.3\n|Dec mean sea surf C = 9.8\n|year mean sea surf C = 11.8\n -->\n|Jan rain mm =67.3\n|Feb rain mm =53.1\n|Mar rain mm =52.3\n|Apr rain mm = 46.9\n|May rain mm =44.1\n|Jun rain mm =39.3\n|Jul rain mm =35.1\n|Aug rain mm =41.4\n|Sep rain mm =46.9\n|Oct rain mm =81.6\n|Nov rain mm =81.6\n|Dec rain mm =78.2\n|year rain mm = 667.9\n\n|unit rain days = 1&nbsp;mm\n|Jan rain days =12.4\n|Feb rain days =9.8\n|Mar rain days = 9.6\n|Apr rain days =8.5\n|May rain days = 8.2\n|Jun rain days =6.6\n|Jul rain days = 6.6\n|Aug rain days =7.1\n|Sep rain days =7.8\n|Oct rain days = 11.5\n|Nov rain days =12.4\n|Dec rain days =12.0\n|year rain days = 112.5\n\n| source 1 = 1981&ndash;2010 averages for the Isle of Portland climate station and Weymouth Cefas station. Sources: [[Met Office]]<ref name=\"MetOffice\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/portland#?tab=climateTables | title = Climate - Chosen location: Portland | publisher = Met Office | accessdate = 2012-12-05}}</ref> and [[Cefas]]<ref name=\"seatemperatures\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.cefas.co.uk/data/sea-temperature-and-salinity-trends/presentation-of-results/station-24-weymouth.aspx | title = Cefas Station 24: Weymouth | publisher = [[Cefas|The Centre for Environment Fisheries & Aquaculture Science]] | accessdate = 2012-12-05 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070613213637/http://www.cefas.co.uk/data/sea-temperature-and-salinity-trends/presentation-of-results/station-24-weymouth.aspx | archivedate = 13 June 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe mild seas that surround Portland act to keep night-time temperatures above freezing, making winter frost rare: on average 9.6 days per year&nbsp;\u2014 this is far below the United Kingdom's average annual total of 55.6 days of frost.<ref name=\"annualmean\" /><ref name=\"UKaverages\" /> Days with snow lying are equally rare: on average zero to six days per year;<ref name=\"metofficesnow\">{{cite web|year=2001 |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/dl/17.gif |title=Met Office UK snow lying days |publisher=Met Office |accessdate=18 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809125155/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/dl/17.gif |archivedate= 9 August 2007 }}</ref> almost all winters have no more than one day with snow lying. It may snow or [[rain and snow mixed|sleet]] in winter, yet it almost never settles on the ground\u2014coastal areas in [[South West England]] such as Portland generally experience the mildest winters in the UK.<ref name=\"metofficewinter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/tmean/16.gif |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531061625/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/tmean/16.gif |archive-date=2010-05-31 |accessdate=10 December 2016 |publisher=Met Office |year=2001 |title=Mean Temperature (\u00b0C) Winter Average 1971-2000}}</ref> Portland is less affected by the Atlantic storms that [[Devon]] and [[Cornwall]] experience. The [[growing season]] lasts for more than 310 days per year,<ref name=\"growingseason\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/#?tab=climateMaps | title = Growing season length \u2013 Annual average: 1971\u20132000 | publisher = Met Office | accessdate = 5 December 2012}}</ref>{{ref label|growingseason|D|D}} and the borough is in [[Hardiness zone]] 9.<ref name=\"hardinesszones\">{{cite web | year = 1999 | url = http://www.gardenweb.com/zones/europe/ | title = Hardiness Zone Map for Europe | publisher = GardenWeb | accessdate = 20 June 2007}}</ref>{{ref label|hardinesszone|E|E}}\n\nWeymouth and Portland, and the rest of the south coast,<ref name=\"metofficeengland\">{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/location/england/index.html | title = Met Office: English climate | publisher = Met Office | accessdate = 6 November 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061117202818/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/location/england/index.html |archivedate = 17 November 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> has the sunniest climate in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"jurassiccoast\" /><ref name=\"sunshine\">{{cite news | url = http://property.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/property/buying_and_selling/article2875491.ece | title = Bring me sunshine | publisher = [[Times Online]] | accessdate = 8 March 2008 | location=London | first1=Robert | last1=Penn | first2=Antony | last2=Woodward | date=18 November 2007}}</ref> Portland averaged 1798.9 hours of sunshine annually between 1981 and 2010,<ref name=\"annualmean\" /> which is 41% of the maximum possible,{{ref label|sunshine|C|C}} and 34% above the [[Climate of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom average]] of 1339.7 hours.<ref name=\"UKaverages\">{{cite web|year=2001 |url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/uk.html |title=UK 1971\u20132000 averages |publisher=Met Office |accessdate=4 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705140124/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/uk.html |archivedate= 5 July 2009 }}</ref> December is the cloudiest month (59.7 hours of sunshine), October and November the joint wettest ({{Convert|81.6|mm|in|1}} of rain) and July is the sunniest and driest month (236.9 hours of sunshine, {{Convert|35.1|mm|in|1}} of rain).<ref name=\"annualmean\" /> Sunshine totals in all months are well above the United Kingdom average,<ref name=\"UKaverages\" /> and monthly rainfall totals throughout the year are less than the UK average, particularly in summer;<ref name=\"UKaverages\" /> this summer minimum of rainfall is not experienced away from the south coast of England.<ref name=\"metofficeengland\" /> The average annual rainfall of {{convert|667.9|mm|in|1}} is well below the UK average of {{convert|1125|mm|in|1}}.<ref name=\"UKaverages\" />\n\n== Demography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"float:right; line-height:1.1em; border:1px #000; margin-left:0; text-align:right;\"\n|-\n! Religion\n! %<ref name=\"WPreligion\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-286262 | title = 2011 Census, Key Statistics for Local Authorities in England and Wales | publisher = [[Office for National Statistics]] | accessdate = 16 December 2007}}</ref>{{ref label|weymouthandportland|F|F}}\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Buddhism|Buddhist]]\n|0.4\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |Christian\n|61.0\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Hinduism|Hindu]]\n|0.1\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Jewish]]\n|0.1\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Muslim]]\n|0.5\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Irreligion|No religion]]\n|29.3\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[List of religions|Other]]\n|0.7\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |[[Sikhism|Sikh]]\n|0.1\n|- style=\"line-height: 1.1em\"\n|align=left |Not stated\n|7.9\n|}\n\n{| class=\"toc\" border=\"1\" style=\"float:right; border-collapse:collapse; margin-right:10pt; margin-top:1em;\"\n|-\n!Age!!Percentage<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" />\n|-\n||0\u201315||align=right|18.1\n|-\n||16\u201317||align=right|2.4\n|-\n||18\u201344||align=right|33.5\n|-\n||45\u201359||align=right|21.9\n|-\n||60\u201384||align=right|21.7\n|-\n||85+||align=right|2.3\n|}\n\n{| class=\"toc\" border=\"1\" style=\"float:right; border-collapse:collapse; margin-right:10pt; margin-top:1em; margin-left:1em; margin-bottom:2em;\"\n|-\n!Year!!Population<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" />\n|-\n||1971||align=right|12,330\n|-\n||1981||align=right|12,410\n|-\n||1991||align=right|13,190\n|-\n||2001||align=right|12,800\n|-\n||2010||align=right|12,400{{ref label|estimate|A|A}}\n|}\n\nThe mid-year population of Portland in 2010 was 12,400;{{ref label|estimate|A|A}} this figure has remained around twelve to thirteen thousand since the 1970s. In 2010 there were 5,786 dwellings in an area of {{convert|11.5|km2|acre|-1}}, giving an approximate population density of 1100 people per km<sup>2</sup> (4.5 per acre).<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" /> The population is almost entirely native to England\u201494.9 percent of residents are of white British ethnicity, well above the England and Wales average of 80.5 percent.<ref name=\"WPreligion\" /> The average price of a detached house on Portland in 2010 was [[GBP|\u00a3]]194,200; [[terraced house]]s are cheaper, at \u00a3149,727, and an apartment or [[Maisonette (apartment)|maisonette]] costs \u00a3110,500.<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" />{{ref label|julysep|G|G}}\n\nCrime rates are below average\u2014there were 5.4 burglaries per 1000 households in 2009 and 2010; which is lower than [[South West England]] (7.6 per 1000) and significantly lower than [[England and Wales]] (11.6 per 1000).<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" /> Unemployment levels are very low, at 1.9 percent in July 2011,<ref name=\"dorsetforyou\" /> compared to the United Kingdom average of 7.7 percent.<ref name=\"unemployment\">{{cite web | year = 2012 | url = http://www.statistics.gov.uk/cci/nugget.asp?id=12 | title = All releases of Labour Market Statistics | publisher = [[Office for National Statistics]] | accessdate = 14 December 2012}}</ref> The most common religious identity in Weymouth and Portland is Christianity, at 61.0 percent, which is slightly above the [[Religion in the United Kingdom#Statistics|England and Wales average]] of 59.3 percent.<ref name=\"WPreligion\" /> The next-largest sector is those with no religion, at 29.3 percent, also slightly above the average of 25.1 percent.<ref name=\"WPreligion\" />\n\n== Transport ==\n[[Image:Dorset transport.png|thumb|right|upright=1.75|The [[A354 road|A354]] links Portland to the main road network and other transport services in Weymouth.]]\nThe [[A354 road]] is the only land access to Portland, via Ferry Bridge, connecting to [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]] and to the wider road network at the [[A35 road|A35]] [[trunk road]] in [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]]. It runs from [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]], splitting into a northbound section through [[Chiswell]] and a southbound section through [[Fortuneswell]], then along [[Chesil Beach]] and across a bridge to the mainland in [[Wyke Regis]]. Formerly the [[Portland Branch Railway]] also crossed to the island. The corridor is now a traffic-free walking and cycle path.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sustrans.org.uk/ncn/map/route/route-26|title=Route 26|publisher=Sustrans |access-date=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nLocal buses are run by [[FirstGroup]], with services to Weymouth.<ref name=\"firstbus\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.firstgroup.com/ukbus/southwest/dorset/timetables/index.php | title = Dorset Timetables | publisher = First Group | accessdate = 6 January 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.today/20070811131154/http://www.firstgroup.com/ukbus/southwest/dorset/timetables/index.php | archivedate = 11 August 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Weymouth is the hub for south Dorset bus routes, with services to Dorchester and local villages.<ref name=\"firstbus\" /> Weymouth is connected to towns and villages along the [[Jurassic Coast]] by the Jurassic Coast Bus service, which runs for {{convert|142|km|mi|0}} from [[Exeter]] to [[Poole]], through [[Sidford]], [[Beer, Devon|Beer]], [[Seaton, Devon|Seaton]], [[Lyme Regis]], [[Charmouth]], [[Bridport]], [[Abbotsbury]], Weymouth, [[Wool, Dorset|Wool]], and [[Wareham, Dorset|Wareham]].<ref name=\"coastbus\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.jurassiccoast.com/283/visiting-the-coast-31/getting-to-and-around-the-jurassic-coast-148/jurassic-coast-bus-service-464.html | title = Jurassic Coast Bus Service | publisher = Jurassic Coast | accessdate = 6 January 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070826183226/http://www.jurassiccoast.com/283/visiting-the-coast-31/getting-to-and-around-the-jurassic-coast-148/jurassic-coast-bus-service-464.html | archive-date = 26 August 2007 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Trains run from Weymouth to London, [[Southampton]] and [[Bristol]], but ferries no longer transport passengers to the French port of [[St Malo]] and the [[Channel Islands]] of [[Guernsey]] and [[Jersey]].<ref name=\"used>{{cite web | year = 2015 | url = hhttps://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-dorset-32013883 | title = used to go | publisher = BBC News | accessdate = 23 March 2015 |</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nSt George's Community Primary School is located in [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.schoolguide.co.uk/schools/st-georges-community-primary-school-portland |title=St George's Community Primary School review |publisher=School Guide |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> The only other school on Portland is the [[Atlantic Academy Portland|Atlantic Academy]], an all-through school for pupils aged 3 to 19 based at two different sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantic-aspirations.org/268/welcome |title=Welcome - Atlantic Academy Isle of Portland |publisher=Atlantic-aspirations.org |date=2018-04-10 |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> Formerly known as the Isle of Portland Aldridge Community Academy, it formed in 2012 by merging four primary schools and one secondary school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/10184563.VIPs_to_attend_handover_of_buildings_to_Portland_Academy/ |title=VIPs to attend handover of buildings to Portland Academy &#124; Bournemouth Echo |publisher=Bournemouthecho.co.uk |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\nSome students commute to [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]] or [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]] to study [[A-Level]]s, or to attend other secondary schools nearby. [[Weymouth College]] in [[Melcombe Regis]] is the nearest [[further education]] college, which has around 7,500 students from [[south west England]] and overseas,<ref name=\"weymouthcollege\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.ac.uk/the-college/welcome.html | title = About Us | publisher = Weymouth College | accessdate = 4 January 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080530161535/http://www.weymouth.ac.uk/the-college/welcome.html | archivedate = 30 May 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> about 1500 studying A-Level courses.<ref name=\"sixthform\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://localinfo.dorsetecho.co.uk/li/secondary_schools_a_level.in.Weymouth | title = Secondary Schools (A-Level) in Weymouth | publisher = Dorset Echo | accessdate = 4 January 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071030134924/http://localinfo.dorsetecho.co.uk/li/secondary_schools_a_level.in.Weymouth | archivedate = 30 October 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n=== Sport and recreation ===\n[[Image:Uk dor sailingacademy.JPG|thumb|right|[[Weymouth and Portland National Sailing Academy]]]]\nIn 2000, the [[Weymouth and Portland National Sailing Academy]] was built in Osprey Quay in Underhill as a centre for sailing in the United Kingdom. [[Weymouth Bay|Weymouth and Portland's waters]] were credited by the [[Royal Yachting Association]] as the best in Northern Europe.<ref name=\"wpnsa\">{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/London2012/home.asp?svid=14 | title = 2012 Olympic Games sailing venue | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 12 November 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061231110947/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/London2012/home.asp?svid=14 |archivedate = 31 December 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> Weymouth and Portland regularly host local, national and international sailing events in their waters; these include the J/24 World Championships in 2005, trials for the 2004 Athens Olympics, the ISAF World Championship 2006, the BUSA Fleet Racing Championships, and the RYA Youth National Championships.<ref name=\"wpnsaevents\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url= http://www.wpnsa.org.uk/pressreleases.htm | title = Press Releases 2006 | publisher = Weymouth & Portland National Sailing Academy | accessdate = 12 November 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061202013033/http://www.wpnsa.org.uk/pressreleases.htm |archivedate = 2 December 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the WPNSA was selected to host sailing events at the [[2012 Summer Olympic Games|2012 Olympic Games]]\u2014mainly because the Academy had recently been built, so no new venue would have to be provided.<ref name=\"2012chosen\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/4653721.stm | title = Sailing town's joy at Olympic win | publisher = BBC | accessdate = 7 January 2008 | date=6 July 2005}}</ref> However, as part of the [[South West of England Regional Development Agency]]'s plans to redevelop Osprey Quay, a new 600-berth marina and an extension with more on-site facilities were built.<ref name=\"portlandmarina\">{{cite web |year = 2007 | url = http://www.portlandmarina.co.uk | title = Dean and Reddyhoff Marina | publisher = Dean and Reddyhoff Limited | accessdate = 26 March 2007}}</ref> Construction was scheduled between October 2007 and the end of 2008, and with its completion and formal opening on 11 June 2009, the venue became the first of the 2012 Olympic Games to be completed.<ref name=\"wpnsaextension\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/6246176.stm | title = New Olympic marina plan approved |publisher= [[BBC]] |accessdate= 27 June 2007 |date=27 June 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= 2012 work completed at WPNSA |url= http://www.rya.org.uk/newsevents/news/Pages/2012sailingvenueofficially.aspx | publisher = [[Royal Yachting Association]] | year = 2009 | accessdate = 10 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Sailing rivals use Olympic venue | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/8193246.stm | publisher = BBC News | accessdate = 10 August 2009 | date=10 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = First 2012 Olympic venue unveiled | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/7753734.stm | publisher = BBC News | accessdate = 30 September 2009 | date=28 November 2008}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|NyBEyROnlCg|Video of HM The Queen visiting the Sailing Academy at YouTube}}</ref>\n\nWeymouth Bay and Portland Harbour are used for other water sports&nbsp;\u2013 the reliable wind is favourable for [[windsurfing|wind]] and [[kitesurfing|kite-surfing]]. Chesil Beach and Portland Harbour are used regularly for angling, scuba diving to shipwrecks, snorkelling, canoeing, and swimming.<ref name=\"watersports\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/Leisure/Watersports/home.asp?svid=69 | title = Watersports in Weymouth and Portland | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 12 November 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061010232523/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/Leisure/Watersports/home.asp?svid=69 |archivedate = 10 October 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> The limestone cliffs and quarries are used for [[rock climbing]]; Portland has areas for [[bouldering]] and deep water soloing, however [[sport climbing]] with bolt protection is the most common style.<ref name=\"rock climbing\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.rockfax.com/databases/results_area.html?id=5 | title = World Rock Climbing Information: Portland | publisher = Rockfax | accessdate = 19 May 2007}}</ref> Since June 2003 the [[South West Coast Path]] [[National Trail]] has included {{convert|21.3|km|mi|1}} of coastal walking around the Isle of Portland, including following the A354 Portland Beach Road twice.<ref>{{cite book|last=South West Coast Path Association|authorlink=South West Coast Path Association|title=South West Coast Path 2009 Guide|publisher=SWCPA|year=2009|page=94|isbn=978-0-907055-15-0}}</ref>\n\nIsle of Portland has a [[Non-League football]] club [[Portland United F.C.]] who play at Grove Corner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portlandutdfc.co.uk/club-info/new-grove-corner/ |title=Portland United FC |publisher=Portlandutdfc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref> They also have a youth set up called Portland United youth football Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familyinformationdirectory.dorsetforyou.gov.uk/kb5/dorset/fsd/service.page?id=1pzil8E_wfI |title=Portland United Youth Football Club &#124; Dorset FID |publisher=Familyinformationdirectory.dorsetforyou.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Rabbits ===\n[[Image:PortlandQuarry.jpg|thumb|right|Accidents in Portland's quarries led to a fear of the word ''rabbit''.]]\nRabbits have long been associated with bad luck on Portland. Use of the name is still taboo\u2014the creatures are often referred to as \"underground mutton\", \"long-eared furry things\" or just \"bunnies\".<ref name=\"wallaceandgromit\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/4318710.stm | title = Wallace and Gromit spook island | publisher = BBC | accessdate = 26 July 2007 | date=7 October 2005}}</ref> The origin of this superstition is obscure (there is no record of it before the 1920s) but it is believed to derive from quarry workers. They would see rabbits emerging from their burrows immediately before a rock fall and blame them for increasing the risk of dangerous, sometimes deadly, [[landslide]]s.<ref name=\"rabbits\" /> If a rabbit was seen in a quarry, the workers would go home for the day, until the safety of the area had been assured.<ref name=\"wallaceandgromit\" />\n\nToday older Portland residents are 'offended' (sometimes for the benefit of tourists) by the mention of rabbits;<ref name=\"rabbits\">{{cite web | year = 2006 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=784 | title = Rabbits, the Portland taboo word | publisher = Weymouth & Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 26 July 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071024070726/http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=784 |archivedate = 24 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> this superstition came to national attention in October 2005 when a special batch of advertisement posters were made for the [[Wallace and Gromit]] film, ''[[Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit|The Curse of the Were-Rabbit]]''. Out of respect for local beliefs the adverts omitted the word 'rabbit' and replaced the film's title with the phrase ''\"Something bunny is going on\"''.<ref name=\"wallaceandgromit\" />\n\n=== Literature ===\n[[Thomas Hardy]] described Portland as \"the peninsula carved by Time out of a single stone\", and named it the ''Isle of Slingers'' and ''Isle of the Race'' in his Wessex novels; it was the main setting of ''[[The Well-Beloved]]'' (1897), and was featured in ''[[The Trumpet-Major]]'' (1880).<ref name=\"Orel1990\">{{cite book|first=H.|last=Orel|title=Thomas Hardy's Personal Writings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XMleCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA263|year= 1990|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-0-230-37371-6|page=263}}</ref><ref name=\"slingers\">{{cite web | year = 2007 | url = http://www.lymeregis.com/hardy_country/ | title = Thomas Hardy County and the Hardy Trail | publisher = Lyme Regis Tourist Information | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref> The cottage that now houses [[Portland Museum, Dorset|Portland Museum]] was the inspiration for the heroine's house in ''The Well-Beloved''. Portlanders were expert stone-throwers in the defence of their land, and Hardy's ''Isle of Slingers'' is heavily based on Portland; the ''Street of Wells'' representing Fortuneswell and ''The Beal'' Portland Bill.  Hardy also called Portland the ''Gibraltar of the North'', with reference to its similarities with [[Gibraltar]]; its physical geography, isolation, comparatively mild climate, and [[Underhill, Dorset|Underhill]]'s winding streets.<ref name=\"wellbeloved\">{{cite web | authorlink = [[Thomas Hardy]] | year = 2007 | url = http://www.fullbooks.com/The-Well-Beloved1.html | title = The Well-Beloved by Thomas Hardy | publisher = Full Books | accessdate = 26 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Hilaire Belloc]]'s book ''The Cruise of the \"''Nona''\"'' is about sailing near Portland, and the reflections it occasions. He describes Portland Race as \"the master terror of our world\", and says \"...&nbsp;if you were to make a list of all the things which Portland Race has swallowed up, it would rival [[Orcus]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/719165/UK-The-Gibraltar-of-Wessex.html |title=UK: The Gibraltar of Wessex |publisher=Telegraph |date=2001-07-14 |accessdate=2018-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Charlie|last=Connelly|title=Attention All Shipping: A Journey Round the Shipping Forecast|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27urnq0h7OAC&pg=PT88|year=2011|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-0-7481-3187-7|page=88}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Museums Without Walls'', [[Jonathan Meades]] declares that \"Portland is a bulky chunk of geological, social, topographical and demographic weirdness. It is the obverse of a beauty spot. 'Beauty' in this construction implies the picturesque. Portland is gloriously bereft of this quality. It is awesome. There is nothing pretty about it.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KWsuCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT40|title=Museum Without Walls|authorlink=Jonathan Meades}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Warlord Chronicles]]'' (1995\u201397), [[Bernard Cornwell]] makes Portland the [[Isle of the Dead (mythology)|Isle of the Dead]], a place of internal exile, where the causeway was guarded to keep the 'dead' (people suffering insanity) from crossing [[Fleet Lagoon|the Fleet]] and returning to the mainland. No historical evidence exists to support this idea.<ref name=\"isleofthedead\">{{cite web | year = 1999 | url = http://www.britishdowsers.org/EEG_site/archive/articles/aua2001_issue24/isleofdead_JHarvey_m.htm | title = The Isle of the Dead | publisher = British Society of Dowsers | accessdate = 30 July 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930021015/http://www.britishdowsers.org/EEG_site/archive/articles/aua2001_issue24/isleofdead_JHarvey_m.htm | archivedate = 30 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Portland Chronicles series of four children's books, set on and around Portland and Weymouth and written by local author Carol Hunt, draw on local history to explore a seventeenth century world of smuggling, witchcraft, piracy and local intrigue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rovingpress.co.uk/PortlandSeaDragon.html |title=Portland Sea Dragon |publisher=Roving Press |date=2 July 2013 |accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Louis L'Amour]] novel ''[[To the Far Blue Mountains]]'' the novel's main character, [[Barnabas Sackett]], hides in [[Cave Hole, Portland|Cave Hole]] at the Bill of Portland before meeting a sailing ship in an attempt to escape from England.\n\n''[[Pink Pippos of Portland]]'', a children's storybook about nearby [[Chesil Beach]] was written by Portland author [[Sandra Fretwell]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Joanna |title=Page-turner is a family affair |url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/1768414.Page-turner_is_a_family_affair/ |website=Dorset Echo |accessdate=12 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Vernacular ===\n''Bunnies'': ([[Isle of Portland#Rabbits|see above]]).\n\n''Kimberlin'': slang for any 'strangers' who live on the island but are not from the island.<ref>Fido Lunettes (nom de plume), 1825, An Historical and Descriptive Account of the Peninsula of Portland from the Earliest to the Present Time, p 48 summary in The Portland Year Book and Island Record 1905, reprinted Portland Museum, 2004. * Stuart Morris, 2016 ''Portland, an Illustrated History'' The Dovecote Press, [[Wimborne]], Dorset: {{ISBN|978-0-9955462-0-2}}</ref>\n\n''Portland screw'': [[fossil]] [[mollusc]] (''[[Aptyxiella portlandica]]'') with a long screw-like shell or its cast.<ref name=\"Portland Stone\">{{cite web | year = 2000 | url = http://iq.learningstone.net/p2/nf/bob_ford/briefing_pack/portland_stone.php | title = The Independent Quarry Research Project | publisher = Portland Quarry and Sculpture Trust | accessdate = 21 July 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100202202257/http://iq.learningstone.net/p2/nf/bob_ford/briefing_pack/portland_stone.php | archive-date = 2 February 2010 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Notable people==\n* Lead singer of rock band [[Art Brut]], [[Eddie Argos]]\n* [[Edgar F. Codd]] (23 August 1923&nbsp;\u2013 18 April 2003), British [[computer science|computer scientist]] and inventor of the [[relational model]] for database management\n* Former Premier League referee [[Paul Durkin]]\n* Former Queensland, Australia, politician [[Pat Comben]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portalbar|England|Islands}}\n\n== References ==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{refbegin}}\n:{{note label|estimate|A|A}}This figure is an estimate for mid-2010.\n:{{note label|ahs1|B|B}}Areas in [[American Horticultural Society]] Heat Zone 1 experience less than one day per year with maximum temperatures above {{convert|30|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.ahs.org/pdfs/05_heat_map.pdf | title = Plant Heat-Zone Map | format = PDF | publisher = [[American Horticultural Society]] | accessdate = 3 January 2008}}</ref>\n:{{note label|sunshine|C|C}}The maximum hours of sunshine possible in one year is approximately 4383 hours (12 hours/day \u00d7 365.25 days).\n:{{note label|growingseason|D|D}}The [[growing season]] in the United Kingdom is defined as starting on the day after five consecutive days with mean temperatures above {{convert|5|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}. The season finishes the day after mean temperatures are below {{convert|5|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}} for five consecutive days.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2005 | url = http://www.defra.gov.uk/environment/statistics/globatmos/kf/gakf19.htm | title = Length of the thermal growing season: 1772\u20132006 | publisher = [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] | accessdate = 22 December 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071103041655/http://www.defra.gov.uk/environment/statistics/globatmos/kf/gakf19.htm <!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate = 3 November 2007}}</ref>\n:{{note label|hardinesszone|E|E}}Areas in [[Hardiness zone]] 9 experience an average lowest recorded temperature each year between {{convert|-6.6|and|-1.1|C|F}}.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2003 | url = http://www.usna.usda.gov/Hardzone/hrdzon3.html | title = Hardiness Zones&nbsp;\u2013 Details | publisher = [[United States National Arboretum]] | accessdate = 22 December 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20010422044919/http://www.usna.usda.gov/Hardzone/hrdzon3.html | archivedate = 22 April 2001 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n:{{note label|weymouthandportland|F|F}}Figures are for Weymouth and Portland as a whole.\n:{{note label|julysep|G|G}}These figures are for July to September in 2010.\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n* Anon 1905, ''The Portland Year Book and Island Record 1905'', reprinted 2004, Portland Museum, Portland, Dorset\n* Theresa Murphy, ''Murder in Dorset 1988.'' Robert Hale Limited, London \u2013 Portland chapters\n* Stuart Morris, 2016 ''Portland, an Illustrated History'' The Dovecote Press, [[Wimborne]], Dorset: {{ISBN|978-0-9955462-0-2}} \n* Geoffrey Carter, 1999 ''Royal Navy at Portland Since 1845''. Maritime Books, {{ISBN|978-0907771296}}.\n* Stuart Morris, 1998 ''Portland'' (''Discover Dorset'' Series) The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|1-874336-49-0}}.\n* Rodney Legg, 1999 ''Portland Encyclopedia''. Dorset Publishing Company, {{ISBN|978-0948699566}}.\n* Jackson, Brian L. 1999. ''Isle of Portland railways''. {{ISBN|0-85361-540-3}}\n* Palmer, Susann. 1999. ''Ancient Portland: Archaeology of the Isle''. Portland: S. Palmer. {{ISBN|0-9532811-0-8}}\n* Stuart Morris, 2002 ''Portland: A Portrait in Colour'' The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|1-874336-91-1}}.\n* Stuart Morris, 2006 ''Portland, Then and Now'' The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|1-904349-48-X}}.\n* ''Dorset: The Royal Navy'' Stuart Morris, 2011, The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|978-1-904349-88-4}}. Features Portland.\n* ''Weymouth & Portland'', Stuart Morris 2012. The Dovecote Press, Wimborne, Dorset: {{ISBN|978-1-904349-98-3}}.\n* {{cite book |last=Hackman |first=Gill |year=2014 |title=Stone to Build London: Portland's Legacy |location=Monkton Farleigh, Wilts |publisher=Folly Books |isbn=978-0-9564405-9-4 |oclc=910854593}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Portland, Isle of}}\n{{commons category|Isle of Portland}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Isle of Portland}}\n* Map sources for grid reference {{mmukscaled|SY690721|100|SY 690 721}}.\n* [http://www.portlandtowncouncil.gov.uk/ Portland Town Council]\n* {{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Portland, Isle of|short=x}}\n[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-dorset-32013883 Last Ferry Crossing]\n\n{{Dorset}}\n{{SSSIs Dorset biological}}\n{{Isle of Portland}}\n{{Jurassic Coast}}\n{{Viking Invasion of England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Portland, Isle Of}}\n[[Category:Isle of Portland| ]]\n[[Category:Headlands of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Islands of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Liberties of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Peninsulas of England]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Jurassic Coast]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Tied islands]]\n[[Category:Tombolos]]\n[[Category:Natural regions of England]]\n[[Category:Natural regions of Dorset]]\n[[Category:Weymouth and Portland]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "template fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isle_of_Portland"}
{"title_page": "Maternity leave in the United States", "text_new": "{{short description|Regulated by US labor law}}\n'''Maternity leave in the United States''' is regulated by [[US labor law]]. The [[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993]] (FMLA) requires 12 weeks of unpaid leave annually for mothers of newborn or newly adopted children if they work for a company with 50 or more employees. Additionally, several states have adopted laws extending the requirements of FMLA to smaller companies.  For the majority of US workers at companies with fewer than 50 employees, there is no legal right to paid or unpaid leave to care for a new child or recover from childbirth.  Studies show the current laws disproportionately impact women [[Person of color|of color]] and low-income women, who are less likely to take unpaid leave.<ref name=\"expecting\" />\n\nThis is below the 16-week minimum recommended by the [[World Health Organization]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vahratian|first=Anjel|last2=Johnson|first2=Timothy R.B.|date=September 2009|title=Maternity Leave Benefits in the United States: Today's Economic Climate Underlines Deficiencies|journal=Birth|volume=36|issue=3|pages=177\u2013179|doi=10.1111/j.1523-536x.2009.00330.x|pmid=19747263|pmc=4262924|issn=0730-7659}}</ref> The United States is one of the only countries in the world, and the only [[OECD|OECD member]], that has not passed laws requiring businesses and corporations to offer paid maternity leave to their employees.<ref>{{cite web|last=OECD|title=Parental Leave Systems|url=https://www.oecd.org/els/soc/PF2_1_Parental_leave_systems.pdf}}</ref> As of 2017, there had been no significant change in the proportion of women who received maternity leave in the past 20 years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zagorsky|first=Jay L.|date=March 2017|title=Divergent Trends in US Maternity and Paternity Leave, 1994\u20132015|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=107|issue=3|pages=460\u2013465|doi=10.2105/ajph.2016.303607|pmid=28103064|pmc=5296693|issn=0090-0036}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBetween 1961 and 1965, only 14% of mothers participated in the workforce within 6 months of their child's birth.<ref>{{cite journal|last=O'Connell|first=M. |author2=B. Downs |author3=K. Smith|title=Maternity Leave and Employment Patterns: 1961-1995|journal=Current Population Reports|year=2001|volume=70|issue=79|pages=1\u201321}}</ref> During the same time period, only 44% of mothers worked during their pregnancy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/en.html|title=Census.gov|last=Bureau|first=US Census|website=www.census.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the enactment of FMLA legislation in 1993, maternity leave coverage was governed by state law, collective bargaining agreements and employer policies.<ref name=\"bw\">{{cite journal|last=Berger|first=L.|author2=J. Waldfogel|title=Maternity Leave and the Employment of New Mothers in the United States|journal=Journal of Population Economics|year=2004|volume=17|issue=2|pages=331\u2013349|doi=10.1007/s00148-003-0159-9}}</ref> The first set of maternity leave related policies emerged after World War I when first wave feminists lobbied for a women's health bill that gave grants to states to provide healthcare for women and children.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/9780203874493|title=Women's Rights in the USA: Policy Debates and Gender Roles|last=McBride|first=Dorothy E.|date=2014-06-11|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780203874493|edition=4|language=en|doi=10.4324/9780203874493}}</ref> By 1969, five states had enacted Temporary [[Disability Insurance]] laws protecting employees from income loss in the occurrence of a temporary medical disability.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tanaka|first=S.|title=Parental Leave and Child Health Across OECD Countries|journal=The Economic Journal|year=2005|volume=115|issue=501|pages=7\u201328|doi=10.1111/j.0013-0133.2005.00970.x}}</ref> Under this legislation, new mothers were granted leaves corresponding to the benefits that other employees received for temporary illness or disability. Changes to the federal tax code in 1976 permitted working families with a dependent child to take a tax credit on child care costs. \u00a0In 1978, the Pregnancy and Discrimination Act (PDA) prohibited employers from treating a woman unfavorably because of pregnancy, childbirth, or a medical condition related to pregnancy or childbirth.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Patton|first=Dana|last2=Costich|first2=Julia F.|last3=Lidstr\u00f6mer|first3=Niklas|date=March 2017 |title=Paid Parental Leave Policies and Infant Mortality Rates in OECD Countries: Policy Implications for the United States |journal=World Medical & Health Policy|volume=9|issue=1|pages=6\u201323|doi=10.1002/wmh3.214 |doi-access=free |issn=1948-4682}}</ref> During a landmark case in 1987, California Federal Savings and Loan Association v. Guerra, upheld a California law requiring most employers to grant pregnant women 4 months of unpaid disability leave and the right to return to their same job.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gordon|first=Victoria|date=2013-06-10|title=Maternity Leave|doi=10.1201/b14999|isbn=9780429254413}}</ref> This state-level trend of maternity leave legislation continued into the 1970s and 1980s where multiple other states passed more explicit recognitions of new mothers' rights to a temporary leave of absence. Ultimately, 12 states and the District of Columbia had implemented measures requiring at least some private sector employers to offer maternity leave packages to its employees.<ref name=\"bw\" /> Even in the absence of this formal legislation, employees in other states often obtained maternity leave through [[collective bargaining]]. Employees frequently held enough bargaining power to influence employer policies and negotiate for the inclusion of maternity leave protection.\n\nDespite some localized employees' access to maternity leave, there was growing pressure for national maternity leave legislation in the early 1990s. Many new mothers continued to be excluded from such maternity leave provisions despite growing national demand. Women now enjoyed greater employment opportunities and changing gender norms that encouraged increased labor involvement. This increased [[female employment]] extended to mothers as well who now were now more likely to engage in the workforce even if they had a young child. The labor participation rate of mothers with children under the age of 1 rose from 31% in 1976 to 54% in 1992.<ref name=\"w\">{{cite journal|last=Waldfogel|first=J.|title=The Family Gap for Young Women in the United States and Britain: Can Maternity Leave Make a Difference?|journal=Journal of Labor Economics|year=1998|volume=16|issue=3|pages=505\u2013545|doi=10.1086/209897}}</ref> The contribution of women's earnings to her family income rose from 26.6% in 1970 to 36% in 2008.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Maternity leave : policy and practice|last=Gordon, Victoria (Associate professor)|isbn=9781466573581|location=Boca Raton|oclc=838447584|date = 2013-06-10}}</ref> In spite of a high labor force participation rate, only an estimated 40% of working women had access to explicit maternity leave protection. This inadequate national coverage provoked intense protest and growing national consensus on the value of maternity leave. Ultimately, the increased salience and galvanized national support prompted the 1993 enactment of the [[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993|Family and Medical Leave Act]] mandating maternity leave.\n\nAlthough the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 required employers to guarantee job-protected, unpaid leave up to 12 weeks after the birth or adoption of a new child, an estimated 41 percent of employees in the United States were not covered by the Family and Medical Leave Act in 2012.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jou|first=Judy|last2=Kozhimannil|first2=Katy B.|last3=Abraham|first3=Jean M.|last4=Blewett|first4=Lynn A.|last5=McGovern|first5=Patricia M.|date=February 2018 |title=Paid Maternity Leave in the United States: Associations with Maternal and Infant Health |journal=Maternal and Child Health Journal|language=en|volume=22|issue=2|pages=216\u2013225|doi=10.1007/s10995-017-2393-x|pmid=29098488|issn=1092-7875}}</ref> Nearly \u2154 of mothers had to work during their pregnancies between 2002-2008.<ref name=\":4\"/> By 2016, only 14% of US workers had access to paid family leave as an employee benefit. About two-thirds of employees (68 percent) had access to paid sick leave, and 38 percent had access to short-term disability benefits.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bartel|first=Ann P.|last2=Rossin-Slater|first2=Maya|last3=Ruhm|first3=Christopher J.|last4=Stearns|first4=Jenna|last5=Waldfogel|first5=Jane|date=2017-11-06|title=Paid Family Leave, Fathers' Leave-Taking, and Leave-Sharing in Dual-Earner Households|journal=Journal of Policy Analysis and Management|volume=37|issue=1|pages=10\u201337|doi=10.1002/pam.22030|pmid=29320808|issn=0276-8739|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w21747.pdf}}</ref> Prior to FMLA, the term \u201cfamily\u201d referred to a nuclear family where with two parents of opposite sex and the \u201cmother\u201d could bear a child. This was the only definition acknowledged by medical and economic research done before the LGBTQ rights movement. Only recently, studies have caught up to a modern and more inclusive definition family.\n\n==Current legislation==\n\nIn the U.S. parents and family are federally protected under The Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 (FMLA)<ref name=\"U.S. Department of Labor\">{{cite web |title=Wage and Hour Division (WHD): Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/ |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> to go on maternity or family leave after the adoption or birth of a child.<ref name=\"dol.gov\">{{cite web |title=Wage and Hour Division (WHD): Frequently Asked Questions |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/fmla-faqs.htm |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> Under this law, legal parents are protected for up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave (per year). The FMLA ensures the job security of parents/employees but does not protect employees who go on paid leave with their employers. Receiving the correct payment from being on leave is between the firm and the employee.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Employee's Guide to The Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/employeeguide.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> However, some states have laws that do protect and guarantee employees for paid family leave (see State Legislation section). Additionally, the FMLA defines \u201cparents\u201d as biological, adoptive, step or foster parent who stood in loco parentis or \u201cin the place of a parent\u201d. Parents do not include parent-in-laws though.<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Department of Labor Wage and Hour Division (July 2015) Fact Sheet #28J: The definition of \"parent\" as it applies to an individual who stood in loco parentis to an employee for FMLA \"eldercare\" protections. |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/regs/compliance/whdfs28c.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis paragraph is for employees who are seeking to get paid using their firm's extended policies on leaves. If you choose to go on maternity or family leave, The Employee's Guide to Family and Medical Leave Act,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Employee's Guide to The Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/employeeguide.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> states that you can sometimes use your unspent sick time, vacation time, personal time, etc., saved up with your employer at the same time of your FMLA leave so that you continue to get paid. Importantly though, in order to use such leave, \u201cyou must follow your employer\u2019s normal leave rules such as submitting a leave form or providing advance notice. Even if you don\u2019t want to use your paid leave, your employer can require you to use it during your FMLA leave\u201d.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Employee's Guide to The Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/employeeguide.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIf you are choosing to use the FMLA to go on regular unpaid leave without any extended or paid leave, it's important to know the qualifications beforehand. The FMLA actually has several limiting stipulations and leaves out certain employee's conditions such as temp workers and trans employees, so only certain employees are eligible. In order to receive maternity leave protections under FMLA, employees must:<ref name=\"dol.gov\"/>\n\n*work for a covered employer;\n*have worked 1,250 hours during the 12 months prior to the start of leave; (special hours of service rules apply to airline flight crew members)<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Department of Labor Wage and Hour Division (July 2015) Fact Sheet #28J: The definition of \"parent\" as it applies to an individual who stood in loco parentis to an employee for FMLA \"eldercare\" protections. |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/regs/compliance/whdfs28c.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n*work at a location where the employer has 50 or more employees within 75 miles; and\n*have worked for the employer for 12 months.\n\nThe 12 months of employment are not required to be consecutive in order for the employee to qualify for FMLA leave. In general, only employment within seven years is counted unless the break in service is (1) due to an employee's fulfillment of military obligations, or (2) governed by a collective bargaining agreement or other written agreement.\n\nThe FMLA is the only law that federally protects American employees who go on maternity or family leave their resumed job security. It was signed into law during President Bill Clinton's first term in 1993 and revised on February 23, 2015 to include same-sex parents and spouses.<ref name=\"U.S. Department of Labor\"/> Two other Federal laws, the Pregnancy Discrimination Act<ref>{{cite web |title=The Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978 |url=https://www.eeoc.gov/laws/statutes/pregnancy.cfm |website=Equal Employment Opportunity Commission |publisher=U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> (PDA) and the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act's (PPACA, also known as the Affordable Care Act, the ACA or Obamacare)<ref name=\"EHealthInsurances Services\">{{cite web |title=Maternity Insurance Coverage under ObamaCare |url=https://www.ehealthinsurance.com/resources/affordable-care-act/maternity-insurance-coverage-obamacare |website=EHealthInsurances Services |publisher=EHealthInsurances Services |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> amendment of the Fair Labor Standards Act,<ref>{{cite web |title=Wage and Hour Division (WHD) Handy Reference Guide to the Fair Labor Standards Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/regs/compliance/hrg.htm |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> provide some additional protection for parents on the birth of a child. For instance, the PDA upholds maternity leave by arguing that employees who give temporarily disabled folks a disability leave should give pregnant women maternity leave with the same protections and benefits. This PDA is essentially arguing that pregnant women should have rights to the same paid of unpaid leave that temporarily disabled workers are afforded by their employers. If an employer offers this protection to temporarily disabled workers then PDA says that pregnant women should also be protected using the same processes and same benefits. Additionally, in 2014 the PPACA amendment to the Fair Labor Standards Act made it so that all insurance companies had to include maternity coverage in individual insurance plans. Therefore, filling the gap for unemployed women with individual insurance coverage plans to be able to afford the prenatal and postnatal pregnancy care that they need to have a healthy baby. Maternity care came to include:<ref name=\"EHealthInsurances Services\"/>\n\n*Outpatient services, such as prenatal and postnatal doctor visits, gestational diabetes screenings, lab studies, medications, etc.\n*Inpatient services, such as hospitalization, physician fees, etc.\n*Newborn baby care\n*Lactation counseling and breast-pump rental\n \nThese federal laws and amendments have increased accessibility and quality of care for prenatal and postnatal mothers and families. For example, before the Affordable Care Act, only 12% of insurance plans sold in the individual market included maternity coverage.<ref name=\"EHealthInsurances Services\"/> Also, according to a journal study on FMLA by researchers at the University of Maryland,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dagher |first=Rada K |display-authors=etal |title=Maternity Leave Duration and Postpartum Mental and Physical Health: Implications for Leave Policies |journal=Journal of Health Politics, Policy and Law |date=December 2013 |volume=39 |issue=2 |pages=369\u2013416 |doi=10.1215/03616878-2416247 |pmid=24305845 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/259201718}}</ref> it was found that mothers who benefitted from FMLA were returned to the same job and sooner than before FMLA thus showing the impact of job stability for mothers. Nonetheless, many employees are still ineligible for the FMLA. According to the Family and Medical Leave Report in 2012, only 59% of American employees were eligible under the FMLA.<ref>{{cite web |title=Family and Medical Leave in 2012: Technical Report |url=https://www.dol.gov/asp/evaluation/fmla/fmla-2012-technical-report.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, employees who returned after FMLA, women exclusively, were given lower wages than the ones to when they left. This comes from the same study by researchers at the University of Maryland, as aforementioned. It should be said that these lower wages may have not been permanent since the study only went to highlight women's experience with maternity leave two years after they leave.\n \nIn recent polls from 2017, Democrats and Republicans both are in high support of federal funding for paid maternity and family leave. According to a study done by the Brookings Institution,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mathur |first=Aparna \n |display-authors=etal |title=Paid Family and Medical Leave: An Issue Whose Time Has Come |url=http://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/es_20170606_paidfamilyleave.pdf |website=Brookings |publisher=AEI-Brookings Working Group on Paid Family Leave |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> a non-profit think tank in D.C., 71% of Republicans and 83% of Democrats support for a paid leave policy. Although the study did not reach a particular compromise on how the policies should work, who should pay for it, how much, and other concerns that might factor into creating a universal paid parental leave policy, they did reach a conclusion. Amongst the diverse group of researchers with different political and economic views, everyone believed that it is worthwhile to consider a federal paid leave policy. One important reason for this is because \u201cThe US is the only advanced country that provides no public support to new parents\u201d. \n \nThe U.S. does not presently have a federal paid maternity and family leave act. Some states, however, do include paid leave legislation for family members. States like California, New Jersey, and New York have pioneered paid leave legislature in their respective states. Reasons for paid leave might include higher job security for women and to reduce women's need for public assistance. A study by the Institute for Women's Research<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gult |first1=Barbara |title=Paid Parental Leave in the United States |url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/our-work/workplace/expecting-better-a.html |website=National Partnership |publisher=National Partnership for Women & Families |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> has also shown that paid leave could reduce employer costs and lead to U.S. economic growth. Also, paid family leave has been shown to increase the health of the family by lowering infant mortality rates.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Sandra L. |last=Hofferth |first2=Sally C. |last2=Curtin |title=Parental Leave Statutes and Maternal Return to Work After Childbirth in the United States |journal=Work and Occupations|volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=73\u2013105 |date=February 1, 2006 |doi=10.1177/0730888405281889}}</ref> Paid family leave would also allow low-income families the ability to take care of their family members without having to sacrifice time and money. Reasons for not having a protected paid family leave policy in place might be justified by the fact that there are limited economic resources to sustain a program.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leef |first1=George |title=Is Federal Paid Family Leave A Good Idea? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/georgeleef/2018/02/02/is-federal-paid-family-leave-a-good-idea/#71f1d98f795f |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, some may disagree with the overreach of the government taking on the responsibility to keep families afloat while on leave. Compared to some other countries, the U.S. remains behind in terms of maternity leave legislature.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Joya |first1=Misra |title=The US is stingier with child care and maternity leave than the rest of the world |url=https://theconversation.com/the-us-is-stingier-with-child-care-and-maternity-leave-than-the-rest-of-the-world-94770 |website=The Conversation |publisher=The Conversation: Academic Rigor, Journalistic Flair |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===State legislation===\nMany states have supplemented these federal regulations and provided more extensive maternity leave benefits, including expanding paid or flexible sick time, expanding access for workers in smaller companies or with less time on the job, right to pump that expands on federal law, and pregnancy accommodations.<ref name=\"expecting\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/research-library/work-family/expecting-better-2016.pdf|title=Expecting Better: A state-by-state analysis of laws that help expecting and new parents (4th edition)|last=National Partnership for Women and Families|date=August 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, 12 states have enacted no additional laws or programs to support family leave before or after birth.<ref name=\"expecting\"/> Fourteen states, along with the District of Columbia, have addressed eligibility requirements by lowering the firm-size threshold from 50 or more employees down to as low as 10 employees. Seven other states, in addition to the District of Columbia, have adopted more generous maternity leave lengths that allow longer absences for the purpose of child rearing. Moreover, some states have enacted legislation enhancing the benefits of leave programs.\n\nCalifornia, New Jersey, and Rhode Island for instance, operate programs that require private-sector employers to pay their employees who utilize maternity leave at partial replacement rates.<ref name=\"grs\">{{cite web|last=Gornick|first=Janet|title=Parental Leave in 21 Countries: Assessing Generosity and Gender Equality |url=http://cepr.net/publications/reports/plp |publisher=Center for Economic and Policy Research |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ray |first3=John |last3=Schmitt |year=2008}}</ref> New York passed paid family leave legislation, which includes maternity leave, in 2016 \u2014 starting off at 8 weeks and 50% of pay in 2018, and reaching 12 weeks and 67% of pay in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://singlemotherguide.com/grants-for-single-mothers/#FMLA |title=Paid Family Leave \u2015 Grants for Single Moms |publisher=Single Mother Guide|access-date=September 14, 2017|date=2011-03-12 }}</ref>\n\nHawaii, Puerto Rico, and the District of Columbia designate childbirth as a temporary disability thus guaranteeing mothers paid maternity leave through [[Disability Insurance]] (TDI) provisions.<ref name=\"eb\">{{cite web|title=Expecting Better: A State-by-State Analysis of Laws that Help New Parents |url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/issues/work-family/expecting-better-a.html |publisher=National Partnership for Women and Families|accessdate=8 April 2013|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nOn Dec. 31, 2019, New Mexico Governor Michelle Lujan Grisham signed an executive order installing paid family leave for state employees, the first such policy in the state. The order, providing 12 weeks of paid family leave for state employees under the Governor's direct purview, became effective January 1, 2020.[https://www.governor.state.nm.us/2019/12/31/governor-orders-12-week-paid-parental-leave-for-state-employees/]\n\n=== Other federal policies ===\nThe Department of Defense has regulated the amount of maternity leave a military member can take. Before February 5, 2016 the leave was six weeks long for active duty members or reservists who had previously done twelve months of active duty time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.airforcetimes.com/story/military/2016/02/09/air-forces-new-12-week-maternity-leave-began-feb-5/80059404/|title=air-forces-new-12-week-maternity-leave-began-feb-5|last=Times|first=Air Force|website=Air Force Times|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> On January 28, 2016, the Defense Secretary, Ashton Carter, increased the paid maternity leave to twelve weeks for all branches.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/645958/carter-announces-12-weeks-paid-military-maternity-leave-other-benefits|title=Carter Announces 12 Weeks Paid Military Maternity Leave, Other Benefit|work=U.S. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref> Traditional reservists, however, are given an eighty-four-day excusal, not leave.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/e2/c/downloads/425869.pdf|title=Army Directive 2016-09 (Maternity Leave Policy)}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States Air Force AFI36-3003, it states that the maternity leave starts after being released from the hospital from giving birth, as also defined for other branches. \"Shared benefits\" can be created if both parents are active Air Force members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://static.e-publishing.af.mil/production/1/af_a1/publication/afi36-3003/afi36-3003.pdf|title=AIR FORCE INSTRUCTION 36-3003|last=Deborah|first=Lee}}</ref> Therefore, a sum of up to twelve weeks can be taken by one parent or distributed amongst the two parents. However, two married active duty members cannot create \"shared benefits\" in the Army, according to the Army Directive 2016-09 (Maternity Leave Policy).<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThere was a stance by the previous Secretary of the Navy, Ray Mabus, to increase the maternity leave from six to eighteen weeks for the Navy and Marine Corps beginning on July 2, 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=87987|title=SECNAV Announces New Maternity Leave Policy|last=Information|first=This story was written by the Office of the Chief of|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref> It was implemented until January 28, 2016, however, it remained eighteen weeks for those who were pregnant previous to and on March 3, 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=93290|title=Navy Updates Maternity Leave Policy|last=Affairs|first=This story was written by Chief of Naval Personnel Public|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIt was a significant leap to go from six to twelve weeks of maternity leave. Other benefits have also been increased to improve the lives of those with newborn or newly adopted children. These benefits include an increase of child care hours to fourteen hours a day, and allowing active duty members more ability to family plan by paying for the sperm and egg freezing.<ref name=\":0\" /> These decisions were made by the previous Defense Secretary \"in an effort to support military families, improve retention and strengthen the force of the future.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn December 20, 2019, as part of the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020 | National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) for Fiscal Year 2020]],<ref>{{USBill|116|S.|1790}}; NDAA 2020, [https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/1790 Pub.L. 116-92], {{USPL|116|92}}</ref> the Federal Employee Paid Leave Act (FEPLA) amended the  [[Family_and_Medical_Leave_Act_of_1993 | Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA)]]  to grant federal government employees up to 12 weeks of paid time off for the birth, adoption or foster of a new child.<ref>[https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title5-section6382&num=0&edition=prelim 5 USC \u00a7\u202f6382(d)(2)]</ref> The law applies to births or placements occurring on or after October 1, 2020.<ref>[https://www.chcoc.gov/content/paid-parental-leave-federal-employees Office of Personnel Management, MEMORANDUM FOR: HEADS OF EXECUTIVE DEPARTMENTS AND AGENCIES on December 27, 2019]</ref>\n\n==Impacts of United States maternity leave==\n\n===Health===\n\n====Child health and development====\n\nLonger maternity leave (up to 25 weeks) is associated with a reduction in post-neonatal and child mortality.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Staehelin|first=Katharina|last2=Bertea|first2=Paola Coda|last3=Stutz|first3=Elisabeth Zemp|date= August 2007|title=Length of maternity leave and health of mother and child \u2013 a review|journal=International Journal of Public Health|volume=52|issue=4|pages=202\u2013209|doi=10.1007/s00038-007-5122-1|issn=1661-8556|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/311716/files/38_2007_Article_5122.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Jou|first=Judy|last2=Kozhimannil|first2=Katy B.|last3=Abraham|first3=Jean M.|last4=Blewett|first4=Lynn A.|last5=McGovern|first5=Patricia M.|date=2017-11-02|title=Paid Maternity Leave in the United States: Associations with Maternal and Infant Health|journal=Maternal and Child Health Journal|volume=22|issue=2|pages=216\u2013225|doi=10.1007/s10995-017-2393-x|pmid=29098488|issn=1092-7875}}</ref> A 2017 study found that there was almost a 50% reduction in the probability of infant rehospitalization when women took maternity leave that was partially and fully paid.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to data from the 2006\u20132010 U.S. National Survey of Family Growth, paid maternity leave of 3 or more months for employed mothers is associated with a higher chance of the mother starting breastfeeding and breastfeeding her child at six months.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Mirkovic|first=Kelsey R.|last2=Perrine|first2=Cria G.|last3=Scanlon|first3=Kelley S.|date=2016|title=Paid Maternity Leave and Breastfeeding Outcomes|journal=Birth|language=en|volume=43|issue=3|pages=233\u2013239|doi=10.1111/birt.12230|pmid=26991788|issn=1523-536X}}</ref> The American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) currently recommends six months of breastfeeding exclusively, and continued breastfeeding as foods are introduced for one year for its medical and neurodevelopmental benefits for the child.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Breastfeeding|first=Section On|date=2012-03-01|title=Breastfeeding and the Use of Human Milk|url=https://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/129/3/e827|journal=Pediatrics|language=en|volume=129|issue=3|pages=e827\u2013e841|doi=10.1542/peds.2011-3552|issn=0031-4005|pmid=22371471|doi-access=free}}</ref> Mothers who are not engaged in employment may be more able to participate in consistent breast-feeding, since maternal employment can interfere with breastfeeding.<ref name=\":5\" /> The Center for Disease Control and Prevention states asthma, obesity, Sudden infant death syndrome, type 2 diabetes, gastrointestinal infections, and certain infections are all less likely to occur in breastfed babies.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/breastfeeding/about-breastfeeding/why-it-matters.html|title=About Breastfeeding|last=CDC|date=2019-03-12|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/29/health/paid-leave-benefits-to-children-research/index.html|title=Paid leave benefits children and families, studies say |author1=Kelly Wallace |author2=Jen Christensen|work=CNN|access-date=2017-10-02}}</ref> Research suggests that breast-feeding has the ability to yield substantial child health improvements in disease prevention and immune system build-up.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Baker|first=M.|author2=K. Milligan|title=Maternal Employment, Breastfeeding and Health: Evidence from Maternity Leave Mandates|journal=Journal of Health Economics|year=2008|volume=27|issue=4|pages=871\u2013887|doi=10.1016/j.jhealeco.2008.02.006|pmid=18387682|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w13188.pdf}}</ref> Moreover, further evidence indicates that maternal care is especially crucial during the first couple of months following child birth, or the time in which American maternity leave is in effect.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ruhm|first=C.|title=Parental Employment and Child Cognitive Development|journal=Journal of Human Resources|year=2004|volume=39|issue=1|pages=155\u2013192|doi=10.2307/3559009|jstor=3559009|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w7666.pdf}}</ref> Finally, evidence shows that paid maternity leave plans can increase paternal involvement in child care as shown by California's state paid maternity leave program.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://prospect.org/article/new-push-paid-family-leave|title=The New Push for Paid Family Leave|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=2013-12-12|work=The American Prospect|access-date=2019-05-13|language=en-US|issn=1049-7285}}</ref>\n\n====Maternal health====\nThe medical definition of [[postpartum]] is the time frame between childbirth and the return of the mother's reproductive organs to their non pregnant state.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGovern|first=Pat|last2=Dowd|first2=Bryan|last3=Gjerdingen|first3=Dwenda|last4=Gross|first4=Cynthia R.|last5=Kenney|first5=Sally|last6=Ukestad|first6=Laurie|last7=McCaffrey|first7=David|last8=Lundberg|first8=Ulf|date=March 2006|title=Postpartum Health of Employed Mothers 5 Weeks After Childbirth |journal=Annals of Family Medicine|volume=4|issue=2|pages=159\u2013167|doi=10.1370/afm.519|pmc=1467019|pmid=16569720}}</ref> For women that return to work during this postpartum period, the stress of maintaining a balance between their professional and parenting responsibilities has been shown to weaken their immune systems and interact poorly with their psychological state.<ref name=\"cm\">{{cite journal|last=Chatterji|first=P.|author2=S. Markowitz|title=Does the Length of Maternity Leave affect Maternal Health?|journal=National Bureau of Economic Research|year=2004}}</ref> Lower rates of breastfeeding may also have negative effects on the mother's health, as breastfeeding lowers the possibility of breast cancer, ovarian cancer, type 2 diabetes, and heart disease for the mother.<ref name=\":6\" /> Women of color and women classified as high economic hardship report postpartum symptoms more frequently and for a longer duration than women not in these categories. This trend is observed with both physical and mental health symptoms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tucker|first=Jenna N.|last2=Grzywacz|first2=Joseph G.|last3=Leng|first3=Iris|last4=Clinch|first4=C. Randall|last5=Arcury|first5=Thomas A.|date=2010-11-10|title=Return to Work, Economic Hardship, and Women's Postpartum Health|journal=Women & Health|volume=50|issue=7|pages=618\u2013638|doi=10.1080/03630242.2010.522468|pmid=21104566|issn=0363-0242}}</ref> Maternity leave over a longer time period is associated with an increase in the health of both the mother and the child. Paid leave with a duration of over 12 weeks is correlated with a decrease in the risk of infant and maternal re-hospitalization.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to a study on mothers of 6-month old infants using data from the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development, mothers who worked more hours experienced higher levels of depressive symptoms and stress due to parenting. They also viewed their personal health as worse when they worked more hours in the time period after childbirth.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chatterji|first=Pinka|last2=Markowitz|first2=Sara|last3=Brooks-Gunn|first3=Jeanne|date=2013-01-01|title=Effects of early maternal employment on maternal health and well-being|journal=Journal of Population Economics|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=285\u2013301|doi=10.1007/s00148-012-0437-5|issn=1432-1475|pmc=3640562|pmid=23645972}}</ref> Maternal-infant separation may cause significant parental stress, depression, and anxiety. Researchers propose paid leave relates to health as it allows women to recover from childbirth and take care of themselves, attend to their infant, visit the hospital for prenatal checkups, wellness, and illness, and manage finances.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weber|first=Ashley|last2=Harrison|first2=Tondi M.|last3=Steward|first3=Deborah|last4=Ludington-Hoe|first4=Susan|date=February 2018|title=Paid Family Leave to Enhance the Health Outcomes of Preterm Infants|journal=Policy, Politics, & Nursing Practice|language=en|volume=19|issue=1\u20132|pages=11\u201328|doi=10.1177/1527154418791821|pmid=30134774|pmc=6532630|issn=1527-1544}}</ref>\n\n====Postpartum depression==== \nAmong other factors, pregnancy can be a cause of depression in women. Symptoms of postpartum depression include a loss of interest in activities, difficulty focusing, thinking, making decisions, and remembering things, anxiety, irritation, slowed speaking, physical pains, and feelings of sadness and worthlessness.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.|url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/postpartum-depression/basics/definition/con-20029130|website=Mayo Clinic}}</ref> In industrial societies, postpartum depression is considered a major public health concern and affects about 15% of women. Postpartum depression also has negative developmental consequences for the child.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Apter-Levy|first=Yael|last2=Feldman|first2=Michal|last3=Vakart|first3=Adam|last4=Ebstein|first4=Richard P.|last5=Feldman|first5=Ruth|date=2013-10-01|title=Impact of Maternal Depression Across the First 6 Years of Life on the Child's Mental Health, Social Engagement, and Empathy: The Moderating Role of Oxytocin|journal=American Journal of Psychiatry|volume=170|issue=10|pages=1161\u20131168|doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.2013.12121597|pmid=23846912|issn=0002-953X|doi-access=free}}</ref> Research indicates 12 weeks may not be a long enough leave duration for those at risk of developing postpartum depression.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dowd|first=Bryan E.|last2=McGovern|first2=Patricia M.|last3=Dagher|first3=Rada K.|date=2014-04-01|title=Maternity Leave Duration and Postpartum Mental and Physical Health: Implications for Leave Policies|journal=Journal of Health Politics, Policy and Law|language=en|volume=39|issue=2|pages=369\u2013416|doi=10.1215/03616878-2416247|pmid=24305845|issn=0361-6878}}</ref> Fewer occurrences of depressive symptoms are correlated to longer maternity leave.<ref name=\"cm\" /> A study using data from the Early Childhood Longitudinal Study - Birth Cohort indicates there is a lower likelihood of women developing severe depression \u00a0and increased overall health if women take longer maternity leave from work.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Chatterji|first=Pinka|last2=Markowitz|first2=Sara|date=July 2008|title=Family Leave after Childbirth and the Health of New Mothers|location=Cambridge, MA|doi=10.3386/w14156|doi-access=free}}</ref> In addition, more depressive symptoms occurred in mothers postpartum when the spouse did not take any paternal leave.<ref name=\":7\" /> Poor physical health of the mother during the postpartum period is associated with more depressive symptoms, making postnatal health, in addition to employment, a prevalent factor when considering mental health in new mothers. Negative physical health symptoms frequently reported included tiredness, back pain, and back problems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woolhouse|first=Hannah|last2=Gartland|first2=Deirdre|last3=Perlen|first3=Susan|last4=Donath|first4=Susan|last5=Brown|first5=Stephanie J.|date=March 2014|title=Physical health after childbirth and maternal depression in the first 12 months post partum: Results of an Australian nulliparous pregnancy cohort study|journal=Midwifery|volume=30|issue=3|pages=378\u2013384|doi=10.1016/j.midw.2013.03.006|pmid=23619027|issn=0266-6138}}</ref>\n\n===Economic===\n\n====Economic efficiency====\nFour states currently offer paid family leave: California, Massachusetts, New Jersey, and Rhode Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/article/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-maternity-leave-in-the-us/|title=10 things you need to know about maternity leave in the US|work=TechRepublic|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> In New Jersey, women who took paid leave in the year after giving birth were 40% less likely to receive public aid or food stamps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rutgers.edu/news-release/rutgers-study-finds-paid-family-leave-leads-positive-economic-outcomes/20120119#.WuXi-zOZM0Q|title=Rutgers Study Finds Paid Family Leave Leads to Positive Economic Outcomes {{!}} Rutgers Today|website=news.rutgers.edu|access-date=2018-04-29|date=2012-01-19}}</ref> According to a California-based study, 87% of employers reported that the paid leave requirement did not increase costs; 9% note that it saved money due to decreased turnover and other costs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cepr.net/publications/reports/leaves-that-pay|title=Leaves That Pay: Employer and Worker Experiences With Paid Family Leave in California|last=Milkman|first=Eileen Appelbaum, Ruth|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, $40 million is spent annually on the re-hospitalization of preterm infants. In addition, each maternal re-hospitalization adds an extra $1,600-3,000 to the cost of childbirth. Paid maternity leave is associated with increased maternal and neonatal health, so offering paid leave could decrease these costs.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThough the overall labor force participation has declined since the year 2000,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Plumer|first1=Brad|title=Three Reasons the US Labor Force Keeps Shrinking|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/09/06/the-incredible-shrinking-labor-force-again/|accessdate=4 June 2017|agency=Washington Post|date=6 September 2013}}</ref> some economists argue that paid maternity leave in California has increased labor force participation among mothers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Claire Cain|title=The Economic Benefits of Paid Parental Leave|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/01/upshot/the-economic-benefits-of-paid-parental-leave.html?_r=0|accessdate=4 June 2017|agency=The New York Times|date=30 January 2015}}</ref> Mothers who receive paid maternity leave may be more likely to return to employment later, and then work more hours and earn higher wages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/01/upshot/the-economic-benefits-of-paid-parental-leave.html|title=The Economic Benefits of Paid Parental Leave|last=Miller|first=Claire Cain|date=2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-02|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> There is some evidence that the state paid maternity leave program in California saves businesses from needing to provide their own leave plans and financially stabilizes workers.<ref name=\":8\"/>\n\nLess favorable maternity leave policies may inhibit a woman's career trajectory and [[promotion (rank)|promotion]] prospects. The extended period of absence of such policies often reduce a women's economic status and opportunities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schwartz|first=F.|title=Management Women and the New Facts of Life|journal=Harvard Business Review|year=1989|volume=23|issue=1|pages=65\u201376}}</ref> During this hiatus, their job skills and experiences may deteriorate thus limiting their potential advancement.\n\n====Motherhood penalty====\n[[File:US Gender pay gap, by age.001.png|thumb|US - women's earnings as a percentage of men's in 2008 by age group]]\nAvailable maternity leave options may also help lower the impact of children on career advancement, or the [[motherhood penalty]]. There currently exists a \"family gap\" between the pay of mothers and nonmothers. In the United States prior to the passage of the FMLA, mothers typically earned 70% of men's wages while nonmothers earned 90%.<ref name=\"w\" /> These earning disparities partially stemmed from insecure employment return prospects. Women without maternity leave protection were often forced to start over with a new employer following their absence.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lazear|first=E.|title=Agency, Earnings Profiles, Productivity, and Hours Restrictions|journal=American Economic Review|year=1981|pages=606\u2013620}}</ref> This interrupted their career progression and burdened them with the additional task of seeking new employment. Such factors ultimately impeded equitable access to income and career opportunities. Women as a group notably experience increasing [[income inequality]] as they age illustrating the impact of motherhood on their wage prospects. However, the implementation of FMLA addressed some of these impediments through the introduction of mandatory maternity leave. Mothers now are more likely to return to their previous employer due to this increased legal protection.<ref name=\"ch\">{{cite journal|last=Curtin|first=S.|author2=S. Hofferth|title=Parental Leave Statutes and Maternal Return to Work After Childbirth in the United States|journal=Work and Occupations|year=2006|volume=33|issue=1|pages=73\u2013105|doi=10.1177/0730888405281889}}</ref> The policy minimizes some of the negative externalities of motherhood by maintaining women's employment options even following maternity leave. Many policy experts though suspect that the remaining gender imbalance is largely attributable to the dearth of paid leave options.<ref name=\"w\" /> Women who worked for companies that provided paid maternity leave before they gave birth are more likely to take such leave for up to 12 weeks, and more likely to return to work more quickly thereafter.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Berger|first1=Lawrence M.|last2=Waldfogel|first2=Jane|title=Maternity leave and the employment of new mothers in the United States|journal=Journal of Population Economics|date=1 June 2004|volume=17|issue=2|pages=331\u2013349|doi=10.1007/s00148-003-0159-9}}</ref>\n\n===Social===\n\n====Access equality====\nUnder the current FMLA system, approximately 40% of United States workers are ineligible for benefits due to the brevity of their tenure or the smallness of their firm.<ref name=\"grs\" /> These excluded populations are often low-waged and minority women thus furthering their already present disadvantage. In 2016, 38% of white working mothers qualified for and could afford to take unpaid leave under FMLA compared with 30% of African American women and 25% of Hispanic women.<ref name=\"expecting\" /> Moreover, the unpaid aspect of the current policy limits access to those who are economically well off. The United States Department of Labor reported that over a 22-month period in 1999 and 2000, 3.5 million people needed leave but were unable to take it due to affordability concerns.<ref>{{cite journal|last=United States Department of Labor|title=Balancing the Needs of Families and Employees: FMLA Survey Report|year=2000|url=http://www.dol.gov/dol/asp/public/fmla/main2000.htm|journal=|access-date=2013-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050322140511/http://www.dol.gov/dol/asp/public/fmla/main2000.htm|archive-date=2005-03-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In the private sector, it was found that 12% of workers received paid paternity leave with 23% of workers in the highest-wage quartile receiving paid maternity leave versus 5% of workers in the lowest-wage quartile.<ref name=\"expecting\" /> The lack of monetary compensation may hinder the ability of women who are not as financially secure as others to balance employment with their family life. Upper class women are more likely to take unpaid leave than lower class women. In addition, more white women take unpaid maternity leave than black or Hispanic women. This imbalance contributes to the discrepancies in infant mortality between groups.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Paternity leave==\n\nCalifornia is the first state to offer paid paternity leave weeks (six weeks, partial payment). New Jersey, Rhode Island,<ref name=\"babycenter.com\" /> and New York<ref name=\"paidfamilyleave.ny.gov\">{{cite web |date=July 2018 |url=https://paidfamilyleave.ny.gov/paid-family-leave-information-employees#eligibility |title=Paid Family leave: Information for employee |publisher=New York State |accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> since passed laws for paid family leave. In the rest of the US, paternity pay weeks are not offered (therefore neither paternity paid leave weeks), but fathers have access to unpaid paternity leave to care for their newborns (without new income).<ref name=\"babycenter.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.babycenter.com/0_paternity-leave-what-are-the-options-for-dads_8258.bc |title=Paternity leave: What are the options for dads? |publisher=BabyCenter |date=November 2015 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ilo.org\">{{cite book|url=http://www.ilo.org/global/publications/ilo-bookstore/order-online/books/WCMS_242615/lang--en/index.htm |title=Maternity and paternity at work: Law and practice across the world |publisher=Ilo.org |date=May 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017|isbn=9789221286301 }}</ref> Often, fathers will take sick days or vacation time when they have newborns. There is also a growing number of fathers that go unpaid. Some employers are required by law to allow 12 weeks of unpaid family leave after the birth or adoption of a child. This law is under [[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993|FMLA]] or Family Medical Leave Act.<ref name=\"babycenter.com\"/> Fathers who have access to paid paternity leave give mothers the opportunity to engage in paid work, with a positive effect on female labor force participation and wages.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/asp/policy-development/PaternityBrief.pdf|title=Paternity Leave: Why Paternal Leave for Fathers is so Important for Working Families|last=United States Department of Labor}}</ref> In 2015, a larger proportion of working fathers than mothers who requested leave received paid leave.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zagorsky|first=Jay L.|date=March 2017|title=Divergent Trends in US Maternity and Paternity Leave, 1994\u20132015|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=107|issue=3|pages=460\u2013465|doi=10.2105/ajph.2016.303607|pmid=28103064|pmc=5296693|issn=0090-0036}}</ref>\n\nThe United States military branches also show a minimal paternity leave. Although some branches give more time after the birth to take the leave, all branches give ten days. This type of leave is applicable to those who are married.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.militaryspot.com/resources/paternity-leave-in-the-military|title=Paternity Leave in the Military - MilitarySpot.com|date=February 7, 2011 |work=MilitarySpot.com|access-date=March 17, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nLonger paternity leave increases the father's engagement with a child, which leads to the child's improved cognitive and mental health outcomes and fewer behavior problems.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Foreign comparison==\n{{see also|Parental leave#Variation in international law}} \n<!--{{Out of date|[[Parental leave]]: \"52 weeks. 18 to be taken by the mother, 2 weeks by the father, the rest as they see fit.\" (in 2014). Assume all of the time is paid (not 100%), at least Iceland has at least 12 months paid and length there is shorter and assume paid time is also not worse in Denmark.}}-->\nThe United States is the only industrialized nation that does not offer paid [[parental leave]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eichner |first1=Maxine |title=Families, human dignity, and state support for caretaking: Why the United States' failure to ameliorate the work-family conflict is a dereliction of the government's basic responsibilities |journal=North Carolina Law Review |date= 1 June 2010 |volume=88 |pages=1593\u20131626 |url=https://scholarship.law.unc.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=4439&context=nclr}}</ref> Of countries in the United Nations only the\u00a0United States,\u00a0Suriname,\u00a0Papua New Guinea, and a few island countries in the\u00a0Pacific Ocean do not require employers to provide paid time off for new parents.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hurt |first1=Alyson |title=Countries Around The World Beat The U.S. On Paid Parental Leave |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/10/06/495839588/countries-around-the-world-beat-the-u-s-on-paid-parental-leave |website=NPR |accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> A study of 168 countries found that 163 guarantee paid leave to women, and 45 guarantee paid paternity leave.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grant |first1=Jodi |last2=Hatcher |first2=Taylor |last3=Patel |first3=Nirali |title=Expecting Better: A State-by-State Analysis of Parental Leave Programs |url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/App/NELIS/REL/79th2017/ExhibitDocument/OpenExhibitDocument?exhibitId=29512&fileDownloadName=0330ab266_ParentalLeaveReportMay05.pdf |publisher=National Partnership for Women & Families}}</ref>\n\nThe United States maternity leave policy is distinct for its relative scarcity of benefits in comparison to other industrialized countries. Thus, the legislation imposes relatively few restrictions on American firms and instead underscores employer discretion in the shaping of maternity leave policy. These firms are thus free to offer maternity leave policies on terms that are more aligned with\u00a0[[corporatocracy|corporate interests]].<ref name=\"grs\" /> \u00a0This United States policy differs greatly from most other western countries in terms of maternity leave provision. These stark maternity leave differentials are demonstrated in both the policy's length and compensation. In terms of the length of protected maternity leave, the United States currently ranks 20th out of the 21 highest-income countries.<ref name=\"grs\" />\u00a0The United States is one of three countries, along with\u00a0[[Oman]]\u00a0and\u00a0[[Papua New Guinea]], that does not offer paid maternity leave. Countries that offer paid maternity leave include [[Mexico]] (12 weeks), [[United Kingdom]] (40 weeks), [[India]] (26 weeks), [[Chile]] (24 weeks), [[Canada]] (up to 18 months), and [[China]] (14 weeks). Although the United States does not guarantee paid maternity leave, employers may provide paid leave if they choose. There are four states in the United States that do provide paid maternity leave and they are California, Georgia, New Jersey, and Rhode Island.<ref name=\"Adam Peck & Bryce Covert\">{{cite web|last1=Peck|first1=Adam|last2=Covert|first2=Bryce|title=U.S. Paid Family Leave Versus The Rest Of The World, In Two Disturbing Charts|url=http://thinkprogress.org/economy/2014/07/30/3465922/paid-family-leave/|website=THINKPROGRESS|publisher=CENTER FOR AMERICAN PROGRESS ACTION FUND|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn the United States like other nations, child care is not always equally shared between mothers and fathers. In the United States, fathers can have some paid leaves if they live in California or other states with similar legislation  (partial paid leave). In contrast, Slovenian fathers have 12 weeks of 100% paid paternity leave. In [[Sweden]], 480 days of 80% paid paternity leave weeks. In [[Norway]], 49 weeks of 100% paid paternity leave weeks or 59 weeks of 80% paid paternity leave. Finnish fathers have 11 partial paid leave weeks.<ref name=\"ilo.org\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forsakringskassan.se/arbetsgivare/foralder/!ut/p/a1/hc-xDoIwEAbgZ2Fg7R0YTHGDRESjk4PYxZRYClopaSu8vpC4mCjedsn3578DBgWwlveN5K7RLVfTzpYXGuIhTYME6REpbuM8XmdxuMlpNILzCPDHJPgvfwI2R4IsfIOZih2w6k64KYWzsum5EaTShqurMNN9SVsuqARmRCWMMORpxr9q5zq78tHHYRiI1FoqQazw8Vui1tZB8QGhexR4i1S_TzzvBa-U_cY!/dl5/d5/L0lDUmlTUSEhL3dHa0FKRnNBLzRKVXBDQSEhL2Vu/?keepNavState=true |title=Individuals - F\u00f6rs\u00e4kringskassan |publisher=Forsakringskassan.se |date= |accessdate=2017-06-09}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Parental leave]]\n* [[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993]]\n* [[Paid family leave]]\n* [[Motherhood penalty]]\n* [[Working mothers]]\n* [[Work-life balance]]\n* [[Maternity]]\n*[[US labor law]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Women in the United States]]\n[[Category:Maternity in the United States]]\n[[Category:Parental leave in the United States]]\n[[Category:Family law]]\n[[Category:United States labor law]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Regulated by US labor law}}\n'''Maternity leave in the United States''' is regulated by [[US labor law]]. The [[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993]] (FMLA) requires 12 weeks of unpaid leave annually for mothers of newborn or newly adopted children if they work for a company with 50 or more employees. Additionally, several states have adopted laws extending the requirements of FMLA to smaller companies.  For the majority of US workers at companies with fewer than 50 employees, there is no legal right to paid or unpaid leave to care for a new child or recover from childbirth.  Studies show the current laws disproportionately impact women [[Person of color|of color]] and low-income women, who are less likely to take unpaid leave.<ref name=\"expecting\" />\n\nThis is below the 16-week minimum recommended by the [[World Health Organization]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vahratian|first=Anjel|last2=Johnson|first2=Timothy R.B.|date=September 2009|title=Maternity Leave Benefits in the United States: Today's Economic Climate Underlines Deficiencies|journal=Birth|volume=36|issue=3|pages=177\u2013179|doi=10.1111/j.1523-536x.2009.00330.x|pmid=19747263|pmc=4262924|issn=0730-7659}}</ref> The United States is one of the only countries in the world, and the only [[OECD|OECD member]], that has not passed laws requiring businesses and corporations to offer paid maternity leave to their employees.<ref>{{cite web|last=OECD|title=Parental Leave Systems|url=https://www.oecd.org/els/soc/PF2_1_Parental_leave_systems.pdf}}</ref> As of 2017, there had been no significant change in the proportion of women who received maternity leave in the past 20 years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zagorsky|first=Jay L.|date=March 2017|title=Divergent Trends in US Maternity and Paternity Leave, 1994\u20132015|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=107|issue=3|pages=460\u2013465|doi=10.2105/ajph.2016.303607|pmid=28103064|pmc=5296693|issn=0090-0036}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBetween 1961 and 1965, only 14% of mothers participated in the workforce within 6 months of their child's birth.<ref>{{cite journal|last=O'Connell|first=M. |author2=B. Downs |author3=K. Smith|title=Maternity Leave and Employment Patterns: 1961-1995|journal=Current Population Reports|year=2001|volume=70|issue=79|pages=1\u201321}}</ref> During the same time period, only 44% of mothers worked during their pregnancy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/en.html|title=Census.gov|last=Bureau|first=US Census|website=www.census.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the enactment of FMLA legislation in 1993, maternity leave coverage was governed by state law, collective bargaining agreements and employer policies.<ref name=\"bw\">{{cite journal|last=Berger|first=L.|author2=J. Waldfogel|title=Maternity Leave and the Employment of New Mothers in the United States|journal=Journal of Population Economics|year=2004|volume=17|issue=2|pages=331\u2013349|doi=10.1007/s00148-003-0159-9}}</ref> The first set of maternity leave related policies emerged after World War I when first wave feminists lobbied for a women's health bill that gave grants to states to provide healthcare for women and children.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/9780203874493|title=Women's Rights in the USA: Policy Debates and Gender Roles|last=McBride|first=Dorothy E.|date=2014-06-11|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780203874493|edition=4|language=en|doi=10.4324/9780203874493}}</ref> By 1969, five states had enacted Temporary [[Disability Insurance]] laws protecting employees from income loss in the occurrence of a temporary medical disability.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tanaka|first=S.|title=Parental Leave and Child Health Across OECD Countries|journal=The Economic Journal|year=2005|volume=115|issue=501|pages=7\u201328|doi=10.1111/j.0013-0133.2005.00970.x}}</ref> Under this legislation, new mothers were granted leaves corresponding to the benefits that other employees received for temporary illness or disability. Changes to the federal tax code in 1976 permitted working families with a dependent child to take a tax credit on child care costs. \u00a0In 1978, the Pregnancy and Discrimination Act (PDA) prohibited employers from treating a woman unfavorably because of pregnancy, childbirth, or a medical condition related to pregnancy or childbirth.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Patton|first=Dana|last2=Costich|first2=Julia F.|last3=Lidstr\u00f6mer|first3=Niklas|date=March 2017 |title=Paid Parental Leave Policies and Infant Mortality Rates in OECD Countries: Policy Implications for the United States |journal=World Medical & Health Policy|volume=9|issue=1|pages=6\u201323|doi=10.1002/wmh3.214 |doi-access=free |issn=1948-4682}}</ref> During a landmark case in 1987, California Federal Savings and Loan Association v. Guerra, upheld a California law requiring most employers to grant pregnant women 4 months of unpaid disability leave and the right to return to their same job.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gordon|first=Victoria|date=2013-06-10|title=Maternity Leave|doi=10.1201/b14999|isbn=9780429254413}}</ref> This state-level trend of maternity leave legislation continued into the 1970s and 1980s where multiple other states passed more explicit recognitions of new mothers' rights to a temporary leave of absence. Ultimately, 12 states and the District of Columbia had implemented measures requiring at least some private sector employers to offer maternity leave packages to its employees.<ref name=\"bw\" /> Even in the absence of this formal legislation, employees in other states often obtained maternity leave through [[collective bargaining]]. Employees frequently held enough bargaining power to influence employer policies and negotiate for the inclusion of maternity leave protection.\n\nDespite some localized employees' access to maternity leave, there was growing pressure for national maternity leave legislation in the early 1990s. Many new mothers continued to be excluded from such maternity leave provisions despite growing national demand. Women now enjoyed greater employment opportunities and changing gender norms that encouraged increased labor involvement. This increased [[female employment]] extended to mothers as well who now were now more likely to engage in the workforce even if they had a young child. The labor participation rate of mothers with children under the age of 1 rose from 31% in 1976 to 54% in 1992.<ref name=\"w\">{{cite journal|last=Waldfogel|first=J.|title=The Family Gap for Young Women in the United States and Britain: Can Maternity Leave Make a Difference?|journal=Journal of Labor Economics|year=1998|volume=16|issue=3|pages=505\u2013545|doi=10.1086/209897}}</ref> The contribution of women's earnings to her family income rose from 26.6% in 1970 to 36% in 2008.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Maternity leave : policy and practice|last=Gordon, Victoria (Associate professor)|isbn=9781466573581|location=Boca Raton|oclc=838447584|date = 2013-06-10}}</ref> In spite of a high labor force participation rate, only an estimated 40% of working women had access to explicit maternity leave protection. This inadequate national coverage provoked intense protest and growing national consensus on the value of maternity leave. Ultimately, the increased salience and galvanized national support prompted the 1993 enactment of the [[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993|Family and Medical Leave Act]] mandating maternity leave.\n\nAlthough the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 required employers to guarantee job-protected, unpaid leave up to 12 weeks after the birth or adoption of a new child, an estimated 41 percent of employees in the United States were not covered by the Family and Medical Leave Act in 2012.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jou|first=Judy|last2=Kozhimannil|first2=Katy B.|last3=Abraham|first3=Jean M.|last4=Blewett|first4=Lynn A.|last5=McGovern|first5=Patricia M.|date=February 2018 |title=Paid Maternity Leave in the United States: Associations with Maternal and Infant Health |journal=Maternal and Child Health Journal|language=en|volume=22|issue=2|pages=216\u2013225|doi=10.1007/s10995-017-2393-x|pmid=29098488|issn=1092-7875}}</ref> Nearly \u2154 of mothers had to work during their pregnancies between 2002-2008.<ref name=\":4\"/> By 2016, only 14% of US workers had access to paid family leave as an employee benefit. About two-thirds of employees (68 percent) had access to paid sick leave, and 38 percent had access to short-term disability benefits.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bartel|first=Ann P.|last2=Rossin-Slater|first2=Maya|last3=Ruhm|first3=Christopher J.|last4=Stearns|first4=Jenna|last5=Waldfogel|first5=Jane|date=2017-11-06|title=Paid Family Leave, Fathers' Leave-Taking, and Leave-Sharing in Dual-Earner Households|journal=Journal of Policy Analysis and Management|volume=37|issue=1|pages=10\u201337|doi=10.1002/pam.22030|pmid=29320808|issn=0276-8739|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w21747.pdf}}</ref> Prior to FMLA, the term \u201cfamily\u201d referred to a nuclear family where with two parents of opposite sex and the \u201cmother\u201d could bear a child. This was the only definition acknowledged by medical and economic research done before the LGBTQ rights movement. Only recently, studies have caught up to a modern and more inclusive definition family.\n\n==Current legislation==\n\nIn the U.S. parents and family are federally protected under The Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 (FMLA)<ref name=\"U.S. Department of Labor\">{{cite web |title=Wage and Hour Division (WHD): Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/ |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> to go on maternity or family leave after the adoption or birth of a child.<ref name=\"dol.gov\">{{cite web |title=Wage and Hour Division (WHD): Frequently Asked Questions |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/fmla-faqs.htm |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> Under this law, legal parents are protected for up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave (per year). The FMLA ensures the job security of parents/employees but does not protect employees who go on paid leave with their employers. Receiving the correct payment from being on leave is between the firm and the employee.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Employee's Guide to The Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/employeeguide.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> However, some states have laws that do protect and guarantee employees for paid family leave (see State Legislation section). Additionally, the FMLA defines \u201cparents\u201d as biological, adoptive, step or foster parent who stood in loco parentis or \u201cin the place of a parent\u201d. Parents do not include parent-in-laws though.<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Department of Labor Wage and Hour Division (July 2015) Fact Sheet #28J: The definition of \"parent\" as it applies to an individual who stood in loco parentis to an employee for FMLA \"eldercare\" protections. |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/regs/compliance/whdfs28c.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis paragraph is for employees who are seeking to get paid using their firm's extended policies on leaves. If you choose to go on maternity or family leave, The Employee's Guide to Family and Medical Leave Act,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Employee's Guide to The Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/employeeguide.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> states that you can sometimes use your unspent sick time, vacation time, personal time, etc., saved up with your employer at the same time of your FMLA leave so that you continue to get paid. Importantly though, in order to use such leave, \u201cyou must follow your employer\u2019s normal leave rules such as submitting a leave form or providing advance notice. Even if you don\u2019t want to use your paid leave, your employer can require you to use it during your FMLA leave\u201d.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Employee's Guide to The Family and Medical Leave Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/fmla/employeeguide.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIf you are choosing to use the FMLA to go on regular unpaid leave without any extended or paid leave, it's important to know the qualifications beforehand. The FMLA actually has several limiting stipulations and leaves out certain employee's conditions such as temp workers and trans employees, so only certain employees are eligible. In order to receive maternity leave protections under FMLA, employees must:<ref name=\"dol.gov\"/>\n\n*work for a covered employer;\n*have worked 1,250 hours during the 12 months prior to the start of leave; (special hours of service rules apply to airline flight crew members)<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Department of Labor Wage and Hour Division (July 2015) Fact Sheet #28J: The definition of \"parent\" as it applies to an individual who stood in loco parentis to an employee for FMLA \"eldercare\" protections. |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/regs/compliance/whdfs28c.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n*work at a location where the employer has 50 or more employees within 75 miles; and\n*have worked for the employer for 12 months.\n\nThe 12 months of employment are not required to be consecutive in order for the employee to qualify for FMLA leave. In general, only employment within seven years is counted unless the break in service is (1) due to an employee's fulfillment of military obligations, or (2) governed by a collective bargaining agreement or other written agreement.\n\nThe FMLA is the only law that federally protects American employees who go on maternity or family leave their resumed job security. It was signed into law during President Bill Clinton's first term in 1993 and revised on February 23, 2015 to include same-sex parents and spouses.<ref name=\"U.S. Department of Labor\"/> Two other Federal laws, the Pregnancy Discrimination Act<ref>{{cite web |title=The Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978 |url=https://www.eeoc.gov/laws/statutes/pregnancy.cfm |website=Equal Employment Opportunity Commission |publisher=U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> (PDA) and the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act's (PPACA, also known as the Affordable Care Act, the ACA or Obamacare)<ref name=\"EHealthInsurances Services\">{{cite web |title=Maternity Insurance Coverage under ObamaCare |url=https://www.ehealthinsurance.com/resources/affordable-care-act/maternity-insurance-coverage-obamacare |website=EHealthInsurances Services |publisher=EHealthInsurances Services |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> amendment of the Fair Labor Standards Act,<ref>{{cite web |title=Wage and Hour Division (WHD) Handy Reference Guide to the Fair Labor Standards Act |url=https://www.dol.gov/whd/regs/compliance/hrg.htm |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> provide some additional protection for parents on the birth of a child. For instance, the PDA upholds maternity leave by arguing that employees who give temporarily disabled folks a disability leave should give pregnant women maternity leave with the same protections and benefits. This PDA is essentially arguing that pregnant women should have rights to the same paid of unpaid leave that temporarily disabled workers are afforded by their employers. If an employer offers this protection to temporarily disabled workers then PDA says that pregnant women should also be protected using the same processes and same benefits. Additionally, in 2014 the PPACA amendment to the Fair Labor Standards Act made it so that all insurance companies had to include maternity coverage in individual insurance plans. Therefore, filling the gap for unemployed women with individual insurance coverage plans to be able to afford the prenatal and postnatal pregnancy care that they need to have a healthy baby. Maternity care came to include:<ref name=\"EHealthInsurances Services\"/>\n\n*Outpatient services, such as prenatal and postnatal doctor visits, gestational diabetes screenings, lab studies, medications, etc.\n*Inpatient services, such as hospitalization, physician fees, etc.\n*Newborn baby care\n*Lactation counseling and breast-pump rental\n \nThese federal laws and amendments have increased accessibility and quality of care for prenatal and postnatal mothers and families. For example, before the Affordable Care Act, only 12% of insurance plans sold in the individual market included maternity coverage.<ref name=\"EHealthInsurances Services\"/> Also, according to a journal study on FMLA by researchers at the University of Maryland,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dagher |first=Rada K |display-authors=etal |title=Maternity Leave Duration and Postpartum Mental and Physical Health: Implications for Leave Policies |journal=Journal of Health Politics, Policy and Law |date=December 2013 |volume=39 |issue=2 |pages=369\u2013416 |doi=10.1215/03616878-2416247 |pmid=24305845 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/259201718}}</ref> it was found that mothers who benefitted from FMLA were returned to the same job and sooner than before FMLA thus showing the impact of job stability for mothers. Nonetheless, many employees are still ineligible for the FMLA. According to the Family and Medical Leave Report in 2012, only 59% of American employees were eligible under the FMLA.<ref>{{cite web |title=Family and Medical Leave in 2012: Technical Report |url=https://www.dol.gov/asp/evaluation/fmla/fmla-2012-technical-report.pdf |website=Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, employees who returned after FMLA, women exclusively, were given lower wages than the ones to when they left. This comes from the same study by researchers at the University of Maryland, as aforementioned. It should be said that these lower wages may have not been permanent since the study only went to highlight women's experience with maternity leave two years after they leave.\n \nIn recent polls from 2017, Democrats and Republicans both are in high support of federal funding for paid maternity and family leave. According to a study done by the Brookings Institution,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mathur |first=Aparna \n |display-authors=etal |title=Paid Family and Medical Leave: An Issue Whose Time Has Come |url=http://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/es_20170606_paidfamilyleave.pdf |website=Brookings |publisher=AEI-Brookings Working Group on Paid Family Leave |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> a non-profit think tank in D.C., 71% of Republicans and 83% of Democrats support for a paid leave policy. Although the study did not reach a particular compromise on how the policies should work, who should pay for it, how much, and other concerns that might factor into creating a universal paid parental leave policy, they did reach a conclusion. Amongst the diverse group of researchers with different political and economic views, everyone believed that it is worthwhile to consider a federal paid leave policy. One important reason for this is because \u201cThe US is the only advanced country that provides no public support to new parents\u201d. \n \nThe U.S. does not presently have a federal paid maternity and family leave act. Some states, however, do include paid leave legislation for family members. States like California, New Jersey, and New York have pioneered paid leave legislature in their respective states. Reasons for paid leave might include higher job security for women and to reduce women's need for public assistance. A study by the Institute for Women's Research<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gult |first1=Barbara |title=Paid Parental Leave in the United States |url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/our-work/workplace/expecting-better-a.html |website=National Partnership |publisher=National Partnership for Women & Families |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> has also shown that paid leave could reduce employer costs and lead to U.S. economic growth. Also, paid family leave has been shown to increase the health of the family by lowering infant mortality rates.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Sandra L. |last=Hofferth |first2=Sally C. |last2=Curtin |title=Parental Leave Statutes and Maternal Return to Work After Childbirth in the United States |journal=Work and Occupations|volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=73\u2013105 |date=February 1, 2006 |doi=10.1177/0730888405281889}}</ref> Paid family leave would also allow low-income families the ability to take care of their family members without having to sacrifice time and money. Reasons for not having a protected paid family leave policy in place might be justified by the fact that there are limited economic resources to sustain a program.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leef |first1=George |title=Is Federal Paid Family Leave A Good Idea? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/georgeleef/2018/02/02/is-federal-paid-family-leave-a-good-idea/#71f1d98f795f |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, some may disagree with the overreach of the government taking on the responsibility to keep families afloat while on leave. Compared to some other countries, the U.S. remains behind in terms of maternity leave legislature.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Joya |first1=Misra |title=The US is stingier with child care and maternity leave than the rest of the world |url=https://theconversation.com/the-us-is-stingier-with-child-care-and-maternity-leave-than-the-rest-of-the-world-94770 |website=The Conversation |publisher=The Conversation: Academic Rigor, Journalistic Flair |accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===State legislation===\nMany states have supplemented these federal regulations and provided more extensive maternity leave benefits, including expanding paid or flexible sick time, expanding access for workers in smaller companies or with less time on the job, right to pump that expands on federal law, and pregnancy accommodations.<ref name=\"expecting\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/research-library/work-family/expecting-better-2016.pdf|title=Expecting Better: A state-by-state analysis of laws that help expecting and new parents (4th edition)|last=National Partnership for Women and Families|date=August 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, 12 states have enacted no additional laws or programs to support family leave before or after birth.<ref name=\"expecting\"/> Fourteen states, along with the District of Columbia, have addressed eligibility requirements by lowering the firm-size threshold from 50 or more employees down to as low as 10 employees. Seven other states, in addition to the District of Columbia, have adopted more generous maternity leave lengths that allow longer absences for the purpose of child rearing. Moreover, some states have enacted legislation enhancing the benefits of leave programs.\n\nCalifornia, New Jersey, and Rhode Island for instance, operate programs that require private-sector employers to pay their employees who utilize maternity leave at partial replacement rates.<ref name=\"grs\">{{cite web|last=Gornick|first=Janet|title=Parental Leave in 21 Countries: Assessing Generosity and Gender Equality |url=http://cepr.net/publications/reports/plp |publisher=Center for Economic and Policy Research |first2=Rebecca |last2=Ray |first3=John |last3=Schmitt |year=2008}}</ref> New York passed paid family leave legislation, which includes maternity leave, in 2016 \u2014 starting off at 8 weeks and 50% of pay in 2018, and reaching 12 weeks and 67% of pay in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://singlemotherguide.com/grants-for-single-mothers/#FMLA |title=Paid Family Leave \u2015 Grants for Single Moms |publisher=Single Mother Guide|access-date=September 14, 2017|date=2011-03-12 }}</ref>\n\nHawaii, Puerto Rico, and the District of Columbia designate childbirth as a temporary disability thus guaranteeing mothers paid maternity leave through [[Disability Insurance]] (TDI) provisions.<ref name=\"eb\">{{cite web|title=Expecting Better: A State-by-State Analysis of Laws that Help New Parents |url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/issues/work-family/expecting-better-a.html |publisher=National Partnership for Women and Families|accessdate=8 April 2013|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nOn Dec. 31, 2019, New Mexico Governor Michelle Lujan Grisham signed an executive order installing paid family leave for state employees, the first such policy in the state. The order, providing 12 weeks of paid family leave for state employees under the Governor's direct purview, became effective January 1, 2020.[https://www.governor.state.nm.us/2019/12/31/governor-orders-12-week-paid-parental-leave-for-state-employees/]\n\n=== Other federal policies ===\nThe Department of Defense has regulated the amount of maternity leave a military member can take. Before February 5, 2016 the leave was six weeks long for active duty members or reservists who had previously done twelve months of active duty time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.airforcetimes.com/story/military/2016/02/09/air-forces-new-12-week-maternity-leave-began-feb-5/80059404/|title=air-forces-new-12-week-maternity-leave-began-feb-5|last=Times|first=Air Force|website=Air Force Times|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> On January 28, 2016, the Defense Secretary, Ashton Carter, increased the paid maternity leave to twelve weeks for all branches.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/645958/carter-announces-12-weeks-paid-military-maternity-leave-other-benefits|title=Carter Announces 12 Weeks Paid Military Maternity Leave, Other Benefit|work=U.S. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref> Traditional reservists, however, are given an eighty-four-day excusal, not leave.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/e2/c/downloads/425869.pdf|title=Army Directive 2016-09 (Maternity Leave Policy)}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States Air Force AFI36-3003, it states that the maternity leave starts after being released from the hospital from giving birth, as also defined for other branches. \"Shared benefits\" can be created if both parents are active Air Force members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://static.e-publishing.af.mil/production/1/af_a1/publication/afi36-3003/afi36-3003.pdf|title=AIR FORCE INSTRUCTION 36-3003|last=Deborah|first=Lee}}</ref> Therefore, a sum of up to twelve weeks can be taken by one parent or distributed amongst the two parents. However, two married active duty members cannot create \"shared benefits\" in the Army, according to the Army Directive 2016-09 (Maternity Leave Policy).<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThere was a stance by the previous Secretary of the Navy, Ray Mabus, to increase the maternity leave from six to eighteen weeks for the Navy and Marine Corps beginning on July 2, 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=87987|title=SECNAV Announces New Maternity Leave Policy|last=Information|first=This story was written by the Office of the Chief of|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref> It was implemented until January 28, 2016, however, it remained eighteen weeks for those who were pregnant previous to and on March 3, 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=93290|title=Navy Updates Maternity Leave Policy|last=Affairs|first=This story was written by Chief of Naval Personnel Public|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIt was a significant leap to go from six to twelve weeks of maternity leave. Other benefits have also been increased to improve the lives of those with newborn or newly adopted children. These benefits include an increase of child care hours to fourteen hours a day, and allowing active duty members more ability to family plan by paying for the sperm and egg freezing.<ref name=\":0\" /> These decisions were made by the previous Defense Secretary \"in an effort to support military families, improve retention and strengthen the force of the future.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn December 20, 2019, as part of the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020 | National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) for Fiscal Year 2020]]<ref>{{USBill|116|S.|1790}}; NDAA 2020, [https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/senate-bill/1790 Pub.L. 116-92], {{USPL|116|92}}</ref>, the Federal Employee Paid Leave Act (FEPLA) amended the  [[Family_and_Medical_Leave_Act_of_1993 | Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA)]]  to grant federal government employees up to 12 weeks of paid time off for the birth, adoption or foster of a new child<ref>[https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title5-section6382&num=0&edition=prelim 5 USC \u00a7\u202f6382(d)(2)]</ref> The law applies to births or placements occurring on or after October 1, 2020.<ref>[https://www.chcoc.gov/content/paid-parental-leave-federal-employees Office of Personnel Management, MEMORANDUM FOR: HEADS OF EXECUTIVE DEPARTMENTS AND AGENCIES on December 27, 2019]</ref>\n\n==Impacts of United States maternity leave==\n\n===Health===\n\n====Child health and development====\n\nLonger maternity leave (up to 25 weeks) is associated with a reduction in post-neonatal and child mortality.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Staehelin|first=Katharina|last2=Bertea|first2=Paola Coda|last3=Stutz|first3=Elisabeth Zemp|date= August 2007|title=Length of maternity leave and health of mother and child \u2013 a review|journal=International Journal of Public Health|volume=52|issue=4|pages=202\u2013209|doi=10.1007/s00038-007-5122-1|issn=1661-8556|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/311716/files/38_2007_Article_5122.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Jou|first=Judy|last2=Kozhimannil|first2=Katy B.|last3=Abraham|first3=Jean M.|last4=Blewett|first4=Lynn A.|last5=McGovern|first5=Patricia M.|date=2017-11-02|title=Paid Maternity Leave in the United States: Associations with Maternal and Infant Health|journal=Maternal and Child Health Journal|volume=22|issue=2|pages=216\u2013225|doi=10.1007/s10995-017-2393-x|pmid=29098488|issn=1092-7875}}</ref> A 2017 study found that there was almost a 50% reduction in the probability of infant rehospitalization when women took maternity leave that was partially and fully paid.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to data from the 2006\u20132010 U.S. National Survey of Family Growth, paid maternity leave of 3 or more months for employed mothers is associated with a higher chance of the mother starting breastfeeding and breastfeeding her child at six months.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Mirkovic|first=Kelsey R.|last2=Perrine|first2=Cria G.|last3=Scanlon|first3=Kelley S.|date=2016|title=Paid Maternity Leave and Breastfeeding Outcomes|journal=Birth|language=en|volume=43|issue=3|pages=233\u2013239|doi=10.1111/birt.12230|pmid=26991788|issn=1523-536X}}</ref> The American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) currently recommends six months of breastfeeding exclusively, and continued breastfeeding as foods are introduced for one year for its medical and neurodevelopmental benefits for the child.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Breastfeeding|first=Section On|date=2012-03-01|title=Breastfeeding and the Use of Human Milk|url=https://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/129/3/e827|journal=Pediatrics|language=en|volume=129|issue=3|pages=e827\u2013e841|doi=10.1542/peds.2011-3552|issn=0031-4005|pmid=22371471|doi-access=free}}</ref> Mothers who are not engaged in employment may be more able to participate in consistent breast-feeding, since maternal employment can interfere with breastfeeding.<ref name=\":5\" /> The Center for Disease Control and Prevention states asthma, obesity, Sudden infant death syndrome, type 2 diabetes, gastrointestinal infections, and certain infections are all less likely to occur in breastfed babies.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/breastfeeding/about-breastfeeding/why-it-matters.html|title=About Breastfeeding|last=CDC|date=2019-03-12|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/29/health/paid-leave-benefits-to-children-research/index.html|title=Paid leave benefits children and families, studies say |author1=Kelly Wallace |author2=Jen Christensen|work=CNN|access-date=2017-10-02}}</ref> Research suggests that breast-feeding has the ability to yield substantial child health improvements in disease prevention and immune system build-up.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Baker|first=M.|author2=K. Milligan|title=Maternal Employment, Breastfeeding and Health: Evidence from Maternity Leave Mandates|journal=Journal of Health Economics|year=2008|volume=27|issue=4|pages=871\u2013887|doi=10.1016/j.jhealeco.2008.02.006|pmid=18387682|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w13188.pdf}}</ref> Moreover, further evidence indicates that maternal care is especially crucial during the first couple of months following child birth, or the time in which American maternity leave is in effect.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ruhm|first=C.|title=Parental Employment and Child Cognitive Development|journal=Journal of Human Resources|year=2004|volume=39|issue=1|pages=155\u2013192|doi=10.2307/3559009|jstor=3559009|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w7666.pdf}}</ref> Finally, evidence shows that paid maternity leave plans can increase paternal involvement in child care as shown by California's state paid maternity leave program.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://prospect.org/article/new-push-paid-family-leave|title=The New Push for Paid Family Leave|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=2013-12-12|work=The American Prospect|access-date=2019-05-13|language=en-US|issn=1049-7285}}</ref>\n\n====Maternal health====\nThe medical definition of [[postpartum]] is the time frame between childbirth and the return of the mother's reproductive organs to their non pregnant state.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGovern|first=Pat|last2=Dowd|first2=Bryan|last3=Gjerdingen|first3=Dwenda|last4=Gross|first4=Cynthia R.|last5=Kenney|first5=Sally|last6=Ukestad|first6=Laurie|last7=McCaffrey|first7=David|last8=Lundberg|first8=Ulf|date=March 2006|title=Postpartum Health of Employed Mothers 5 Weeks After Childbirth |journal=Annals of Family Medicine|volume=4|issue=2|pages=159\u2013167|doi=10.1370/afm.519|pmc=1467019|pmid=16569720}}</ref> For women that return to work during this postpartum period, the stress of maintaining a balance between their professional and parenting responsibilities has been shown to weaken their immune systems and interact poorly with their psychological state.<ref name=\"cm\">{{cite journal|last=Chatterji|first=P.|author2=S. Markowitz|title=Does the Length of Maternity Leave affect Maternal Health?|journal=National Bureau of Economic Research|year=2004}}</ref> Lower rates of breastfeeding may also have negative effects on the mother's health, as breastfeeding lowers the possibility of breast cancer, ovarian cancer, type 2 diabetes, and heart disease for the mother.<ref name=\":6\" /> Women of color and women classified as high economic hardship report postpartum symptoms more frequently and for a longer duration than women not in these categories. This trend is observed with both physical and mental health symptoms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tucker|first=Jenna N.|last2=Grzywacz|first2=Joseph G.|last3=Leng|first3=Iris|last4=Clinch|first4=C. Randall|last5=Arcury|first5=Thomas A.|date=2010-11-10|title=Return to Work, Economic Hardship, and Women's Postpartum Health|journal=Women & Health|volume=50|issue=7|pages=618\u2013638|doi=10.1080/03630242.2010.522468|pmid=21104566|issn=0363-0242}}</ref> Maternity leave over a longer time period is associated with an increase in the health of both the mother and the child. Paid leave with a duration of over 12 weeks is correlated with a decrease in the risk of infant and maternal re-hospitalization.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to a study on mothers of 6-month old infants using data from the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development, mothers who worked more hours experienced higher levels of depressive symptoms and stress due to parenting. They also viewed their personal health as worse when they worked more hours in the time period after childbirth.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chatterji|first=Pinka|last2=Markowitz|first2=Sara|last3=Brooks-Gunn|first3=Jeanne|date=2013-01-01|title=Effects of early maternal employment on maternal health and well-being|journal=Journal of Population Economics|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=285\u2013301|doi=10.1007/s00148-012-0437-5|issn=1432-1475|pmc=3640562|pmid=23645972}}</ref> Maternal-infant separation may cause significant parental stress, depression, and anxiety. Researchers propose paid leave relates to health as it allows women to recover from childbirth and take care of themselves, attend to their infant, visit the hospital for prenatal checkups, wellness, and illness, and manage finances.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weber|first=Ashley|last2=Harrison|first2=Tondi M.|last3=Steward|first3=Deborah|last4=Ludington-Hoe|first4=Susan|date=February 2018|title=Paid Family Leave to Enhance the Health Outcomes of Preterm Infants|journal=Policy, Politics, & Nursing Practice|language=en|volume=19|issue=1\u20132|pages=11\u201328|doi=10.1177/1527154418791821|pmid=30134774|pmc=6532630|issn=1527-1544}}</ref>\n\n====Postpartum depression==== \nAmong other factors, pregnancy can be a cause of depression in women. Symptoms of postpartum depression include a loss of interest in activities, difficulty focusing, thinking, making decisions, and remembering things, anxiety, irritation, slowed speaking, physical pains, and feelings of sadness and worthlessness.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.|url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/postpartum-depression/basics/definition/con-20029130|website=Mayo Clinic}}</ref> In industrial societies, postpartum depression is considered a major public health concern and affects about 15% of women. Postpartum depression also has negative developmental consequences for the child.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Apter-Levy|first=Yael|last2=Feldman|first2=Michal|last3=Vakart|first3=Adam|last4=Ebstein|first4=Richard P.|last5=Feldman|first5=Ruth|date=2013-10-01|title=Impact of Maternal Depression Across the First 6 Years of Life on the Child's Mental Health, Social Engagement, and Empathy: The Moderating Role of Oxytocin|journal=American Journal of Psychiatry|volume=170|issue=10|pages=1161\u20131168|doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.2013.12121597|pmid=23846912|issn=0002-953X|doi-access=free}}</ref> Research indicates 12 weeks may not be a long enough leave duration for those at risk of developing postpartum depression.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dowd|first=Bryan E.|last2=McGovern|first2=Patricia M.|last3=Dagher|first3=Rada K.|date=2014-04-01|title=Maternity Leave Duration and Postpartum Mental and Physical Health: Implications for Leave Policies|journal=Journal of Health Politics, Policy and Law|language=en|volume=39|issue=2|pages=369\u2013416|doi=10.1215/03616878-2416247|pmid=24305845|issn=0361-6878}}</ref> Fewer occurrences of depressive symptoms are correlated to longer maternity leave.<ref name=\"cm\" /> A study using data from the Early Childhood Longitudinal Study - Birth Cohort indicates there is a lower likelihood of women developing severe depression \u00a0and increased overall health if women take longer maternity leave from work.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Chatterji|first=Pinka|last2=Markowitz|first2=Sara|date=July 2008|title=Family Leave after Childbirth and the Health of New Mothers|location=Cambridge, MA|doi=10.3386/w14156|doi-access=free}}</ref> In addition, more depressive symptoms occurred in mothers postpartum when the spouse did not take any paternal leave.<ref name=\":7\" /> Poor physical health of the mother during the postpartum period is associated with more depressive symptoms, making postnatal health, in addition to employment, a prevalent factor when considering mental health in new mothers. Negative physical health symptoms frequently reported included tiredness, back pain, and back problems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woolhouse|first=Hannah|last2=Gartland|first2=Deirdre|last3=Perlen|first3=Susan|last4=Donath|first4=Susan|last5=Brown|first5=Stephanie J.|date=March 2014|title=Physical health after childbirth and maternal depression in the first 12 months post partum: Results of an Australian nulliparous pregnancy cohort study|journal=Midwifery|volume=30|issue=3|pages=378\u2013384|doi=10.1016/j.midw.2013.03.006|pmid=23619027|issn=0266-6138}}</ref>\n\n===Economic===\n\n====Economic efficiency====\nFour states currently offer paid family leave: California, Massachusetts, New Jersey, and Rhode Island.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/article/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-maternity-leave-in-the-us/|title=10 things you need to know about maternity leave in the US|work=TechRepublic|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref> In New Jersey, women who took paid leave in the year after giving birth were 40% less likely to receive public aid or food stamps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.rutgers.edu/news-release/rutgers-study-finds-paid-family-leave-leads-positive-economic-outcomes/20120119#.WuXi-zOZM0Q|title=Rutgers Study Finds Paid Family Leave Leads to Positive Economic Outcomes {{!}} Rutgers Today|website=news.rutgers.edu|access-date=2018-04-29|date=2012-01-19}}</ref> According to a California-based study, 87% of employers reported that the paid leave requirement did not increase costs; 9% note that it saved money due to decreased turnover and other costs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cepr.net/publications/reports/leaves-that-pay|title=Leaves That Pay: Employer and Worker Experiences With Paid Family Leave in California|last=Milkman|first=Eileen Appelbaum, Ruth|access-date=2018-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, $40 million is spent annually on the re-hospitalization of preterm infants. In addition, each maternal re-hospitalization adds an extra $1,600-3,000 to the cost of childbirth. Paid maternity leave is associated with increased maternal and neonatal health, so offering paid leave could decrease these costs.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThough the overall labor force participation has declined since the year 2000,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Plumer|first1=Brad|title=Three Reasons the US Labor Force Keeps Shrinking|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/09/06/the-incredible-shrinking-labor-force-again/|accessdate=4 June 2017|agency=Washington Post|date=6 September 2013}}</ref> some economists argue that paid maternity leave in California has increased labor force participation among mothers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Claire Cain|title=The Economic Benefits of Paid Parental Leave|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/01/upshot/the-economic-benefits-of-paid-parental-leave.html?_r=0|accessdate=4 June 2017|agency=The New York Times|date=30 January 2015}}</ref> Mothers who receive paid maternity leave may be more likely to return to employment later, and then work more hours and earn higher wages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/01/upshot/the-economic-benefits-of-paid-parental-leave.html|title=The Economic Benefits of Paid Parental Leave|last=Miller|first=Claire Cain|date=2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-02|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> There is some evidence that the state paid maternity leave program in California saves businesses from needing to provide their own leave plans and financially stabilizes workers.<ref name=\":8\"/>\n\nLess favorable maternity leave policies may inhibit a woman's career trajectory and [[promotion (rank)|promotion]] prospects. The extended period of absence of such policies often reduce a women's economic status and opportunities.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schwartz|first=F.|title=Management Women and the New Facts of Life|journal=Harvard Business Review|year=1989|volume=23|issue=1|pages=65\u201376}}</ref> During this hiatus, their job skills and experiences may deteriorate thus limiting their potential advancement.\n\n====Motherhood penalty====\n[[File:US Gender pay gap, by age.001.png|thumb|US - women's earnings as a percentage of men's in 2008 by age group]]\nAvailable maternity leave options may also help lower the impact of children on career advancement, or the [[motherhood penalty]]. There currently exists a \"family gap\" between the pay of mothers and nonmothers. In the United States prior to the passage of the FMLA, mothers typically earned 70% of men's wages while nonmothers earned 90%.<ref name=\"w\" /> These earning disparities partially stemmed from insecure employment return prospects. Women without maternity leave protection were often forced to start over with a new employer following their absence.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lazear|first=E.|title=Agency, Earnings Profiles, Productivity, and Hours Restrictions|journal=American Economic Review|year=1981|pages=606\u2013620}}</ref> This interrupted their career progression and burdened them with the additional task of seeking new employment. Such factors ultimately impeded equitable access to income and career opportunities. Women as a group notably experience increasing [[income inequality]] as they age illustrating the impact of motherhood on their wage prospects. However, the implementation of FMLA addressed some of these impediments through the introduction of mandatory maternity leave. Mothers now are more likely to return to their previous employer due to this increased legal protection.<ref name=\"ch\">{{cite journal|last=Curtin|first=S.|author2=S. Hofferth|title=Parental Leave Statutes and Maternal Return to Work After Childbirth in the United States|journal=Work and Occupations|year=2006|volume=33|issue=1|pages=73\u2013105|doi=10.1177/0730888405281889}}</ref> The policy minimizes some of the negative externalities of motherhood by maintaining women's employment options even following maternity leave. Many policy experts though suspect that the remaining gender imbalance is largely attributable to the dearth of paid leave options.<ref name=\"w\" /> Women who worked for companies that provided paid maternity leave before they gave birth are more likely to take such leave for up to 12 weeks, and more likely to return to work more quickly thereafter.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Berger|first1=Lawrence M.|last2=Waldfogel|first2=Jane|title=Maternity leave and the employment of new mothers in the United States|journal=Journal of Population Economics|date=1 June 2004|volume=17|issue=2|pages=331\u2013349|doi=10.1007/s00148-003-0159-9}}</ref>\n\n===Social===\n\n====Access equality====\nUnder the current FMLA system, approximately 40% of United States workers are ineligible for benefits due to the brevity of their tenure or the smallness of their firm.<ref name=\"grs\" /> These excluded populations are often low-waged and minority women thus furthering their already present disadvantage. In 2016, 38% of white working mothers qualified for and could afford to take unpaid leave under FMLA compared with 30% of African American women and 25% of Hispanic women.<ref name=\"expecting\" /> Moreover, the unpaid aspect of the current policy limits access to those who are economically well off. The United States Department of Labor reported that over a 22-month period in 1999 and 2000, 3.5 million people needed leave but were unable to take it due to affordability concerns.<ref>{{cite journal|last=United States Department of Labor|title=Balancing the Needs of Families and Employees: FMLA Survey Report|year=2000|url=http://www.dol.gov/dol/asp/public/fmla/main2000.htm|journal=|access-date=2013-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050322140511/http://www.dol.gov/dol/asp/public/fmla/main2000.htm|archive-date=2005-03-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In the private sector, it was found that 12% of workers received paid paternity leave with 23% of workers in the highest-wage quartile receiving paid maternity leave versus 5% of workers in the lowest-wage quartile.<ref name=\"expecting\" /> The lack of monetary compensation may hinder the ability of women who are not as financially secure as others to balance employment with their family life. Upper class women are more likely to take unpaid leave than lower class women. In addition, more white women take unpaid maternity leave than black or Hispanic women. This imbalance contributes to the discrepancies in infant mortality between groups.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Paternity leave==\n\nCalifornia is the first state to offer paid paternity leave weeks (six weeks, partial payment). New Jersey, Rhode Island,<ref name=\"babycenter.com\" /> and New York<ref name=\"paidfamilyleave.ny.gov\">{{cite web |date=July 2018 |url=https://paidfamilyleave.ny.gov/paid-family-leave-information-employees#eligibility |title=Paid Family leave: Information for employee |publisher=New York State |accessdate=July 22, 2018}}</ref> since passed laws for paid family leave. In the rest of the US, paternity pay weeks are not offered (therefore neither paternity paid leave weeks), but fathers have access to unpaid paternity leave to care for their newborns (without new income).<ref name=\"babycenter.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.babycenter.com/0_paternity-leave-what-are-the-options-for-dads_8258.bc |title=Paternity leave: What are the options for dads? |publisher=BabyCenter |date=November 2015 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ilo.org\">{{cite book|url=http://www.ilo.org/global/publications/ilo-bookstore/order-online/books/WCMS_242615/lang--en/index.htm |title=Maternity and paternity at work: Law and practice across the world |publisher=Ilo.org |date=May 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017|isbn=9789221286301 }}</ref> Often, fathers will take sick days or vacation time when they have newborns. There is also a growing number of fathers that go unpaid. Some employers are required by law to allow 12 weeks of unpaid family leave after the birth or adoption of a child. This law is under [[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993|FMLA]] or Family Medical Leave Act.<ref name=\"babycenter.com\"/> Fathers who have access to paid paternity leave give mothers the opportunity to engage in paid work, with a positive effect on female labor force participation and wages.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dol.gov/asp/policy-development/PaternityBrief.pdf|title=Paternity Leave: Why Paternal Leave for Fathers is so Important for Working Families|last=United States Department of Labor}}</ref> In 2015, a larger proportion of working fathers than mothers who requested leave received paid leave.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zagorsky|first=Jay L.|date=March 2017|title=Divergent Trends in US Maternity and Paternity Leave, 1994\u20132015|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=107|issue=3|pages=460\u2013465|doi=10.2105/ajph.2016.303607|pmid=28103064|pmc=5296693|issn=0090-0036}}</ref>\n\nThe United States military branches also show a minimal paternity leave. Although some branches give more time after the birth to take the leave, all branches give ten days. This type of leave is applicable to those who are married.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.militaryspot.com/resources/paternity-leave-in-the-military|title=Paternity Leave in the Military - MilitarySpot.com|date=February 7, 2011 |work=MilitarySpot.com|access-date=March 17, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nLonger paternity leave increases the father's engagement with a child, which leads to the child's improved cognitive and mental health outcomes and fewer behavior problems.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Foreign comparison==\n{{see also|Parental leave#Variation in international law}} \n<!--{{Out of date|[[Parental leave]]: \"52 weeks. 18 to be taken by the mother, 2 weeks by the father, the rest as they see fit.\" (in 2014). Assume all of the time is paid (not 100%), at least Iceland has at least 12 months paid and length there is shorter and assume paid time is also not worse in Denmark.}}-->\nThe United States is the only industrialized nation that does not offer paid [[parental leave]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Eichner |first1=Maxine |title=Families, human dignity, and state support for caretaking: Why the United States' failure to ameliorate the work-family conflict is a dereliction of the government's basic responsibilities |journal=North Carolina Law Review |date= 1 June 2010 |volume=88 |pages=1593\u20131626 |url=https://scholarship.law.unc.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=4439&context=nclr}}</ref> Of countries in the United Nations only the\u00a0United States,\u00a0Suriname,\u00a0Papua New Guinea, and a few island countries in the\u00a0Pacific Ocean do not require employers to provide paid time off for new parents.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hurt |first1=Alyson |title=Countries Around The World Beat The U.S. On Paid Parental Leave |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/10/06/495839588/countries-around-the-world-beat-the-u-s-on-paid-parental-leave |website=NPR |accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> A study of 168 countries found that 163 guarantee paid leave to women, and 45 guarantee paid paternity leave.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grant |first1=Jodi |last2=Hatcher |first2=Taylor |last3=Patel |first3=Nirali |title=Expecting Better: A State-by-State Analysis of Parental Leave Programs |url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/App/NELIS/REL/79th2017/ExhibitDocument/OpenExhibitDocument?exhibitId=29512&fileDownloadName=0330ab266_ParentalLeaveReportMay05.pdf |publisher=National Partnership for Women & Families}}</ref>\n\nThe United States maternity leave policy is distinct for its relative scarcity of benefits in comparison to other industrialized countries. Thus, the legislation imposes relatively few restrictions on American firms and instead underscores employer discretion in the shaping of maternity leave policy. These firms are thus free to offer maternity leave policies on terms that are more aligned with\u00a0[[corporatocracy|corporate interests]].<ref name=\"grs\" /> \u00a0This United States policy differs greatly from most other western countries in terms of maternity leave provision. These stark maternity leave differentials are demonstrated in both the policy's length and compensation. In terms of the length of protected maternity leave, the United States currently ranks 20th out of the 21 highest-income countries.<ref name=\"grs\" />\u00a0The United States is one of three countries, along with\u00a0[[Oman]]\u00a0and\u00a0[[Papua New Guinea]], that does not offer paid maternity leave. Countries that offer paid maternity leave include [[Mexico]] (12 weeks), [[United Kingdom]] (40 weeks), [[India]] (26 weeks), [[Chile]] (24 weeks), [[Canada]] (up to 18 months), and [[China]] (14 weeks). Although the United States does not guarantee paid maternity leave, employers may provide paid leave if they choose. There are four states in the United States that do provide paid maternity leave and they are California, Georgia, New Jersey, and Rhode Island.<ref name=\"Adam Peck & Bryce Covert\">{{cite web|last1=Peck|first1=Adam|last2=Covert|first2=Bryce|title=U.S. Paid Family Leave Versus The Rest Of The World, In Two Disturbing Charts|url=http://thinkprogress.org/economy/2014/07/30/3465922/paid-family-leave/|website=THINKPROGRESS|publisher=CENTER FOR AMERICAN PROGRESS ACTION FUND|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn the United States like other nations, child care is not always equally shared between mothers and fathers. In the United States, fathers can have some paid leaves if they live in California or other states with similar legislation  (partial paid leave). In contrast, Slovenian fathers have 12 weeks of 100% paid paternity leave. In [[Sweden]], 480 days of 80% paid paternity leave weeks. In [[Norway]], 49 weeks of 100% paid paternity leave weeks or 59 weeks of 80% paid paternity leave. Finnish fathers have 11 partial paid leave weeks.<ref name=\"ilo.org\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forsakringskassan.se/arbetsgivare/foralder/!ut/p/a1/hc-xDoIwEAbgZ2Fg7R0YTHGDRESjk4PYxZRYClopaSu8vpC4mCjedsn3578DBgWwlveN5K7RLVfTzpYXGuIhTYME6REpbuM8XmdxuMlpNILzCPDHJPgvfwI2R4IsfIOZih2w6k64KYWzsum5EaTShqurMNN9SVsuqARmRCWMMORpxr9q5zq78tHHYRiI1FoqQazw8Vui1tZB8QGhexR4i1S_TzzvBa-U_cY!/dl5/d5/L0lDUmlTUSEhL3dHa0FKRnNBLzRKVXBDQSEhL2Vu/?keepNavState=true |title=Individuals - F\u00f6rs\u00e4kringskassan |publisher=Forsakringskassan.se |date= |accessdate=2017-06-09}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Parental leave]]\n* [[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993]]\n* [[Paid family leave]]\n* [[Motherhood penalty]]\n* [[Working mothers]]\n* [[Work-life balance]]\n* [[Maternity]]\n*[[US labor law]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Women in the United States]]\n[[Category:Maternity in the United States]]\n[[Category:Parental leave in the United States]]\n[[Category:Family law]]\n[[Category:United States labor law]]\n", "name_user": "Aot007", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther federal policies:Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maternity_leave_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Second Hungarian Republic", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Hungarian Republic\n|native_name = ''Magyar K\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g''\n|common_name = Hungary\n|p1 = Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u201346){{!}}Kingdom of Hungary\n|flag_p1 = Flag of Hungary (1915-1918, 1919-1946).svg\n|s1 = Hungarian People's Republic\n|flag_s1 = Flag of Hungary (1949-1956; 1-2 aspect ratio).svg\n|image_flag = Flag of Hungary (1946-1949, 1956-1957; 1-2 aspect ratio).svg\n|image_coat = Coat of arms of Hungary (1946-1949, 1956-1957).svg\n|image_map = Ungheria (1945-1949).png |image_map_caption =\n|national_motto = \n|national_anthem = ''[[Himnusz]]''<br /><small>Hymn\n|capital = Budapest\n|government_type = [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[parliamentary republic]] (1946\u20131947){{-}}[[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[dominant-party]] [[parliamentary republic]] (1947\u20131949)\n|common_languages = [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n|religion = [[Christianity]] <br>[[Judaism]]\n|title_leader = [[List of heads of state of Hungary|President]]\n|leader1 = [[Zolt\u00e1n Tildy]]\n|year_leader1 = 1946&ndash;1948\n|leader2 = [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d Szakasits]]\n|year_leader2 = 1948&ndash;1949\n|title_deputy = [[List of Prime Ministers of Hungary|Prime Minister]]\n|deputy1 = [[Ferenc Nagy]]\n|year_deputy1 = 1946&ndash;1947\n|deputy2 = [[Lajos Dinny\u00e9s]]\n|year_deputy2 = 1947&ndash;1948\n|deputy3 = [[Istv\u00e1n Dobi]]\n|year_deputy3 = 1948&ndash;1949\n|legislature = [[National Assembly of Hungary|National Assembly]]\n|era = Cold War\n|event_start = Monarchy abolished \n|date_start = 1 February\n|year_start = 1946\n|event_end = [[Hungarian Constitution of 1949|People's Republic declared]]\n|date_end = 20 August\n|year_end = 1949\n|event1 = [[Paris Peace Treaties, 1947|Paris Peace Treaty]]\n|date_event1 = 10 February 1947\n|event2 = [[Salami tactics|Communist coup]]\n|date_event2 = 31 May 1947<ref>'' [http://www.rev.hu/history_of_45/ora2/ora2_e.htm Part 2: Communist take-over, 1946-1949]  The Institute for the History of the 1956 Revolution.  </ref>\n|stat_year1 = 1946\n|stat_pop1 = \n|ref_area1 = <ref name=revai>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=\u00c9leszt\u0151s, L\u00e1szl\u00f3 |encyclopedia=R\u00e9vai \u00faj lexikona |title=Magyarorsz\u00e1g hat\u00e1rai |trans-title=Borders of Hungary |language=Hungarian |year=2004 |publisher=Babits Kiad\u00f3 |volume=Volume 13 |location=Szeksz\u00e1rd |isbn=963-9556-13-0 |page=895}}</ref>\n|stat_area1 = 93073\n|stat_year2 = 1947\n|stat_pop2 = \n|stat_area2 = 93011\n|ref_area2 = <ref name=revai/>\n|stat_year3 = 1949\n|stat_pop3 = 9,204,799\n|stat_area3 = 93011\n|ref_area3 = <ref name=revai/>\n|ref_pop3 = <ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|title=Az 1990. \u00e9vi n\u00e9psz\u00e1ml\u00e1l\u00e1s el\u0151zetes adatai.|journal=Statisztikai Szemle|date=October 1990|volume=68|issue=10|url=http://www.ksh.hu/statszemle_archive/viewer.html?ev=1990&szam=10&old=8|page=750}}</ref>\n|currency = [[Hungarian peng\u0151|Peng\u0151]]{{\\}}[[Hungarian ad\u00f3peng\u0151|Ad\u00f3peng\u0151]]&nbsp;<sup>b</sup><br />[[Hungarian forint|Forint]]\n|footnote_a = Predominantly [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]].\n|footnote_b = Until 1 August 1946.\n|footnote_c = [[Bratislava bridgehead]] until 10 February 1947.\n|today = {{flagcountry|Hungary}}<br />{{flagcountry|Slovakia}}<sup>c</sup>\n}}\n\nThe '''Second Hungarian Republic''' ({{lang-hu|Magyar K\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g}}) was a [[parliamentary republic]] briefly established after the disestablishment of the [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u20131946)|Kingdom of Hungary]] on 1 February 1946 and was itself dissolved on 20 August 1949. It was succeeded by the [[People's Republic of Hungary]].\n\n== History ==\n\nFrom September 1944 until April 1945, as [[End of World War II in Europe|World War II in Europe]] drew to a close, the [[Red Army]] [[Soviet occupation of Hungary|occupied Hungary]]. The [[Siege of Budapest]] lasted almost two months and much of the city was destroyed. Neither the [[Allies of World War II|Western Allies]] nor the [[Soviet Union]] supported any changes to Hungary's pre-1938 borders, so the [[Paris Peace Treaties, 1947|peace treaty signed by Hungary in 1947]] declared that \"The decisions of the [[First Vienna Award|Vienna Award]] of 2 November 1938 are declared null and void\".<ref>[http://www.law.fsu.edu/library/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS076.pdf Treaty of Peace with Hungary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041204184436/http://www.law.fsu.edu/library/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS076.pdf |date=2004-12-04 }}</ref> This meant that Hungary's borders were moved back to those that existed on 1 January 1938 and it lost the territories it had regained between 1938 and 1941. The Soviet Union also annexed [[Carpathian Ruthenia|Sub-Carpathia]], some of which had been part of Hungary before 1938. Between 1946 and 1948, half of [[Germans of Hungary|Hungary's ethnic German minority]] (around 250,000 people)<ref>Chad Bryant, Chad Carl Bryant, [https://books.google.com/books?id=NOCOVmwJFMMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Prague+in+Black:+Nazi+Rule+and+Czech+Nationalism&hl=en&sa=X&ei=o6aiUKvUO6mY0QWej4DADg&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Prague%20in%20Black%3A%20Nazi%20Rule%20and%20Czech%20Nationalism&f=false Prague in Black: Nazi Rule and Czech Nationalism], Harvard University Press, 2007, p. 209</ref> were deported to Germany and there was [[Hungarians in Slovakia#Population exchanges|a forced \"exchange of population\"]] between Hungary and [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rieber|first1=Alfred J.|title=Forced Migration in Central and Eastern Europe, 1939-1950|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135274894|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=7kSMAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=a+forced+%22exchange+of+population%22+between+Hungary+and+Czechoslovakia&source=bl&ots=nKby7cJILg&sig=z2i7CvsN_s_sUXMR8S9OehHs15A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjF1_XG1brWAhWH6YMKHQPXBLUQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=a%20forced%20%22exchange%20of%20population%22%20between%20Hungary%20and%20Czechoslovakia&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Soviets set up an alternative government in [[Debrecen]] on 21 December 1944 before capturing Budapest on 18 January 1945. [[Zolt\u00e1n Tildy]] became the provisional prime minister.\n[[File:Nagy Ferenc-MTI 1946.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Ferenc Nagy]]\nIn [[Hungarian parliamentary election, 1945|elections held in November 1945]], the [[Independent Smallholders' Party]] won 57% of the vote. The [[Hungarian Communist Party]], now under the leadership of [[M\u00e1ty\u00e1s R\u00e1kosi]] and [[Ern\u0151 Ger\u0151]], two survivors from the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]] of 1919, received support from only 17% of the population. The Soviet commander in Hungary, [[Marshal of the Soviet Union|Marshal]] [[Kliment Voroshilov]], refused to allow the Smallholders Party to form a government. Instead Voroshilov established a coalition government with the communists holding some of the key posts. Under Parliament, the leader of the Smallholders, Zolt\u00e1n Tildy, was named president and [[Ferenc Nagy]] prime minister in February 1946. M\u00e1ty\u00e1s R\u00e1kosi became deputy prime minister.\n\nDuring 1945 and 1946, the national currency, the [[Hungarian peng\u0151|peng\u0151]], was all but destroyed by the most ruinous [[hyperinflation]] in recorded history. The only way to restore sanity to the economy was a new currency, so the [[Hungarian forint|forint]] was reintroduced in 1946.\n\n[[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Rajk]] became [[Ministry of Interior (Hungary)|minister of the interior]] and in this post established the [[State Protection Authority|security police (\u00c1VO)]]. In February 1947 the police began arresting leaders of the Smallholders Party and the [[National Peasant Party (Hungary)|National Peasant Party]]. It also pressured both parties to expel those members who weren't willing to do the Communists' bidding as \"fascists.\" Several prominent figures in both parties escaped abroad. Later, R\u00e1kosi boasted that he had dealt with his partners in the government, one by one, [[Salami tactics|\"cutting them off like slices of salami.\"]]{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nBy 1947, the power of the other parties in the coalition had been reduced in favour of the Communists, and they became the largest single party in [[Hungarian parliamentary election, 1947|elections held that year]]. The Communists were the dominant partners in the coalition People's Independence Front government. Nagy was replaced as prime minister by the more pliable [[Lajos Dinny\u00e9s]].\n\nIn October 1947, R\u00e1kosi gave the leaders of the non-Communist parties an ultimatum: cooperate with a new, Communist-dominated coalition government or go into exile.<ref>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/hutoc.html Hungary: a country study].  [[Library of Congress]] Federal Research Division, December 1989.</ref> The [[Hungarian Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]] effectively ceased to exist as an independent organization, and Independent Smallholders' Party secretary [[B\u00e9la Kov\u00e1cs (politician, 1908)|B\u00e9la Kov\u00e1cs]] was arrested and sent to Siberia. Other opposition leaders such as [[Anna K\u00e9thly]], Ferenc Nagy and Istv\u00e1n Szab\u00f3 were imprisoned or sent into exile.\n{{History of Hungary}}\nThe Republic of Hungary effectively ended in June 1948, when the Social Democrats were forced to merge with the Communists to form the [[Hungarian Working People's Party]]. However, the few independent-minded Social Democrats still left in the party were pushed out in short order. For all intents and purposes, this left the MDP as the MKP under a new name. In August, Tildy was forced out as president in favour of Social Democrat-turned-Communist [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d Szakasits]]. That December, Dinny\u00e9s was replaced as leader of the Smallholders and prime minister by the openly pro-Communist [[Istv\u00e1n Dobi]]. At the [[Hungarian parliamentary election, 1949|1949 elections]], voters were presented with a single list from the Communist-controlled Independent People's Front, which carried 95 percent of the vote. By this time, [[fellow traveler]]s had taken over the other parties and turned them into loyal partners of the Communists.\n\nOn 18 August 1949, the Parliament passed [[Hungarian Constitution of 1949|Hungary's first written constitution]] (1949/XX.) \u2013 a near-carbon copy of the [[1936 Soviet Constitution|1936 constitution of the Soviet Union]]. The name of the country became the [[People's Republic of Hungary]], \"the country of the workers and peasants\" where \"every authority is held by the working people\". Socialism was declared as the main goal of the nation. A new coat of arms was adopted with Communist symbols, such as the [[red star]], a [[hammer and sickle|hammer]], and an ear of wheat.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[History of Hungary]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portalbar|Hungary}}\n\n{{Years in Hungary}}\n{{Hungary topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Republic of Hungary (1946-1949)}}\n[[Category:Modern history of Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:Former republics|Hungary, Second]]\n[[Category:Territorial evolution of Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:1940s in Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1946]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1949]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Hungary]]\n[[Category:1949 disestablishments in Hungary]]\n[[Category:1946 in Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:1947 in Hungary|.]]\n[[Category:1948 in Hungary|.]]\n[[Category:1949 in Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Hungarian Republic\n|native_name = ''Magyar K\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g''\n|common_name = Hungary\n|p1 = Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u201346){{!}}Kingdom of Hungary\n|flag_p1 = Flag of Hungary (1915-1918, 1919-1946).svg\n|s1 = Hungarian People's Republic\n|flag_s1 = Flag of Hungary (1949-1956; 1-2 aspect ratio).svg\n|image_flag = Flag of Hungary (1946-1949, 1956-1957; 1-2 aspect ratio).svg\n|image_coat = Coat of arms of Hungary (1946-1949, 1956-1957).svg\n|image_map = Ungheria (1945-1949).png |image_map_caption =\n|national_motto = \n|national_anthem = ''[[Himnusz]]''<br /><small>Hymn\n|capital = Budapest\n|government_type = [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[parliamentary republic]] (1946\u20131947){{-}}[[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[dominant-party]] [[parliamentary republic]] (1947\u20131949)\n|common_languages = [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n|religion = [[Christianity]] <br>[[Judaism]]\n|title_leader = [[List of heads of state of Hungary|President]]\n|leader1 = [[Zolt\u00e1n Tildy]]\n|year_leader1 = 1946&ndash;1948\n|leader2 = [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d Szakasits]]\n|year_leader2 = 1948&ndash;1949\n|title_deputy = [[List of Prime Ministers of Hungary|Prime Minister]]\n|deputy1 = [[Ferenc Nagy]]\n|year_deputy1 = 1946&ndash;1947\n|deputy2 = [[Lajos Dinny\u00e9s]]\n|year_deputy2 = 1947&ndash;1948\n|deputy3 = [[Istv\u00e1n Dobi]]\n|year_deputy3 = 1948&ndash;1949\n|legislature = [[National Assembly of Hungary|National Assembly]]\n|era = Cold War\n|event_start = Monarchy abolished \n|date_start = 1 February\n|year_start = 1946\n|event_end = [[Hungarian Constitution of 1949|People's Republic declared]]\n|date_end = 20 August\n|year_end = 1949\n|event1 = [[Paris Peace Treaties, 1947|Paris Peace Treaty]]\n|date_event1 = 10 February 1947\n|event2 = [[Salami tactics|Communist coup]]\n|date_event2 = 31 May 1947\n|stat_year1 = 1946\n|stat_pop1 = \n|ref_area1 = <ref name=revai>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=\u00c9leszt\u0151s, L\u00e1szl\u00f3 |encyclopedia=R\u00e9vai \u00faj lexikona |title=Magyarorsz\u00e1g hat\u00e1rai |trans-title=Borders of Hungary |language=Hungarian |year=2004 |publisher=Babits Kiad\u00f3 |volume=Volume 13 |location=Szeksz\u00e1rd |isbn=963-9556-13-0 |page=895}}</ref>\n|stat_area1 = 93073\n|stat_year2 = 1947\n|stat_pop2 = \n|stat_area2 = 93011\n|ref_area2 = <ref name=revai/>\n|stat_year3 = 1949\n|stat_pop3 = 9,204,799\n|stat_area3 = 93011\n|ref_area3 = <ref name=revai/>\n|ref_pop3 = <ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|title=Az 1990. \u00e9vi n\u00e9psz\u00e1ml\u00e1l\u00e1s el\u0151zetes adatai.|journal=Statisztikai Szemle|date=October 1990|volume=68|issue=10|url=http://www.ksh.hu/statszemle_archive/viewer.html?ev=1990&szam=10&old=8|page=750}}</ref>\n|currency = [[Hungarian peng\u0151|Peng\u0151]]{{\\}}[[Hungarian ad\u00f3peng\u0151|Ad\u00f3peng\u0151]]&nbsp;<sup>b</sup><br />[[Hungarian forint|Forint]]\n|footnote_a = Predominantly [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]].\n|footnote_b = Until 1 August 1946.\n|footnote_c = [[Bratislava bridgehead]] until 10 February 1947.\n|today = {{flagcountry|Hungary}}<br />{{flagcountry|Slovakia}}<sup>c</sup>\n}}\n\nThe '''Second Hungarian Republic''' ({{lang-hu|Magyar K\u00f6zt\u00e1rsas\u00e1g}}) was a [[parliamentary republic]] briefly established after the disestablishment of the [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u20131946)|Kingdom of Hungary]] on 1 February 1946 and was itself dissolved on 20 August 1949. It was succeeded by the [[People's Republic of Hungary]].\n\n== History ==\n\nFrom September 1944 until April 1945, as [[End of World War II in Europe|World War II in Europe]] drew to a close, the [[Red Army]] [[Soviet occupation of Hungary|occupied Hungary]]. The [[Siege of Budapest]] lasted almost two months and much of the city was destroyed. Neither the [[Allies of World War II|Western Allies]] nor the [[Soviet Union]] supported any changes to Hungary's pre-1938 borders, so the [[Paris Peace Treaties, 1947|peace treaty signed by Hungary in 1947]] declared that \"The decisions of the [[First Vienna Award|Vienna Award]] of 2 November 1938 are declared null and void\".<ref>[http://www.law.fsu.edu/library/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS076.pdf Treaty of Peace with Hungary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041204184436/http://www.law.fsu.edu/library/collection/LimitsinSeas/IBS076.pdf |date=2004-12-04 }}</ref> This meant that Hungary's borders were moved back to those that existed on 1 January 1938 and it lost the territories it had regained between 1938 and 1941. The Soviet Union also annexed [[Carpathian Ruthenia|Sub-Carpathia]], some of which had been part of Hungary before 1938. Between 1946 and 1948, half of [[Germans of Hungary|Hungary's ethnic German minority]] (around 250,000 people)<ref>Chad Bryant, Chad Carl Bryant, [https://books.google.com/books?id=NOCOVmwJFMMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Prague+in+Black:+Nazi+Rule+and+Czech+Nationalism&hl=en&sa=X&ei=o6aiUKvUO6mY0QWej4DADg&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Prague%20in%20Black%3A%20Nazi%20Rule%20and%20Czech%20Nationalism&f=false Prague in Black: Nazi Rule and Czech Nationalism], Harvard University Press, 2007, p. 209</ref> were deported to Germany and there was [[Hungarians in Slovakia#Population exchanges|a forced \"exchange of population\"]] between Hungary and [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rieber|first1=Alfred J.|title=Forced Migration in Central and Eastern Europe, 1939-1950|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135274894|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=7kSMAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=a+forced+%22exchange+of+population%22+between+Hungary+and+Czechoslovakia&source=bl&ots=nKby7cJILg&sig=z2i7CvsN_s_sUXMR8S9OehHs15A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjF1_XG1brWAhWH6YMKHQPXBLUQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=a%20forced%20%22exchange%20of%20population%22%20between%20Hungary%20and%20Czechoslovakia&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Soviets set up an alternative government in [[Debrecen]] on 21 December 1944 before capturing Budapest on 18 January 1945. [[Zolt\u00e1n Tildy]] became the provisional prime minister.\n[[File:Nagy Ferenc-MTI 1946.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Ferenc Nagy]]\nIn [[Hungarian parliamentary election, 1945|elections held in November 1945]], the [[Independent Smallholders' Party]] won 57% of the vote. The [[Hungarian Communist Party]], now under the leadership of [[M\u00e1ty\u00e1s R\u00e1kosi]] and [[Ern\u0151 Ger\u0151]], two survivors from the [[Hungarian Soviet Republic]] of 1919, received support from only 17% of the population. The Soviet commander in Hungary, [[Marshal of the Soviet Union|Marshal]] [[Kliment Voroshilov]], refused to allow the Smallholders Party to form a government. Instead Voroshilov established a coalition government with the communists holding some of the key posts. Under Parliament, the leader of the Smallholders, Zolt\u00e1n Tildy, was named president and [[Ferenc Nagy]] prime minister in February 1946. M\u00e1ty\u00e1s R\u00e1kosi became deputy prime minister.\n\nDuring 1945 and 1946, the national currency, the [[Hungarian peng\u0151|peng\u0151]], was all but destroyed by the most ruinous [[hyperinflation]] in recorded history. The only way to restore sanity to the economy was a new currency, so the [[Hungarian forint|forint]] was reintroduced in 1946.\n\n[[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Rajk]] became [[Ministry of Interior (Hungary)|minister of the interior]] and in this post established the [[State Protection Authority|security police (\u00c1VO)]]. In February 1947 the police began arresting leaders of the Smallholders Party and the [[National Peasant Party (Hungary)|National Peasant Party]]. It also pressured both parties to expel those members who weren't willing to do the Communists' bidding as \"fascists.\" Several prominent figures in both parties escaped abroad. Later, R\u00e1kosi boasted that he had dealt with his partners in the government, one by one, [[Salami tactics|\"cutting them off like slices of salami.\"]]{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nBy 1947, the power of the other parties in the coalition had been reduced in favour of the Communists, and they became the largest single party in [[Hungarian parliamentary election, 1947|elections held that year]]. The Communists were the dominant partners in the coalition People's Independence Front government. Nagy was replaced as prime minister by the more pliable [[Lajos Dinny\u00e9s]].\n\nIn October 1947, R\u00e1kosi gave the leaders of the non-Communist parties an ultimatum: cooperate with a new, Communist-dominated coalition government or go into exile.<ref>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/hutoc.html Hungary: a country study].  [[Library of Congress]] Federal Research Division, December 1989.</ref> The [[Hungarian Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]] effectively ceased to exist as an independent organization, and Independent Smallholders' Party secretary [[B\u00e9la Kov\u00e1cs (politician, 1908)|B\u00e9la Kov\u00e1cs]] was arrested and sent to Siberia. Other opposition leaders such as [[Anna K\u00e9thly]], Ferenc Nagy and Istv\u00e1n Szab\u00f3 were imprisoned or sent into exile.\n{{History of Hungary}}\nThe Republic of Hungary effectively ended in June 1948, when the Social Democrats were forced to merge with the Communists to form the [[Hungarian Working People's Party]]. However, the few independent-minded Social Democrats still left in the party were pushed out in short order. For all intents and purposes, this left the MDP as the MKP under a new name. In August, Tildy was forced out as president in favour of Social Democrat-turned-Communist [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d Szakasits]]. That December, Dinny\u00e9s was replaced as leader of the Smallholders and prime minister by the openly pro-Communist [[Istv\u00e1n Dobi]]. At the [[Hungarian parliamentary election, 1949|1949 elections]], voters were presented with a single list from the Communist-controlled Independent People's Front, which carried 95 percent of the vote. By this time, [[fellow traveler]]s had taken over the other parties and turned them into loyal partners of the Communists.\n\nOn 18 August 1949, the Parliament passed [[Hungarian Constitution of 1949|Hungary's first written constitution]] (1949/XX.) \u2013 a near-carbon copy of the [[1936 Soviet Constitution|1936 constitution of the Soviet Union]]. The name of the country became the [[People's Republic of Hungary]], \"the country of the workers and peasants\" where \"every authority is held by the working people\". Socialism was declared as the main goal of the nation. A new coat of arms was adopted with Communist symbols, such as the [[red star]], a [[hammer and sickle|hammer]], and an ear of wheat.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[History of Hungary]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portalbar|Hungary}}\n\n{{Years in Hungary}}\n{{Hungary topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Republic of Hungary (1946-1949)}}\n[[Category:Modern history of Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:Former republics|Hungary, Second]]\n[[Category:Territorial evolution of Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:1940s in Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1946]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1949]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Hungary]]\n[[Category:1949 disestablishments in Hungary]]\n[[Category:1946 in Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:1947 in Hungary|.]]\n[[Category:1948 in Hungary|.]]\n[[Category:1949 in Hungary|Second Hungarian Republic]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n", "name_user": "ImperatorPublius", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Hungarian_Republic"}
{"title_page": "Richmond High School (Richmond, California)", "text_new": "{{Cleanup school|date=October 2009}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name           = Richmond High School\n| image          = RHS Oilers Richmond CA logo.png\n| address        = 1250 - 23rd St.\n| city           = [[Richmond, California|Richmond]]\n| state          = [[California]]\n| zipcode        = 94804510\n| country        = [[United States]]\n| coordinates    = {{Coord|37.9518682|-122.3421929|display=inline,title|notes=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=gnispq:3:::NO::P3_FID:231554|title=GNIS Detail - Richmond High School|date=14 June 2000|work=Geographic Names Information System|publisher=United States Geological Survey|accessdate=8 April 2010}}</ref>}} \n| established    = 1907\n| type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n| district       = [[West Contra Costa Unified School District]]\n| grades         = 9-12\n| principal = Jose DeLeon; Vice Principals Rocio Reyes, Michael Hatcher, John Hillyer\n| faculty        = Elsa Torres, Luis Mazariegos, Veronica Vega, Zenaida Rivera-Camacho, Lola Verdin\n| enrollment     = 1,511 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0632550&SchoolPageNum=4&ID=063255005055|title=Richmond High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| ratio          = 22.29<ref name=NCES/>\n| teaching_staff = 67.80 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n| athletics      = Football, baseball, soccer, volleyball, badminton, basketball, tennis, swimming\n| athletics_conference     = [[California Interscholastic Federation|CIF]] [[North Coast Section]] - ACCAL\n| colors         = {{color box|red}} {{color box|blue}}\n| mascot         = Oiler\n| free_texrt    = \n| free_text      =\n| free_label2    =\n| free_text2     =\n| website        = [http://www.wccusd.net/site/Default.aspx?PageID=2485 Richmond High School]\n}}\n\n'''Richmond High School''' (RHS) is a [[public high school]] located on [[23rd Street (Richmond, California)|23rd Street]], in [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], [[California]], United States.  It is part of the [[West Contra Costa Unified School District]] (WCCUSD).\n\n==Student demographics==\nAccording to Richmond High's School Accountability Report Card (SARC),<ref name=sarc>{{cite web|title=Richmond High's School Accountability Report Card (SARC) for 2007-2008|url=http://www.wccusd.net/School%20Information/SARC/2007-2008/High%20School/090127_2007-08%20SARC_Richmond%20High%20School.pdf}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which is required to be published annually, the school has a predominantly Hispanic or Latino student base, accounting for 76.43% of its total enrollment.  The SARC report also cites that 75% of the student base is \"socioeconomically disadvantaged\", with 54% designated as \"English learners\".\n\n==Academics==\n\nBy multiple measures, Richmond High School's academic performance is extremely poor.\n\n{{cst_scores |eng=17|math=3|sci=12|hist=8|score_url=http://www.wccusd.net/School%20Information/SARC/2007-2008/High%20School/090127_2007-08%20SARC_Richmond%20High%20School.pdf}}\n\nAfrican-American and Latino students suck d!(k fared worse than the overall student body, with 0% of African-American students and 2% of Latino students achieving proficiency in mathematics.\n\nHowever, compared with other schools in the district with similar demographics, Richmond High School students are higher achievers. This is in part the result of the implementation of a system of Smaller Learning Communities, also called academies. Presently there are five separate academies: Multimedia, Law, Health, Engineering, and Creative & Performing Arts. Three of these academies are certified by the California Partnership Academies arm of the California Department of Education. Students choose an academy based on their interests and are provided with integrated curriculum project-based learning opportunities, career technical elective classes, teachers with a common preparation period, internships, and mentors. Academies handle all but the most serious discipline problems.\n\nRichmond High School competes in the [[FIRST Robotics Competition]] as Team 841, the \"Biomechs\".\n\n==Crime==\n{{Main article|2009 Richmond High School gang rape}}\nIn 2009 a student was raped on the school property, over a period of hours, by multiple individuals. The incident received national publicity.<ref name=\"kgo1028\">{{cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=news/local/east_bay&id=7086765|title=5 arrested in rape of girl in Richmond|last=Vega|first=Cecilia|date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=October 28, 2009|publisher=[[KGO-TV|KGO]]|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, a P.E teacher who worked at the school was arrested for inappropriate relationship with an underage student.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2019/08/28/richmond-high-teacher-arrested-inappropriate-relationship-student/|title=Richmond High Teacher Charged With Multiple Sex Crimes For Alleged Student Relationship|date=2019-08-28|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/ktvu-local-news/richmond-hs-teacher-arrested-for-inappropriate-relationship-with-student|title=Richmond HS teacher arrested for inappropriate relationship with student|last=FOX|website=KTVU|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Ken Carter]], former basketball coach at Richmond, subject of the [[2005 in film|2005 film]] ''[[Coach Carter]]''\n* [[Eli Holman]], professional basketball player\n* [[Jim Landis]], center fielder for the [[Chicago White Sox]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://napavalleyregister.com/sports/spending-time-with-a-local-legend/article_a8f1e5d6-101a-11e1-9e9b-001cc4c03286.html|title=Spending time with a local legend|last=WILCOX|first=ANDY|website=Napa Valley Register|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n* [[Louis A. Mackey]], linebacker for the [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[Andres Soto]], activist\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area|Schools}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161021073842/http://rhsnewswire.net/ Campus newspaper]\n* [http://www.wccusd.net/site/Default.aspx?PageID=2485 Richmond High School]\n\n{{Richmond, California}}\n{{Contra Costa County, California Schools}}\n[[Category:Education in Richmond, California]]\n[[Category:High schools in Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup school|date=October 2009}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name           = Richmond High School\n| image          = RHS Oilers Richmond CA logo.png\n| address        = 1250 - 23rd St.\n| city           = [[Richmond, California|Richmond]]\n| state          = [[California]]\n| zipcode        = 94804510\n| country        = [[United States]]\n| coordinates    = {{Coord|37.9518682|-122.3421929|display=inline,title|notes=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/pls/gnispublic/f?p=gnispq:3:::NO::P3_FID:231554|title=GNIS Detail - Richmond High School|date=14 June 2000|work=Geographic Names Information System|publisher=United States Geological Survey|accessdate=8 April 2010}}</ref>}} \n| established    = 1907\n| type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n| district       = [[West Contra Costa Unified School District]]\n| grades         = 9-12\n| principal = Jose DeLeon; Vice Principals Rocio Reyes, Michael Hatcher, John Hillyer\n| faculty        = Elsa Torres, Luis Mazariegos, Veronica Vega, Zenaida Rivera-Camacho, Lola Verdin\n| enrollment     = 1,511 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0632550&SchoolPageNum=4&ID=063255005055|title=Richmond High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| ratio          = 22.29<ref name=NCES/>\n| teaching_staff = 67.80 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n| athletics      = Football, baseball, soccer, volleyball, badminton, basketball, tennis, swimming\n| athletics_conference     = [[California Interscholastic Federation|CIF]] [[North Coast Section]] - ACCAL\n| colors         = {{color box|red}} {{color box|blue}}\n| mascot         = Oiler\n| free_texrt    = \n| free_text      =\n| free_label2    =\n| free_text2     =\n| website        = [http://www.wccusd.net/site/Default.aspx?PageID=2485 Richmond High School]\n}}\n\n'''Richmond High School''' (RHS) is a [[public high school]] located on [[23rd Street (Richmond, California)|23rd Street]], in [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], [[California]], United States.  It is part of the [[West Contra Costa Unified School District]] (WCCUSD).\n\n==Student demographics==\nAccording to Richmond High's School Accountability Report Card (SARC),<ref name=sarc>{{cite web|title=Richmond High's School Accountability Report Card (SARC) for 2007-2008|url=http://www.wccusd.net/School%20Information/SARC/2007-2008/High%20School/090127_2007-08%20SARC_Richmond%20High%20School.pdf}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which is required to be published annually, the school has a predominantly Hispanic or Latino student base, accounting for 76.43% of its total enrollment.  The SARC report also cites that 75% of the student base is \"socioeconomically disadvantaged\", with 54% designated as \"English learners\".\n\n==Academics==\n\nBy multiple measures, Richmond High School's academic performance is extremely poor.\n\n{{cst_scores |eng=17|math=3|sci=12|hist=8|score_url=http://www.wccusd.net/School%20Information/SARC/2007-2008/High%20School/090127_2007-08%20SARC_Richmond%20High%20School.pdf}}\n\nAfrican-American and Latino students fared worse than the overall student body, with 0% of African-American students and 2% of Latino students achieving proficiency in mathematics.\n\nHowever, compared with other schools in the district with similar demographics, Richmond High School students are higher achievers. This is in part the result of the implementation of a system of Smaller Learning Communities, also called academies. Presently there are five separate academies: Multimedia, Law, Health, Engineering, and Creative & Performing Arts. Three of these academies are certified by the California Partnership Academies arm of the California Department of Education. Students choose an academy based on their interests and are provided with integrated curriculum project-based learning opportunities, career technical elective classes, teachers with a common preparation period, internships, and mentors. Academies handle all but the most serious discipline problems.\n\nRichmond High School competes in the [[FIRST Robotics Competition]] as Team 841, the \"Biomechs\".\n\n==Crime==\n{{Main article|2009 Richmond High School gang rape}}\nIn 2009 a student was raped on the school property, over a period of hours, by multiple individuals. The incident received national publicity.<ref name=\"kgo1028\">{{cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=news/local/east_bay&id=7086765|title=5 arrested in rape of girl in Richmond|last=Vega|first=Cecilia|date=October 28, 2009|accessdate=October 28, 2009|publisher=[[KGO-TV|KGO]]|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, a P.E teacher who worked at the school was arrested for inappropriate relationship with an underage student.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2019/08/28/richmond-high-teacher-arrested-inappropriate-relationship-student/|title=Richmond High Teacher Charged With Multiple Sex Crimes For Alleged Student Relationship|date=2019-08-28|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/ktvu-local-news/richmond-hs-teacher-arrested-for-inappropriate-relationship-with-student|title=Richmond HS teacher arrested for inappropriate relationship with student|last=FOX|website=KTVU|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Ken Carter]], former basketball coach at Richmond, subject of the [[2005 in film|2005 film]] ''[[Coach Carter]]''\n* [[Eli Holman]], professional basketball player\n* [[Jim Landis]], center fielder for the [[Chicago White Sox]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://napavalleyregister.com/sports/spending-time-with-a-local-legend/article_a8f1e5d6-101a-11e1-9e9b-001cc4c03286.html|title=Spending time with a local legend|last=WILCOX|first=ANDY|website=Napa Valley Register|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n* [[Louis A. Mackey]], linebacker for the [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[Andres Soto]], activist\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area|Schools}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161021073842/http://rhsnewswire.net/ Campus newspaper]\n* [http://www.wccusd.net/site/Default.aspx?PageID=2485 Richmond High School]\n\n{{Richmond, California}}\n{{Contra Costa County, California Schools}}\n[[Category:Education in Richmond, California]]\n[[Category:High schools in Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in California]]\n", "name_user": "49.196.165.241", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAcademics)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richmond_High_School_(Richmond,_California)"}
